{"title_page": "Ancient Egyptian cattle", "text_new": "[[File:Nebamun-ViewingTheProduceOfTheEstates-3.JPG|thumb|Scene showing the presentation oan cattle to [[Nebamun]]]] \n'''Egyptian cattle''' were a domesticated form of [[cattle]] kept by the [[Ancient Egypt|Ancient Egyptian]]s. They are of uncertain origin.<ref>{{cite web|urlROBLOX IS BETTER AS WELL AS ADOPT ME\n</ref>\n\n==Sources and origins==\nThe earliest evidence for them is from the [http://www.ucl.ac.uk/museums-static/digitalegypt/maps/index.html Fayum]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ucl.ac.uk/museums-static/digitalegypt/maps/index.html |title=Map of Egypt |publisher=Ucl.ac.uk |date= |accessdate=2016-09-09}}</ref> region, dating back to the [[5th millennium BC]].<ref>http://www.ucl.ac.uk/museums-static/digitalegypt/foodproduction/cattle.html</ref> In the past the type was given its own species name, '''''Bos aegyptiacus''''', but it is now regarded as part of the same scientific [[taxon]] as other domestic cattle: either ''Bos taurus'' or ''Bos primigenius'' subspecies ''taurus''.\n\nAncient Egyptian cattle did not have a hump. They either had large widespread horns, which arched first inward and then outward, or shorter horns which had the same structure. According to Egyptian art, they were coloured either black, brown, brown and white, white spotted, black and white, or white.\n\nIt is uncertain as to where Egyptian cattle originated, as some{{Who|date=September 2010}} claim that they were acquired from the [[Levant]] or [[Mesopotamia]] while others{{Who|date=September 2010}} claim that it was domesticated independently from a [[North Africa]]n subspecies of the [[aurochs]], ''[[Bos primigenius mauretanicus]]''. There is evidence for both sides as cattle had been domesticated in the Levant by the 8th millennium BC.\n\n==Role in Egypt==\nThey were important to the Ancient Egyptians who put them out to pasture on land that couldn't be farmed on, either because it was too far from the [[Nile]] to [[irrigation|irrigate]] or in the [[Nile delta]] (and thus too wet to farm). The Egyptians used them for food, [[milk]], [[leather]], and [[sacrifice]].\n\nAncient Egyptian cattle came to be considered so important that many [[Egyptian Mythology|Egyptian gods]] were considered to have the form of cattle, notable deities being [[Hathor]], [[Ptah]] (as the [[Apis (deity)|Apis Bull]]), [[Montu]] (as the [[Buchis]] bull), and [[Ra|Atum-Ra]] (as the [[Mnevis]] bull). Many were [[mummy|mummified]].\n\nDuring the [[New Kingdom]] the [[Zebu]], hump-backed [[cattle]] from [[Syria]], were introduced to Egypt and the earlier form seems to have slowly been replaced by these new cattle.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ucl.ac.uk/museums-static/digitalegypt/foodproduction/cattle2.html |title=Cattle in Ancient Egypt |publisher=Ucl.ac.uk |date= |accessdate=2016-09-09}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Commons category|Bovines in ancient Egypt}}\n\n[[Category:Extinct cattle breeds]]\n[[Category:Ancient Egyptian society]]\n[[Category:Bovines]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Nebamun-ViewingTheProduceOfTheEstates-3.JPG|thumb|Scene showing the presentation of Egyptian cattle to [[Nebamun]]]] \n'''Egyptian cattle''' were a domesticated form of [[cattle]] kept by the [[Ancient Egypt|Ancient Egyptian]]s. They are of uncertain origin.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ucl.ac.uk/museums-static/digitalegypt/foodproduction/cattle.html |title=Cattle in Ancient Egypt |publisher=Ucl.ac.uk |date= |accessdate=2016-09-09}}</ref>\n\n==Sources and origins==\nThe earliest evidence for them is from the [http://www.ucl.ac.uk/museums-static/digitalegypt/maps/index.html Fayum]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ucl.ac.uk/museums-static/digitalegypt/maps/index.html |title=Map of Egypt |publisher=Ucl.ac.uk |date= |accessdate=2016-09-09}}</ref> region, dating back to the [[5th millennium BC]].<ref>http://www.ucl.ac.uk/museums-static/digitalegypt/foodproduction/cattle.html</ref> In the past the type was given its own species name, '''''Bos aegyptiacus''''', but it is now regarded as part of the same scientific [[taxon]] as other domestic cattle: either ''Bos taurus'' or ''Bos primigenius'' subspecies ''taurus''.\n\nAncient Egyptian cattle did not have a hump. They either had large widespread horns, which arched first inward and then outward, or shorter horns which had the same structure. According to Egyptian art, they were coloured either black, brown, brown and white, white spotted, black and white, or white.\n\nIt is uncertain as to where Egyptian cattle originated, as some{{Who|date=September 2010}} claim that they were acquired from the [[Levant]] or [[Mesopotamia]] while others{{Who|date=September 2010}} claim that it was domesticated independently from a [[North Africa]]n subspecies of the [[aurochs]], ''[[Bos primigenius mauretanicus]]''. There is evidence for both sides as cattle had been domesticated in the Levant by the 8th millennium BC.\n\n==Role in Egypt==\nThey were important to the Ancient Egyptians who put them out to pasture on land that couldn't be farmed on, either because it was too far from the [[Nile]] to [[irrigation|irrigate]] or in the [[Nile delta]] (and thus too wet to farm). The Egyptians used them for food, [[milk]], [[leather]], and [[sacrifice]].\n\nAncient Egyptian cattle came to be considered so important that many [[Egyptian Mythology|Egyptian gods]] were considered to have the form of cattle, notable deities being [[Hathor]], [[Ptah]] (as the [[Apis (deity)|Apis Bull]]), [[Montu]] (as the [[Buchis]] bull), and [[Ra|Atum-Ra]] (as the [[Mnevis]] bull). Many were [[mummy|mummified]].\n\nDuring the [[New Kingdom]] the [[Zebu]], hump-backed [[cattle]] from [[Syria]], were introduced to Egypt and the earlier form seems to have slowly been replaced by these new cattle.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ucl.ac.uk/museums-static/digitalegypt/foodproduction/cattle2.html |title=Cattle in Ancient Egypt |publisher=Ucl.ac.uk |date= |accessdate=2016-09-09}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Commons category|Bovines in ancient Egypt}}\n\n[[Category:Extinct cattle breeds]]\n[[Category:Ancient Egyptian society]]\n[[Category:Bovines]]\n", "name_user": "81.106.131.81", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ancient_Egyptian_cattle"}
{"title_page": "Cell-mediated immunity", "text_new": "'''Cell-mediated immunity''' is an immune response that does not involve antibodies. Rather, cell-mediated immunity is the activation of phagocytes, antigen-specific cytotoxic T-lymphocytes, and the release of various cytokines in response to antigen.\nHistorically, the immune system was separated into two branches: [[humoral immunity]], for which the protective function of immunization could be found in the humor (cell-free bodily fluid or [[blood plasma|serum]]) and '''cellular immunity''', for which the protective function of immunization was associated with cells. [[CD4]] cells or [[T helper cell|helper T cell]]s provide protection against different pathogens. [[Naive T cells]], which are mature T cells that have yet to encounter an [[antigen]], are converted into activated effector T cells after encountering [[antigen-presenting cells]] (APCs). These APCs, such as [[macrophages]], [[dendritic cells]], and [[B cells]] in some circumstances, load antigenic peptides onto the [[Major histocompatibility complex|MHC]] of the cell, in turn presenting the peptide to receptors on T cells. The most important of these APCs are highly specialized dendritic cells; conceivably operating solely to ingest and present antigens. <ref name=\"auto\">{{cite book|last1=Janeway|first1=Charles|last2=Travers|first2=Paul|last3=Walport|first3=Mark|last4=Shlomchik|first4=Mark|title=Immunobiology|date=2001|publisher=Garland Science|location=New York|isbn=978-0-8153-3642-6|edition=5th|url=https://archive.org/details/immunobiology00char|accessdate=24 January 2017}}</ref>\n\nActivated Effector T cells can be placed into three functioning classes, detecting [[peptide]] antigens originating from various types of [[pathogen]]: The first class being 1) [[Cytotoxic T cells]], which kill infected target cells by [[apoptosis]] without using cytokines, 2) [[TH1 cells]], which primarily function to activate macrophages, and 3) [[TH2 cells]], which primarily function to stimulate [[B cells]] into producing [[antibodies]].<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\nThe [[innate immune system]] and the [[adaptive immune system]] each comprise both [[humoral immunity|humoral]] and cell-mediated components.\n\nCellular immunity protects the body through:\n\n* T-cell mediated immunity or [[T-cell immunity]]: activating antigen-specific [[cytotoxic T cell]]s that are able to induce [[apoptosis]] in body cells displaying [[epitopes]] of foreign antigen on their surface, such as [[virus]]-infected cells, cells with intracellular bacteria, and cancer cells displaying [[tumor]] antigens;\n* [[Macrophage]] and [[natural killer cell]] action: enabling the destruction of pathogens via recognition and secretion of cytotoxic granules (for natural killer cells)<ref name=\"Eissmann\">{{cite web |last1=Eissmann |first1=Philipp |title=Natural Killer Cells |url=https://www.immunology.org/public-information/bitesized-immunology/cells/natural-killer-cells |website=British Society for Immunology |publisher=British Society for Immunology |accessdate=8 November 2018}}</ref> and phagocytosis (for macrophages)<ref name=\"Saldana\">{{cite web |last1=Saldana |first1=Jos\u00e9 |title=Macrophages |url=https://www.immunology.org/public-information/bitesized-immunology/cells/macrophages |website=British Society for Immunology |publisher=British Society for Immunology |accessdate=8 November 2018}}</ref>; and\n* Stimulating cells to secrete a variety of [[cytokine]]s that influence the function of other cells involved in adaptive immune responses and innate immune responses.<ref name=\"Eissmann\" /><ref name=\"Saldana\" />\n\nCell-mediated immunity is directed primarily at microbes that survive in [[phagocytes]] and [[microbes]] that infect non-phagocytic cells. It is most effective in removing virus-infected cells, but also participates in defending against [[fungi]], [[protozoan]]s, [[cancer]]s, and intracellular bacteria. It also plays a major role in [[transplant rejection]].\n\n==See also==\n* [[Immune system]]\n* [[Immunity (medical)|Immunity]]\n* [[Gay]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n* [http://www.britannica.com/science/cell-mediated-immunity Cell-mediated immunity] (Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica)\n* [https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK10762/ Chapter 8:T Cell-Mediated Immunity ] Immunobiology: The Immune System in Health and Disease. 5th edition.\n\n==Further reading==\n* [https://link.springer.com/chapter/10.1007/978-3-662-10373-9_3 Cell-Mediated Immunity. Murphy]\n* [http://missinglink.ucsf.edu/lm/immunology_module/prologue/objectives/obj07.html Cell-mediated immunity: How T cells recognize and respond to foreign antigens]\n\n{{Blood}}\n{{Immune_system}}\n{{Hypersensitivity and autoimmune diseases}}\n\n[[Category:Immunology]]\n", "text_old": "'''Cell-mediated immunity''' is an immune response that does not involve antibodies. Rather, cell-mediated immunity is the activation of phagocytes, antigen-specific cytotoxic T-lymphocytes, and the release of various cytokines in response to antigen.\nHistorically, the immune system was separated into two branches: [[humoral immunity]], for which the protective function of immunization could be found in the humor (cell-free bodily fluid or [[blood plasma|serum]]) and '''cellular immunity''', for which the protective function of immunization was associated with cells. [[CD4]] cells or [[T helper cell|helper T cell]]s provide protection against different pathogens. [[Naive T cells]], which are mature T cells that have yet to encounter an [[antigen]], are converted into activated effector T cells after encountering [[antigen-presenting cells]] (APCs). These APCs, such as [[macrophages]], [[dendritic cells]], and [[B cells]] in some circumstances, load antigenic peptides onto the [[Major histocompatibility complex|MHC]] of the cell, in turn presenting the peptide to receptors on T cells. The most important of these APCs are highly specialized dendritic cells; conceivably operating solely to ingest and present antigens. <ref name=\"auto\">{{cite book|last1=Janeway|first1=Charles|last2=Travers|first2=Paul|last3=Walport|first3=Mark|last4=Shlomchik|first4=Mark|title=Immunobiology|date=2001|publisher=Garland Science|location=New York|isbn=978-0-8153-3642-6|edition=5th|url=https://archive.org/details/immunobiology00char|accessdate=24 January 2017}}</ref>\n\nActivated Effector T cells can be placed into three functioning classes, detecting [[peptide]] antigens originating from various types of [[pathogen]]: The first class being 1) [[Cytotoxic T cells]], which kill infected target cells by [[apoptosis]] without using cytokines, 2) [[TH1 cells]], which primarily function to activate macrophages, and 3) [[TH2 cells]], which primarily function to stimulate [[B cells]] into producing [[antibodies]].<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\nThe [[innate immune system]] and the [[adaptive immune system]] each comprise both [[humoral immunity|humoral]] and cell-mediated components.\n\nCellular immunity protects the body through:\n\n* T-cell mediated immunity or [[T-cell immunity]]: activating antigen-specific [[cytotoxic T cell]]s that are able to induce [[apoptosis]] in body cells displaying [[epitopes]] of foreign antigen on their surface, such as [[virus]]-infected cells, cells with intracellular bacteria, and cancer cells displaying [[tumor]] antigens;\n* [[Macrophage]] and [[natural killer cell]] action: enabling the destruction of pathogens via recognition and secretion of cytotoxic granules (for natural killer cells)<ref name=\"Eissmann\">{{cite web |last1=Eissmann |first1=Philipp |title=Natural Killer Cells |url=https://www.immunology.org/public-information/bitesized-immunology/cells/natural-killer-cells |website=British Society for Immunology |publisher=British Society for Immunology |accessdate=8 November 2018}}</ref> and phagocytosis (for macrophages)<ref name=\"Saldana\">{{cite web |last1=Saldana |first1=Jos\u00e9 |title=Macrophages |url=https://www.immunology.org/public-information/bitesized-immunology/cells/macrophages |website=British Society for Immunology |publisher=British Society for Immunology |accessdate=8 November 2018}}</ref>; and\n* Stimulating cells to secrete a variety of [[cytokine]]s that influence the function of other cells involved in adaptive immune responses and innate immune responses.<ref name=\"Eissmann\" /><ref name=\"Saldana\" />\n\nCell-mediated immunity is directed primarily at microbes that survive in [[phagocytes]] and [[microbes]] that infect non-phagocytic cells. It is most effective in removing virus-infected cells, but also participates in defending against [[fungi]], [[protozoan]]s, [[cancer]]s, and intracellular bacteria. It also plays a major role in [[transplant rejection]].\n\n==See also==\n* [[Immune system]]\n* [[Immunity (medical)|Immunity]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n* [http://www.britannica.com/science/cell-mediated-immunity Cell-mediated immunity] (Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica)\n* [https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK10762/ Chapter 8:T Cell-Mediated Immunity ] Immunobiology: The Immune System in Health and Disease. 5th edition.\n\n==Further reading==\n* [https://link.springer.com/chapter/10.1007/978-3-662-10373-9_3 Cell-Mediated Immunity. Murphy]\n* [http://missinglink.ucsf.edu/lm/immunology_module/prologue/objectives/obj07.html Cell-mediated immunity: How T cells recognize and respond to foreign antigens]\n\n{{Blood}}\n{{Immune_system}}\n{{Hypersensitivity and autoimmune diseases}}\n\n[[Category:Immunology]]\n", "name_user": "2403:6200:88a8:efe7:259f:f26f:79d7:5765", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eSee also)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cell-mediated_immunity"}
{"title_page": "Eric Butcher", "text_new": "{{Infobox artist\n\n| image         = File:Eric Butcher in his studio, photographed by Jonny Back.jpg\n| alt           =\n| imagesize     =\n| caption       = Eric Butcher in his studio\n| birth_date    = {{Birth year and age|1970}}\n| birth_place   = Singapore\n| nationality   = [[Great Britain|British]]\n| field         = Painting\n| training      = [[Corpus Christi College, Cambridge]], \n[[Wimbledon College of Art|Wimbledon School of Art]]\n| movement      = [[Abstract art]]\n| works         =\n}}\n\n'''Eric Butcher''' (born 1970) is a contemporary British abstract painter known for his reductive, processed-based approach.\n\nButcher read philosophy at [[Corpus Christi College, Cambridge]], graduating in 1994 and completed an MA in Fine Art at [[Wimbledon College of Art|Wimbledon School of Art]] in 2001. He has exhibited extensively in the UK and internationally with shows in Germany, Italy, Australia and the USA.<ref name=\"Underground\">(2007). \u201cUnderground\u201d, p.78. Centre for Art International Research, Liverpool, {{ISBN|978-0-9552820-6-5}}.</ref> He currently shows with Toomey Tourell gallery, San Francisco,<ref>Toomey-Tourell Fine Art [http://toomey-tourell.com/artists/eric-butcher/ \"Eric Butcher\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121001153714/http://www.toomey-tourell.com/artists/eric-butcher |date=2012-10-01 }}</ref> Galerie Robert Drees in Hannover<ref>Galerie Robert Drees [http://www.galerie-robert-drees.de/index.php/drees/kuenstler/eric_butcher] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120823232622/http://www.galerie-robert-drees.de/index.php/drees/kuenstler/eric_butcher |date=2012-08-23 }}\"Eric Butcher\"</ref> and Patrick Heide Contemporary Art.<ref>Patrick Heide Contemporary Art, Collaborating Artists [https://www.patrickheide.com/index.php/artists/eric-butcher]</ref> \n\nHe has received awards from the [[Arts Council England|Arts Council, England]] and the [[Arts and Humanities Research Council]]. He has also held an Arts Institute at Bournemouth Research Fellowship (now the [[Arts University Bournemouth|AUB]]<ref>[http://aub.ac.uk/about-us/governance/\u201dArts University College Bournemouth\u201d]{{Dead link|date=December 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}.</ref>) and was the Centre for Arts International Research/Liverpool School of Art & Design Multiple Perspectives Fellow 2007.<ref name=\"Underground\" />\n\nButcher was a selected artist in the final Jerwood Drawing Prize in 2017<ref>Jerwood Drawing Prize 2017, published by the Jerwood Charitable Foundation, London {{ISBN|978-1-908331-29-8}} (texts: Anita Taylor, David Dibosa, Helen Legg, Michael Simpson)</ref> (now [[Trinity Buoy Wharf Drawing Prize]]) alongside artists such as [[Barbara Walker (artist)]] and selected by writer/curator, David Dibosa; director of [[Tate Liverpool]], Helen Legg (then director of [[Spike Island Artspace]]); and [[Michael Simpson (painter)]]. In 2020 Butcher exhibited his second solo show, Sweet Heresy<ref>Sweet Heresy | Eric Butcher [https://www.patrickheide.com/exhibitions/sweet-heresy-eric-butcher]</ref>, at Patrick Heide Contemporary Art, which coincided with the release of Time Trial, a newly published 160-page hardback catalogue of his recent work.<ref>\u201dTime Trial\u201d, Eric Butcher {{ISBN|978-1-5272-5156-4}}.</ref>\n\n\n__TOC__\n\n==Early Life and Education==\nEric Butcher was born in Singapore in 1970 to a Dutch mother and British father. Shortly after he was born the family moved to Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia and then settled in the UK in Hampshire, England in 1974.\nAfter leaving school at 16 he spent two formative years studying art at [[Basingstoke College of Technology]], after which he undertook A Levels at evening classes and eventually found his way to [[Corpus Christi College, Cambridge]], reading philosophy and graduating in 1994.\nAfter several years of developing his work in relative isolation he returned to art school and in 2001 he completed an MA in Fine Art at Wimbledon School of Art. He has worked for the past twenty years from a rural setting in his studio in Oxfordshire<ref>\"Eric Butcher: Richness in Rightness\", p.22. Paul Carey-Kent {{ISBN|978-1-5272-5156-4}}.</ref> a converted barn and a place of tranquility, creativity and precision.<ref>Patrick Heide Contemporary Art, Collaborating Artists [https://www.patrickheide.com/index.php/artists/eric-butcher]</ref> \n\n==Career==\n===Early work===\nButcher's earliest exhibited works were compositions of oil, resin and spray paint on large, tablet-like MDF supports. The combination of painted surface and exaggerated depth of the support made the works deliberately and obviously three-dimensional objects \u2013 an \u2018attempt to deny the viewer the desire to see the surface as anything other than surface\u2019.<ref>(2003). \u201cArcs + Surfaces, A Conversation with Eric Butcher\u201d, p.11. Vertigo Gallery, London, {{ISBN|1-903771-08-0}}.</ref> This composed physical presence was inherent in even the most restrained of Butcher's works, as William Packer would go on to say in his introduction to Butcher's 2005 catalogue, Carbon Candy, \u2018even when hung conventionally, flat to the wall, they remain obviously and directly physical\u2019.<ref>\u201dCarbon Candy\u201d, p.4. Vertigo Gallery, London, {{ISBN|1-903771-12-9}}.</ref> Although characterised by their appearance \u2013 an abstract \u2018accretion of paint, resin and various other fluids\u2019<ref name=\"Arcs\">(2003). \u201cArcs + Surfaces, A Conversation with Eric Butcher\u201d, p.12. Vertigo Gallery, London, {{ISBN|1-903771-08-0}}.</ref> - their manufacture was faithful to the rules that govern Butcher's creative process.<ref>Eric Butcher [http://www.ericbutcher.com/statement/ \"statement\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130824131126/http://ericbutcher.com/statement/ |date=2013-08-24 }}.</ref> Butcher has said of his practice that \u2018the application or subtraction of paint as a set of processes is achieved through a variety of continually evolving techniques which draw attention to the physical properties of my materials\u2019,<ref name=\"ericbutcher\">Eric Butcher [http://www.ericbutcher.com/statement/\"statement\u201d] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130824131126/http://ericbutcher.com/statement/ |date=2013-08-24 }}.</ref> a result that would be most clearly manifest in his subsequent metal works. The introduction of metal as a support revolutionised Butcher's creative output and his approach to the act of painting, \u2018it may just be a flat piece of metal\u2026 But they all have little nicks, edges and imperfections\u2026 the end result is an accumulation of what I have learnt about that surface\u2019.<ref name=\"Arcs\" />\n[[File:Eric Butcher, ER.358.jpg|thumb|left|alt=ER.358.|ER.358 Oil and resin on extruded aluminium box sections.]]\n===Philosophy and approach to painting===\n\u2018The application or subtraction of paint\u2019 in Butcher's practice is executed through the use of \u2018a metal blade drawn across the painting\u2019s surface\u2019<ref name=\"DefiniteArticle\">\u201dDefinite Article, Objects and Surfaces, Eric Butcher\u201d, p.7. Vertigo Gallery, London, {{ISBN|1-903771-13-7}}.</ref> pulling a thin transparent monochrome of oil and resin over the metal support, \u2018this procedure is then repeated and repeated, building up a surface of accumulated residues'.<ref name=\"DefiniteArticle\" /> The outcome of each painting is determined by \u2018variations in colour modulation\u2019<ref name=\"DefiniteArticle\" /> and largely \u2018by the physical characteristics of the support\u2019.<ref>Eric Butcher [https://www.ericbutcher.com/statement\u201dstatement\u201d]</ref> 'Paint is registered in vertical and horizontal bands across the surface of the metal plane, with areas of metal left unpainted and its polished face exposed to the viewer. the colour is omitted and the bare aluminium emerges. As a result two rhythms arise; on the one hand the colour fields are interrupted by sections of contrasting colour, and on the other hand we have the various degrees of paint application, which range from impasto to diaphanous. They completely cover the aluminium, yet also let it shimmer through'.<ref>Kr\u00e4mer, Harald (2013). \"Bildwerke\", p.23. Galerie Robert Drees.</ref> \n\nAlthough Butcher has a uniform approach to each work,<ref name=\"DefiniteArticle\" /> they nevertheless differ vastly from one another as the artist may encounter subtle material differences in the surface of each extrusion; burrs in the metal itself or unexpected variations in the applied paint wash.<ref>Sheldon, Julie (2007). \u201cUnderground\u201d, p.32. Centre for Art International Research, Liverpool, {{ISBN|978-0-9552820-6-5}}.</ref> Almost every piece will seek to preserve some element of the metal as well, \u2018the aluminium asserts itself as the artwork\u2019s true substance\u2019.<ref name=\"Baker\" /> As Butcher seeks to articulate the surfaces of aluminium structures,<ref name=\"ericbutcher\" /> he does so not only through the repetitive layers of colour application, but also through the preservation of the support's original condition (before his intervention) \u2013 both make for an overall representation of that particular structure's history.\n\nFor the Material Witness exhibition at Toomey Tourell gallery in 2010, Butcher exhibited fourteen of his painted aluminium extrusions.<ref name=\"Baker\">Baker, Kenneth (March 13, 2010). \u201cButcher Shines at Toomey Tourell\u201d. San Francisco Chronicle, p.E-1.</ref> Hung vertically and spaced asymmetrically with a measured and careful distance between one another,<ref name=\"Baker\" /> the display articulated Butcher's increasing awareness of, and preoccupation with, \u2018installation\u2019 in creating a total cohesive experience rather than an isolated object.<ref name=\"ericbutcher\" /> As Kenneth Baker, in his [[San Francisco Chronicle]] review, wrote of the work's interaction with the space it occupied, \u2018to walk this piece is to compose and recompose it through observation. Its geometry and built-in illusionism dictate that it cannot be seen whole\u2019.<ref name=\"Baker\" /> This can also be said of Butcher's curatorial practice, where, as in the Definite Article exhibition curated by the artist himself,<ref>\u201dDefinite Article, Objects and Surfaces, Eric Butcher\u201d, p.3. Vertigo Gallery, London, {{ISBN|1-903771-13-7}}.</ref> he deals with the scale and arrangement of works by Roger Ackling, [[Marc Vaux]] and Cathy Wade, as well as his own. Butcher's attempts within his own works in that exhibition to, \u2018engage the space around the painted surface\u2019<ref name=\"DefiniteArticle\" /> were similarly factors that he encountered in his curation of the exhibition as a whole, \u2018each of the artists\u2026 employs a range of techniques to encourage the viewer to engage with the work physically\u2019.<ref name=\"DefiniteArticle\" />\n[[File:Eric Butcher, GR.578.jpg|thumb|right|alt=GR.578.|GR.578 Blind embossed paper with cutouts.]]\n\n===Site-specific Installations===\nEric Butcher's site-specific installations are interventions in space. Like the intimate relationship between painted surface and objects that distinguish his work, they become 'a pause in the act or a mistake in the material'<ref name=Bildwerke>Kr\u00e4mer, Harald (2013). \"Bildwerke\", p.27. Galerie Robert Drees.</ref>, 'subtle and stunning, installed in space dispersed over corners, corridors or in staircases they become architecture in motion'.<ref name=TimeTrial16>Heide, Patrick (2019). 'Time Trial', p.16. Galerie Robert Drees, Patrick Heide Contemporary Art and Eric Butcher.</ref> This methodology can be seen in the lengths, or fragments, of aluminium that 'seem to cling to the wall [in his installations]. In part driven by chance, and yet still composed according to a strict order'.<ref name=Bildwerke /> The context of these installations have become increasingly important, 'determined by aspects of its context; both its physical environment and psychological purpose'<ref name=TimeTrial>Butcher, Eric (2019). 'Time Trial', p.89. Galerie Robert Drees, Patrick Heide Contemporary Art and Eric Butcher.</ref> as Butcher says in his recent catalogue, Time Trial. 'As soon as I started to consider the intersections between surfaces and the wall, I was naturally, logically led to a consideration of the whole environmental context of the work and hence to site-specificity.'<ref name=TimeTrial /> This mirrors his approach to the objects he works with, the 'relationship between the painted surface and the object (upon which one surface has been singled out for preferential treatment), between 'surface' and 'objectness'.<ref name=TimeTrial68>Butcher, Eric (2019). 'Time Trial', p.68. Galerie Robert Drees, Patrick Heide Contemporary Art and Eric Butcher.</ref> \n\nAlthough the components of these installations appear to 'cling to the wall'<ref name=Bildwerke />, the evidence of their fixings are increasingly integral to the installation, 'how a piece fixes to the wall, its method of construction, the way in which the work is joined together and adhered to its backing; I want this to be clear and evident. Bolts and fixings are used which in some cases pierce the painted surfaces'.<ref name=TimeTrial65>Butcher, Eric (2019). 'Time Trial', p.65. Galerie Robert Drees, Patrick Heide Contemporary Art and Eric Butcher.</ref>\n\n===Paperworks===\nAs a consequence of this preoccupation with installation, some of Butcher's most recent pieces, his works on paper, experiment diagrammatically with possible arrangements for his large-scale installations of aluminium pieces, 'they repeat\nthe principle of the aluminium works in their own specific way'<ref name=Bildwerke /> introducing elements of chance.<ref name=\"ConversationWith\">\u201dA Conversation With Jagjit Chuhan\u201d, p. 77. Centre for Art International Research, Liverpool, {{ISBN|978-0-9557360-4-9}}.</ref> In these paper works, impressions of metal plates are embossed into sheets of saturated paper by running it through a printing press.<ref>\u201dA Conversation With Jagjit Chuhan\u201d, p. 80. Centre for Art International Research, Liverpool, {{ISBN|978-0-9557360-4-9}}.</ref> Some sections of the plates\u2019 impressions are then highlighted by ink, whereas some sections are cut out altogether \u2013 some left purely as a trace.<ref name=\"ConversationWith\" /> 'These interventions take place separated from one another, yet may also intertwine. Through these perforations, the wall which is behind the deckle edged paper becomes a component of the work and takes on a bigger or smaller role depending on the size and quantity of perforations'.<ref name=Bildwerke /> Butcher refers to this register of trace in his paper works as speaking, metaphorically, of loss and absence.<ref>\u201dA Conversation With Jagjit Chuhan\u201d, p. 81. Centre for Art International Research, Liverpool, {{ISBN|978-0-9557360-4-9}}.</ref>\n\n==Exhibition History==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Selected Solo Exhibitions !! Gallery/Museum\n|-\n| 2020 || Sweet Heresy || Patrick Heide Contemporary Art, London\n|-\n| 2018 || Artificial Light || Nancy Toomey Fine Art, San Francisco, USA\n|-\n| 2015 || Data Capture || Patrick Heide Contemporary Art, London\n|-\n| 2013 || A Synthetic Kind of Love || Galerie Robert Drees, Hannover, Germany\n|-\n| 2010 || Material Witness || Toomey-Tourell gallery, San Francisco, USA\n|-\n| 2007 || Honey Trap || Toomey-Tourell gallery, San Francisco, USA\n|-\n| 2007 || Static Interference || Vertigo gallery, London\n|-\n| 2005 || Hanging Garden || Text + Work, the Art Institute at Bournemouth\n|-\n| 2005 || Arte Fiera || Vertigo gallery, Bologna, Italy\n|-\n| 2004 || Carbon Candy || Vertigo gallery, London \n|-\n| 2003 || Arcs + Surfaces || Vertigo gallery, London \n|-\n| 2002 || Cusp (two-person with Rebecca McLynn) || Sarah Myerscough Fine Art, London\n|-\n| 2000 || A Line of Enquiry || The Loading Bay, London\n|-\n| 1999 || The Antidote || The Loading Bay, London\n|-\n| 1997 || New Paintings || Concord Sylvania, London\n|-\n| 1997 || The Painted Figure (two-person with Gabriel Schmitz) || Hirschl Contemporary Art, London \n|-\n| 1995 || Lingering in Chambers of the Sea || The Acorn gallery, Liverpool\n|-\n| 1995 || New Paintings || Gallery 28, Reading\n|-\n| 1993 || Coming Up for Air || Engert Haus, Munich, Germany\n|-\n| 1991 || Beata Clarisa || Corpus Christi College, Cambridge\n|}\n\n=== Group Exhibitions ===\nEric Butcher has participated in many group shows including \"The Waterlilly Foundation\", [[Cambridge Guildhall]] (1994), \"The Genitals Are Beauty\", The House of William Blake, London (1995), \"The Art Experience\", The Atrium Gallery, London (1997), \"Wall to Wall\", Sarah Myerscough Fine Art, London (2002), \"Paperwork\" and \"30 x 30\", Vertigo Gallery, London (2003), \"Surface\", Vertigo Gallery (2004), the touring exhibition \"Definite Article\" with Roger Ackling, [[Marc Vaux]] and Cathy Wade, Vertigo gallery, London and Toomey-Tourell gallery, San Francisco, USA (2005/6), \"Meeting Place - Contemporary Art and the Museum Collection\", [[Russell-Cotes Art Gallery & Museum]], Bournemouth and the Arts Institute at Bournemouth (curated by Stephanie James & Jackie Serafopoulos) (2007), \"Underground\", [[Shoreditch]] Town Hall basement, London (three-person with Roger Ackling and Sim\u00f3n Granell) (2007), \"Ten\", Toomey-Tourell gallery, San Francisco, USA (2008), \"\u00dcber Fl\u00e4chen\", Galerie Robert Drees, Hannover, Germany (2010), \"Raw\", Pertwee, Anderson & Gold, London, (2011), \"Beyond the Commission\", The Gallery, Arts University College Bournemouth (2011), \"One Thing Leads to Another\", Portland House, Malvern (2011), \"The Devil Finds Work for Idle Hands\", Toomey-Tourell gallery, San Francisco, USA (2012), \"ReGroup\", Red Space, London (2012).\n\nRecent selected group exhibitions also include the touring exhibition \"A Machine Aesthetic\", Gallery North [[Northumbria University]], Newcastle; The Gallery, AUB, Bournemouth; Project Space Plus, University of Lincoln; The Gallery, Norwich University of the Arts; Transition Gallery, London, \"Down to Zero\", Patrick Heide Contemporary Art, London (curated by Michael Roberts), \"(Detail)\", H Project Space, Bangkok, Thailand; Usher Gallery, Lincoln; Transition gallery, London (curated by Andrew Bracey) (2014), \"An Einem Tisch - Contemporary Geometrical Abstraction\", Galerie Robert Drees, Hannover, Germany, \"Beyond Gravity II\", Galerie und Kunstcabinett Corona Unger, Bremen, Germany (2016), \"OVADA Seven Counties Open\", OVADA Warehouse, Oxford, \"The Jerwood Drawing Prize\", Jerwood Space, London, East Gallery, Norwich, The Edge, Bath, Sidney Cooper Gallery, Canterbury Vane Gallery, Newcastle-upon-Tyne, \"Mardi Gras Requiem\", Project Space Plus, Lincoln (2017), \"Intensity\", the House of St. Barnabas, London (curated by Paul Carey-Kent), \"Einsnullnull\", Galerie Robert Drees, Hannover, Germany (2018), \"Everything but Canvas\", Galerie Robert Drees, Hannover, Germany (2019), and \"Invited By\", Galerie Robert Drees, Hannover, Germany (2019/20).\n\n==Curating==\nButcher's creative practice has also embraced curating; initiating exhibitions/projects including Emission (2001), Definite Article (2005/6), Underground (2007), The Devil Finds Work for Idle Hands (2012) and A Machine Aesthetic (2013/14). A Machine Aesthetic (co-curated with Sim\u00f3n Granell), was a major national touring exhibition presenting the work of 11 contemporary British artists whose creative practices engaged with the concept of mechanisation. The exhibition explored the various manifestations, uses and influences of different aspects of mechanisation within the practices of an otherwise diverse group of artists (with [[Andrew Bracey]], Eric Butcher, David Connearn, Rob Currie, Paul Goodfellow, Sim\u00f3n Granell, [[Emma Hart (artist)]], Dan Hays, Natasha Kidd, Tim Knowles, Michael Roberts). In conjunction with the exhibition, the curators guest edited an edition of the arts and culture magazine Garageland (issue XVI: Machines)<ref>[https://www.transitiongallery.co.uk/htmlpages/editions/GL16/intro.htm \"Garageland: issue XVI: Machines\" {{ISSN|1749-9267}}.</ref>, which was themed to coincide with the show.\n\n\n==Further reading==\n*Butcher Shines at Toomey Tourell, Kenneth Baker, San Francisco Chronicle, pg. E - 1, March 13, 2010\n* Material Witness, Centre for Art International Research, Liverpool, {{ISBN|978-0-9557360-4-9}}. Text: Roy Exley, Eric Butcher & the Aluminium Works\n* Underground, Centre for Art International Research, Liverpool, {{ISBN|978-0-9552820-6-5}}. Texts: John Haldane, Underground; Lee Trimings, Loveslaves; Julie Sheldon, Process by Protocol; Tania Kovats, Digging.\n* Meeting Place, the Russell-Cotes Art Gallery & Museum, Bournemouth, in association with Text + Work, the Arts Institute at Bournemouth, {{ISBN|978-0-901196-20-0}}, Ed. Stephanie James & Les Buckingham. Texts inc. Eric Butcher, Discoveries\n* Art at More London, The LG collection of Contemporary art, London (collection catalogue), Ed. Margaret O\u2019Regan\n* Hanging Garden, Text + Work, the Arts Institute at Bournemouth, Bournemouth {{ISBN|0-901196-09-6}} (exhibition catalogue). Text, James Barron, Spaces, In, Out and Around\n* Definite Article, Vertigo Gallery, London, {{ISBN|1-903771-13-7}} (exhibition catalogue). Text: Eric Butcher, Objects and Surfaces. Essay reprinted (abridged) in Art & Architecture Journal, No. 63, Autumn 2005\n* Carbon Candy, Vertigo Gallery, London, {{ISBN|1-903771-12-9}} (exhibition catalogue). Text: William Packer, Untitled\n* Arcs + Surfaces, Vertigo Gallery, London, {{ISBN|1-903771-08-0}} (exhibition catalogue). Texts: Angela Kingston, New Paintings by Eric Butcher, Catherine Shearn, A Conversation with Eric Butcher.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.ericbutcher.com Eric Butcher website]\n*[http://www.toomey-tourell.com/artists/eric-butcher/ Eric Butcher at Toomey Tourell gallery]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20120823232622/http://www.galerie-robert-drees.de/index.php/drees/kuenstler/eric_butcher Eric Butcher at Galerie Robert Drees]\n*[https://www.patrickheide.com/artists/eric-butcher Eric Butcher at Patrick Heide Contemporary Art]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Butcher, Eric}}\n[[Category:20th-century English painters]]\n[[Category:English male painters]]\n[[Category:21st-century English painters]]\n[[Category:1970 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Singaporean emigrants to the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Corpus Christi College, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:People associated with Arts University Bournemouth]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox artist\n\n| image         = File:Eric Butcher in his studio, photographed by Jonny Back.jpg\n| alt           =\n| imagesize     =\n| caption       = Eric Butcher in his studio\n| birth_date    = {{Birth year and age|1970}}\n| birth_place   = Singapore\n| nationality   = [[Great Britain|British]]\n| field         = Painting\n| training      = [[Corpus Christi College, Cambridge]], \n[[Wimbledon College of Art|Wimbledon School of Art]]\n| movement      = [[Abstract art]]\n| works         =\n}}\n\n'''Eric Butcher''' (born 1970) is a contemporary British abstract painter known for his reductive, processed-based approach.\n\nButcher read philosophy at [[Corpus Christi College, Cambridge]], graduating in 1994 and completed an MA in Fine Art at [[Wimbledon College of Art|Wimbledon School of Art]] in 2001. He has exhibited extensively in the UK and internationally with shows in Germany, Italy, Australia and the USA.<ref name=\"Underground\">(2007). \u201cUnderground\u201d, p.78. Centre for Art International Research, Liverpool, {{ISBN|978-0-9552820-6-5}}.</ref> He currently shows with Toomey Tourell gallery, San Francisco,<ref>Toomey-Tourell Fine Art [http://toomey-tourell.com/artists/eric-butcher/ \"Eric Butcher\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121001153714/http://www.toomey-tourell.com/artists/eric-butcher |date=2012-10-01 }}</ref> Galerie Robert Drees in Hannover<ref>Galerie Robert Drees [http://www.galerie-robert-drees.de/index.php/drees/kuenstler/eric_butcher] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120823232622/http://www.galerie-robert-drees.de/index.php/drees/kuenstler/eric_butcher |date=2012-08-23 }}\"Eric Butcher\"</ref> and Patrick Heide Contemporary Art.<ref>Patrick Heide Contemporary Art, Collaborating Artists [https://www.patrickheide.com/index.php/artists/eric-butcher]</ref> \n\nHe has received awards from the [[Arts Council England|Arts Council, England]] and the [[Arts and Humanities Research Council]]. He has also held an Arts Institute at Bournemouth Research Fellowship (now the [[Arts University Bournemouth|AUB]]<ref>[http://aub.ac.uk/about-us/governance/\u201dArts University College Bournemouth\u201d]{{Dead link|date=December 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}.</ref>) and was the Centre for Arts International Research/Liverpool School of Art & Design Multiple Perspectives Fellow 2007.<ref name=\"Underground\" />\n\nButcher was a selected artist in the final Jerwood Drawing Prize in 2017<ref>Jerwood Drawing Prize 2017, published by the Jerwood Charitable Foundation, London {{ISBN|978-1-908331-29-8}} (texts: Anita Taylor, David Dibosa, Helen Legg, Michael Simpson)</ref> (now [[Trinity Buoy Wharf Drawing Prize]]) alongside artists such as [[Barbara Walker (artist)]]. In 2020 Butcher exhibited his second solo show at Patrick Heide Contemporary Art, Sweet Heresy<ref>Sweet Heresy | Eric Butcher [https://www.patrickheide.com/exhibitions/sweet-heresy-eric-butcher]</ref> which coincided with the release of Time Trial, a newly published 160-page hardback catalogue of his recent work.<ref>\u201dTime Trial\u201d, Eric Butcher {{ISBN|978-1-5272-5156-4}}.</ref>\n\n\n__TOC__\n\n==Early Life and Education==\nEric Butcher was born in Singapore in 1970 to a Dutch mother and British father. Shortly after he was born the family moved to Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia and then settled in the UK in Hampshire, England in 1974.\nAfter leaving school at 16 he spent two formative years studying art at [[Basingstoke College of Technology]], after which he undertook A Levels at evening classes and eventually found his way to [[Corpus Christi College, Cambridge]], reading philosophy and graduating in 1994.\nAfter several years of developing his work in relative isolation he returned to art school and in 2001 he completed an MA in Fine Art at Wimbledon School of Art. He has worked for the past twenty years from a rural setting in his studio in Oxfordshire<ref>\"Eric Butcher: Richness in Rightness\", p.22. Paul Carey-Kent {{ISBN|978-1-5272-5156-4}}.</ref> a converted barn and a place of tranquility, creativity and precision.<ref>Patrick Heide Contemporary Art, Collaborating Artists [https://www.patrickheide.com/index.php/artists/eric-butcher]</ref> \n\n==Career==\n===Early work===\nButcher's earliest exhibited works were compositions of oil, resin and spray paint on large, tablet-like MDF supports. The combination of painted surface and exaggerated depth of the support made the works deliberately and obviously three-dimensional objects \u2013 an \u2018attempt to deny the viewer the desire to see the surface as anything other than surface\u2019.<ref>(2003). \u201cArcs + Surfaces, A Conversation with Eric Butcher\u201d, p.11. Vertigo Gallery, London, {{ISBN|1-903771-08-0}}.</ref> This composed physical presence was inherent in even the most restrained of Butcher's works, as William Packer would go on to say in his introduction to Butcher's 2005 catalogue, Carbon Candy, \u2018even when hung conventionally, flat to the wall, they remain obviously and directly physical\u2019.<ref>\u201dCarbon Candy\u201d, p.4. Vertigo Gallery, London, {{ISBN|1-903771-12-9}}.</ref> Although characterised by their appearance \u2013 an abstract \u2018accretion of paint, resin and various other fluids\u2019<ref name=\"Arcs\">(2003). \u201cArcs + Surfaces, A Conversation with Eric Butcher\u201d, p.12. Vertigo Gallery, London, {{ISBN|1-903771-08-0}}.</ref> - their manufacture was faithful to the rules that govern Butcher's creative process.<ref>Eric Butcher [http://www.ericbutcher.com/statement/ \"statement\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130824131126/http://ericbutcher.com/statement/ |date=2013-08-24 }}.</ref> Butcher has said of his practice that \u2018the application or subtraction of paint as a set of processes is achieved through a variety of continually evolving techniques which draw attention to the physical properties of my materials\u2019,<ref name=\"ericbutcher\">Eric Butcher [http://www.ericbutcher.com/statement/\"statement\u201d] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130824131126/http://ericbutcher.com/statement/ |date=2013-08-24 }}.</ref> a result that would be most clearly manifest in his subsequent metal works. The introduction of metal as a support revolutionised Butcher's creative output and his approach to the act of painting, \u2018it may just be a flat piece of metal\u2026 But they all have little nicks, edges and imperfections\u2026 the end result is an accumulation of what I have learnt about that surface\u2019.<ref name=\"Arcs\" />\n[[File:Eric Butcher, ER.358.jpg|thumb|left|alt=ER.358.|ER.358 Oil and resin on extruded aluminium box sections.]]\n===Philosophy and approach to painting===\n\u2018The application or subtraction of paint\u2019 in Butcher's practice is executed through the use of \u2018a metal blade drawn across the painting\u2019s surface\u2019<ref name=\"DefiniteArticle\">\u201dDefinite Article, Objects and Surfaces, Eric Butcher\u201d, p.7. Vertigo Gallery, London, {{ISBN|1-903771-13-7}}.</ref> pulling a thin transparent monochrome of oil and resin over the metal support, \u2018this procedure is then repeated and repeated, building up a surface of accumulated residues'.<ref name=\"DefiniteArticle\" /> The outcome of each painting is determined by \u2018variations in colour modulation\u2019<ref name=\"DefiniteArticle\" /> and largely \u2018by the physical characteristics of the support\u2019.<ref>Eric Butcher [https://www.ericbutcher.com/statement\u201dstatement\u201d]</ref> 'Paint is registered in vertical and horizontal bands across the surface of the metal plane, with areas of metal left unpainted and its polished face exposed to the viewer. the colour is omitted and the bare aluminium emerges. As a result two rhythms arise; on the one hand the colour fields are interrupted by sections of contrasting colour, and on the other hand we have the various degrees of paint application, which range from impasto to diaphanous. They completely cover the aluminium, yet also let it shimmer through'.<ref>Kr\u00e4mer, Harald (2013). \"Bildwerke\", p.23. Galerie Robert Drees.</ref> \n\nAlthough Butcher has a uniform approach to each work,<ref name=\"DefiniteArticle\" /> they nevertheless differ vastly from one another as the artist may encounter subtle material differences in the surface of each extrusion; burrs in the metal itself or unexpected variations in the applied paint wash.<ref>Sheldon, Julie (2007). \u201cUnderground\u201d, p.32. Centre for Art International Research, Liverpool, {{ISBN|978-0-9552820-6-5}}.</ref> Almost every piece will seek to preserve some element of the metal as well, \u2018the aluminium asserts itself as the artwork\u2019s true substance\u2019.<ref name=\"Baker\" /> As Butcher seeks to articulate the surfaces of aluminium structures,<ref name=\"ericbutcher\" /> he does so not only through the repetitive layers of colour application, but also through the preservation of the support's original condition (before his intervention) \u2013 both make for an overall representation of that particular structure's history.\n\nFor the Material Witness exhibition at Toomey Tourell gallery in 2010, Butcher exhibited fourteen of his painted aluminium extrusions.<ref name=\"Baker\">Baker, Kenneth (March 13, 2010). \u201cButcher Shines at Toomey Tourell\u201d. San Francisco Chronicle, p.E-1.</ref> Hung vertically and spaced asymmetrically with a measured and careful distance between one another,<ref name=\"Baker\" /> the display articulated Butcher's increasing awareness of, and preoccupation with, \u2018installation\u2019 in creating a total cohesive experience rather than an isolated object.<ref name=\"ericbutcher\" /> As Kenneth Baker, in his [[San Francisco Chronicle]] review, wrote of the work's interaction with the space it occupied, \u2018to walk this piece is to compose and recompose it through observation. Its geometry and built-in illusionism dictate that it cannot be seen whole\u2019.<ref name=\"Baker\" /> This can also be said of Butcher's curatorial practice, where, as in the Definite Article exhibition curated by the artist himself,<ref>\u201dDefinite Article, Objects and Surfaces, Eric Butcher\u201d, p.3. Vertigo Gallery, London, {{ISBN|1-903771-13-7}}.</ref> he deals with the scale and arrangement of works by Roger Ackling, [[Marc Vaux]] and Cathy Wade, as well as his own. Butcher's attempts within his own works in that exhibition to, \u2018engage the space around the painted surface\u2019<ref name=\"DefiniteArticle\" /> were similarly factors that he encountered in his curation of the exhibition as a whole, \u2018each of the artists\u2026 employs a range of techniques to encourage the viewer to engage with the work physically\u2019.<ref name=\"DefiniteArticle\" />\n[[File:Eric Butcher, GR.578.jpg|thumb|right|alt=GR.578.|GR.578 Blind embossed paper with cutouts.]]\n\n===Site-specific Installations===\nEric Butcher's site-specific installations are interventions in space. Like the intimate relationship between painted surface and objects that distinguish his work, they become 'a pause in the act or a mistake in the material'<ref name=Bildwerke>Kr\u00e4mer, Harald (2013). \"Bildwerke\", p.27. Galerie Robert Drees.</ref>, 'subtle and stunning, installed in space dispersed over corners, corridors or in staircases they become architecture in motion'.<ref name=TimeTrial16>Heide, Patrick (2019). 'Time Trial', p.16. Galerie Robert Drees, Patrick Heide Contemporary Art and Eric Butcher.</ref> This methodology can be seen in the lengths, or fragments, of aluminium that 'seem to cling to the wall [in his installations]. In part driven by chance, and yet still composed according to a strict order'.<ref name=Bildwerke /> The context of these installations have become increasingly important, 'determined by aspects of its context; both its physical environment and psychological purpose'<ref name=TimeTrial>Butcher, Eric (2019). 'Time Trial', p.89. Galerie Robert Drees, Patrick Heide Contemporary Art and Eric Butcher.</ref> as Butcher says in his recent catalogue, Time Trial. 'As soon as I started to consider the intersections between surfaces and the wall, I was naturally, logically led to a consideration of the whole environmental context of the work and hence to site-specificity.'<ref name=TimeTrial /> This mirrors his approach to the objects he works with, the 'relationship between the painted surface and the object (upon which one surface has been singled out for preferential treatment), between 'surface' and 'objectness'.<ref name=TimeTrial68>Butcher, Eric (2019). 'Time Trial', p.68. Galerie Robert Drees, Patrick Heide Contemporary Art and Eric Butcher.</ref> \n\nAlthough the components of these installations appear to 'cling to the wall'<ref name=Bildwerke />, the evidence of their fixings are increasingly integral to the installation, 'how a piece fixes to the wall, its method of construction, the way in which the work is joined together and adhered to its backing; I want this to be clear and evident. Bolts and fixings are used which in some cases pierce the painted surfaces'.<ref name=TimeTrial65>Butcher, Eric (2019). 'Time Trial', p.65. Galerie Robert Drees, Patrick Heide Contemporary Art and Eric Butcher.</ref>\n\n===Paperworks===\nAs a consequence of this preoccupation with installation, some of Butcher's most recent pieces, his works on paper, experiment diagrammatically with possible arrangements for his large-scale installations of aluminium pieces, 'they repeat\nthe principle of the aluminium works in their own specific way'<ref name=Bildwerke /> introducing elements of chance.<ref name=\"ConversationWith\">\u201dA Conversation With Jagjit Chuhan\u201d, p. 77. Centre for Art International Research, Liverpool, {{ISBN|978-0-9557360-4-9}}.</ref> In these paper works, impressions of metal plates are embossed into sheets of saturated paper by running it through a printing press.<ref>\u201dA Conversation With Jagjit Chuhan\u201d, p. 80. Centre for Art International Research, Liverpool, {{ISBN|978-0-9557360-4-9}}.</ref> Some sections of the plates\u2019 impressions are then highlighted by ink, whereas some sections are cut out altogether \u2013 some left purely as a trace.<ref name=\"ConversationWith\" /> 'These interventions take place separated from one another, yet may also intertwine. Through these perforations, the wall which is behind the deckle edged paper becomes a component of the work and takes on a bigger or smaller role depending on the size and quantity of perforations'.<ref name=Bildwerke /> Butcher refers to this register of trace in his paper works as speaking, metaphorically, of loss and absence.<ref>\u201dA Conversation With Jagjit Chuhan\u201d, p. 81. Centre for Art International Research, Liverpool, {{ISBN|978-0-9557360-4-9}}.</ref>\n\n==Exhibition History==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Selected Solo Exhibitions !! Gallery/Museum\n|-\n| 2020 || Sweet Heresy || Patrick Heide Contemporary Art, London\n|-\n| 2018 || Artificial Light || Nancy Toomey Fine Art, San Francisco, USA\n|-\n| 2015 || Data Capture || Patrick Heide Contemporary Art, London\n|-\n| 2013 || A Synthetic Kind of Love || Galerie Robert Drees, Hannover, Germany\n|-\n| 2010 || Material Witness || Toomey-Tourell gallery, San Francisco, USA\n|-\n| 2007 || Honey Trap || Toomey-Tourell gallery, San Francisco, USA\n|-\n| 2007 || Static Interference || Vertigo gallery, London\n|-\n| 2005 || Hanging Garden || Text + Work, the Art Institute at Bournemouth\n|-\n| 2005 || Arte Fiera || Vertigo gallery, Bologna, Italy\n|-\n| 2004 || Carbon Candy || Vertigo gallery, London \n|-\n| 2003 || Arcs + Surfaces || Vertigo gallery, London \n|-\n| 2002 || Cusp (two-person with Rebecca McLynn) || Sarah Myerscough Fine Art, London\n|-\n| 2000 || A Line of Enquiry || The Loading Bay, London\n|-\n| 1999 || The Antidote || The Loading Bay, London\n|-\n| 1997 || New Paintings || Concord Sylvania, London\n|-\n| 1997 || The Painted Figure (two-person with Gabriel Schmitz) || Hirschl Contemporary Art, London \n|-\n| 1995 || Lingering in Chambers of the Sea || The Acorn gallery, Liverpool\n|-\n| 1995 || New Paintings || Gallery 28, Reading\n|-\n| 1993 || Coming Up for Air || Engert Haus, Munich, Germany\n|-\n| 1991 || Beata Clarisa || Corpus Christi College, Cambridge\n|}\n\n=== Group Exhibitions ===\nEric Butcher has participated in many group shows including \"The Waterlilly Foundation\", [[Cambridge Guildhall]] (1994), \"The Genitals Are Beauty\", The House of William Blake, London (1995), \"The Art Experience\", The Atrium Gallery, London (1997), \"Wall to Wall\", Sarah Myerscough Fine Art, London (2002), \"Paperwork\" and \"30 x 30\", Vertigo Gallery, London (2003), \"Surface\", Vertigo Gallery (2004), the touring exhibition \"Definite Article\" with Roger Ackling, [[Marc Vaux]] and Cathy Wade, Vertigo gallery, London and Toomey-Tourell gallery, San Francisco, USA (2005/6), \"Meeting Place - Contemporary Art and the Museum Collection\", [[Russell-Cotes Art Gallery & Museum]], Bournemouth and the Arts Institute at Bournemouth (curated by Stephanie James & Jackie Serafopoulos) (2007), \"Underground\", [[Shoreditch]] Town Hall basement, London (three-person with Roger Ackling and Sim\u00f3n Granell) (2007), \"Ten\", Toomey-Tourell gallery, San Francisco, USA (2008), \"\u00dcber Fl\u00e4chen\", Galerie Robert Drees, Hannover, Germany (2010), \"Raw\", Pertwee, Anderson & Gold, London, (2011), \"Beyond the Commission\", The Gallery, Arts University College Bournemouth (2011), \"One Thing Leads to Another\", Portland House, Malvern (2011), \"The Devil Finds Work for Idle Hands\", Toomey-Tourell gallery, San Francisco, USA (2012), \"ReGroup\", Red Space, London (2012).\n\nRecent selected group exhibitions also include the touring exhibition \"A Machine Aesthetic\", Gallery North [[Northumbria University]], Newcastle; The Gallery, AUB, Bournemouth; Project Space Plus, University of Lincoln; The Gallery, Norwich University of the Arts; Transition Gallery, London, \"Down to Zero\", Patrick Heide Contemporary Art, London (curated by Michael Roberts), \"(Detail)\", H Project Space, Bangkok, Thailand; Usher Gallery, Lincoln; Transition gallery, London (curated by Andrew Bracey) (2014), \"An Einem Tisch - Contemporary Geometrical Abstraction\", Galerie Robert Drees, Hannover, Germany, \"Beyond Gravity II\", Galerie und Kunstcabinett Corona Unger, Bremen, Germany (2016), \"OVADA Seven Counties Open\", OVADA Warehouse, Oxford, \"The Jerwood Drawing Prize\", Jerwood Space, London, East Gallery, Norwich, The Edge, Bath, Sidney Cooper Gallery, Canterbury Vane Gallery, Newcastle-upon-Tyne, \"Mardi Gras Requiem\", Project Space Plus, Lincoln (2017), \"Intensity\", the House of St. Barnabas, London (curated by Paul Carey-Kent), \"Einsnullnull\", Galerie Robert Drees, Hannover, Germany (2018), \"Everything but Canvas\", Galerie Robert Drees, Hannover, Germany (2019), and \"Invited By\", Galerie Robert Drees, Hannover, Germany (2019/20).\n\n==Curating==\nButcher's creative practice has also embraced curating; initiating exhibitions/projects including Emission (2001), Definite Article (2005/6), Underground (2007), The Devil Finds Work for Idle Hands (2012) and A Machine Aesthetic (2013/14). A Machine Aesthetic (co-curated with Sim\u00f3n Granell), was a major national touring exhibition presenting the work of 11 contemporary British artists whose creative practices engaged with the concept of mechanisation. The exhibition explored the various manifestations, uses and influences of different aspects of mechanisation within the practices of an otherwise diverse group of artists (with [[Andrew Bracey]], Eric Butcher, David Connearn, Rob Currie, Paul Goodfellow, Sim\u00f3n Granell, [[Emma Hart (artist)]], Dan Hays, Natasha Kidd, Tim Knowles, Michael Roberts). In conjunction with the exhibition, the curators guest edited an edition of the arts and culture magazine Garageland (issue XVI: Machines)<ref>[https://www.transitiongallery.co.uk/htmlpages/editions/GL16/intro.htm \"Garageland: issue XVI: Machines\" {{ISSN|1749-9267}}.</ref>, which was themed to coincide with the show.\n\n\n==Further reading==\n*Butcher Shines at Toomey Tourell, Kenneth Baker, San Francisco Chronicle, pg. E - 1, March 13, 2010\n* Material Witness, Centre for Art International Research, Liverpool, {{ISBN|978-0-9557360-4-9}}. Text: Roy Exley, Eric Butcher & the Aluminium Works\n* Underground, Centre for Art International Research, Liverpool, {{ISBN|978-0-9552820-6-5}}. Texts: John Haldane, Underground; Lee Trimings, Loveslaves; Julie Sheldon, Process by Protocol; Tania Kovats, Digging.\n* Meeting Place, the Russell-Cotes Art Gallery & Museum, Bournemouth, in association with Text + Work, the Arts Institute at Bournemouth, {{ISBN|978-0-901196-20-0}}, Ed. Stephanie James & Les Buckingham. Texts inc. Eric Butcher, Discoveries\n* Art at More London, The LG collection of Contemporary art, London (collection catalogue), Ed. Margaret O\u2019Regan\n* Hanging Garden, Text + Work, the Arts Institute at Bournemouth, Bournemouth {{ISBN|0-901196-09-6}} (exhibition catalogue). Text, James Barron, Spaces, In, Out and Around\n* Definite Article, Vertigo Gallery, London, {{ISBN|1-903771-13-7}} (exhibition catalogue). Text: Eric Butcher, Objects and Surfaces. Essay reprinted (abridged) in Art & Architecture Journal, No. 63, Autumn 2005\n* Carbon Candy, Vertigo Gallery, London, {{ISBN|1-903771-12-9}} (exhibition catalogue). Text: William Packer, Untitled\n* Arcs + Surfaces, Vertigo Gallery, London, {{ISBN|1-903771-08-0}} (exhibition catalogue). Texts: Angela Kingston, New Paintings by Eric Butcher, Catherine Shearn, A Conversation with Eric Butcher.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.ericbutcher.com Eric Butcher website]\n*[http://www.toomey-tourell.com/artists/eric-butcher/ Eric Butcher at Toomey Tourell gallery]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20120823232622/http://www.galerie-robert-drees.de/index.php/drees/kuenstler/eric_butcher Eric Butcher at Galerie Robert Drees]\n*[https://www.patrickheide.com/artists/eric-butcher Eric Butcher at Patrick Heide Contemporary Art]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Butcher, Eric}}\n[[Category:20th-century English painters]]\n[[Category:English male painters]]\n[[Category:21st-century English painters]]\n[[Category:1970 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Singaporean emigrants to the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Corpus Christi College, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:People associated with Arts University Bournemouth]]\n", "name_user": "Barrettjonathan", "label": "safe", "comment": "grammar introduction", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eric_Butcher"}
{"title_page": "Elimelech of Lizhensk", "text_new": "{{Infobox rebbe\n| title           = Elimelech of Lezajsk\n| image           = Ohel Le\u017cajsk 01.jpg\n| caption         = Grave of Rabbi Elimelech of Lizhensk\n| birth_name       = Elimelech Weisblum\n| main_work       = Noam Elimelech\n| predecessor     = [[Dov Ber of Mezeritch]]\n| successor       = [[Yaakov Yitzchak of Lublin|Chozeh of Lublin]], [[Yisroel Hopsztajn|Yisroel of Kozhnitz]]\n| spouse = Shprintza,  Gittel\n| children          = Rabbi Elazar, Rabbi Eliezer Lipa, Reb Yaakov, Mirish, Esther - Ethel\n\n| dynasty     = Lizhensk\n| father          = Eliezer Lipman\n| mother          = Mirel dit Mirish\n| birth_date      = 1717\n| birth_place     = [[Tykocin]], [[Polish-Lithuanian Commonwealth|Kingdom of Poland]]\n| death_date      = March 11, 1787\n| death_place     = [[Le\u017cajsk]], [[Kingdom of Galicia and Lodomeria]]\n| place of burial = Le\u017cajsk, [[Poland]]\n|\n}}\n\n'''Elimelech Weisblum of Lizhensk''' (1717\u2013March 11, 1787<ref>See image of gravestone at e.g. http://2.bp.blogspot.com/_fTh0xyZ1FRQ/R-rEbh5TgVI/AAAAAAAABA4/h3023o7lqXI/s400/elimelech.jpg which gives the year as \u05ea' \u05e0' \u05e6' \u05d1' \u05d4' which is 547, short for the Jewish year 5,547, or 1787.</ref>) was a [[rabbi]] and one of the great founding [[Rebbe]]s of the [[Hasidic Judaism|Hasidic movement]]. He was known after his hometown, [[Le\u017cajsk]] ({{lang-yi|\u05dc\u05d9\u05d6\u05e9\u05e2\u05e0\u05e1\u05e7|translit=Lizhensk}}) near [[Rzesz\u00f3w]] in [[Poland]]. He was part of the inner \"Chevraya Kadisha\" (Holy Society) school of the [[Maggid]] Rebbe [[Dov Ber of Mezeritch]] (second leader of the Hasidic movement), who became the decentralised, third generation leadership after the passing of Rebbe Dov Ber in 1772. Their dissemination to new areas of [[Eastern Europe]] led the movement's rapid revivalist expansion.\n\nRebbi Elimelech authored the classic [[Hasidic philosophy|work]] ''Noam Elimelech''. It developed the Hasidic theory of the [[Tzaddik]] into the full doctrine of \"''Practical/Popular Tzaddikism''\". This shaped the social role of [[Ayin and Yesh|mystical]] [[Rebbe|leadership]], characteristic of the \"''Mainstream Hasidic''\" path. He was the founder of Hasidism in [[Poland]]-[[Galicia (Eastern Europe)|Galicia]], and numerous leaders and [[Hasidic dynasties|dynasties]] emerged from his disciples in the early 19th century, including the [[Chozeh of Lublin]], the [[Maggid of Koznitz]] and [[Menachem Mendel of Rimanov]], one of the three \"Fathers of Polish Hasidism\". Because of this, Rebbi Elimelech is venerated by the \"Mainstream\" path in Hasidism, predominant especially in Poland, who descend from his influence.\n\n==Biography==\nRebbe Elimelech was born in [[Galicia (Central Europe)|Galicia]] (Central Europe), which was located in the Kingdom of Poland that was part of the [[Polish-Lithuanian Commonwealth]]. He died in [[Le\u017cajsk]] on the 21st of [[Adar]]. He was known as a [[Tzadik]] who devoted his life to studying and teaching the [[Torah]], as well as encouraging people to draw closer in return to God.\n\n===The brothers Rabbi Elimelech and Reb Zushya===\nRebbe Elimelech was a prominent student of the [[Dovber of Mezeritch|Maggid of Mezeritch]], and was brought under his tutelage by his brother the famous Rebbe Reb [[Meshulam Zushya of Anipoli]]. Both brothers are central figures in Hasidic tradition and Reb Zushya is especially beloved for his sincerity and fervour. The two offered a contrast in the model of the Hasidic [[Rebbe]], with Elimelech the ascetic scholar, and Zushya giving the impression of the charismatic \"saintly simpleton\", although he too was well versed in [[Hasidic philosophy]]. Of all the students in the Maggid's \"Holy Society\" it is told that only Zushya could contain his [[dveikus]] (fervour) and remain in the room as the Maggid revealed fiery new teachings. The other students would faint or run out of the room in ecstasy.<ref>Cited in ''The Great Maggid'' by [[Jacob Immanuel Schochet]]. Kehot Publications</ref> The two brothers would travel together in mystical exile of [[Teshuvah|repentance]] to atone on behalf of the whole Jewish people and the exile of the [[Shechinah]] (Divine Presence). Famous Hasidic tales are told of their encounters.\n<blockquote>\nOn one occasion, Rabbi Elimelech and Reb Zushya were staying at an inn. Each night, gentile peasants would enter their room and jestingly beat the one who lay nearest the fireside, Reb Zushya. One night, Rabbi Elimelech offered to change places with his brother so that he could take the beatings instead. Suggesting that Reb Zushya had suffered enough of this \"Divine admonishment\", the agreement was made and Rabbi Elimelech lay next to the fire instead. That night, the common gentiles again entered to begin their jest. This time, however, one of them said that the one by the fire had taken his fair share of the treatment, and now it would be better to jest with the other one! Again Reb Zushya took the beatings. Afterwards, he told his brother that whatever is decided in Heaven transpires!\n</blockquote>\n\n===Hasidic Leadership===\nAfter the death of the [[Dovber of Mezeritch|Maggid of Mezeritch]], the Hasidic movement avoided one centralised leader, as had characterised it under the [[Baal Shem Tov]] and the Maggid. Instead the great leadership of students of the Maggid dispersed across Eastern Europe, from Poland to Russia, taking with them their different interpretations of Hasidism. Nonetheless, in this third generation, Rabbi Elimelech was considered by most of the Maggid's students and followers as his successor. He began the dissemination of Hasidism in Poland, which subsequently increased to a much greater extent under his foremost disciple, the [[Yaakov Yitzchak of Lublin|Chozeh of Lublin]].\n\nMany of Rebbe Elimelech's students (talmidim) went on to be Rebbes in their own right. The most famous are the [[Chozeh of Lublin]], Rebbe [[Menachem Mendel of Rimanov]], the [[Kozhnitzer Maggid]], the [[Apter Rov]] and Rabbi [[Kalonymus Kalman Epstein|Kalonymus Kalman Halevi Epstein]], author of ''Maor Vashemesh''.\n\nTo this day his grave in [[Le\u017cajsk]], [[Poland]], is visited by thousands of those faithful to Hasidism, particularly on the anniversary of his death, the 21st of the Hebrew month of [[Adar]] (in leap years, commemorated twice, in Adar I and Adar II).<ref>David M. Gitlitz & Linda Kay Davidson \u2018\u2019Pilgrimage and the Jews\u2019\u2019 (Westport: CT: Praeger, 2006), 112-115.</ref> In 2012, approximately 6,000 pilgrims <ref>http://www.rp.pl/artykul/10,838345-Chasydzi-pielgrzymuja-do-grobu-cadyka.html</ref> came to visit the site on the anniversary coming from Israel, Ukraine, Hungary, Germany, Holland, France, Great Britain, Canada and the USA.<ref>http://www.nowiny24.pl/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20120315/LEZAJSK/120319740</ref> In most Chasidic [[minyan]]im, [[Tachanun]] is omitted on the Noam Elimelech's [[Bereavement in Judaism#Annual remembrances|Yartzeit]].<ref>See {{cite web |url=http://woodstocktom.com/2009/12/everything-you-wanted-to-know-about-tachanun/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-03-08 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110718081857/http://woodstocktom.com/2009/12/everything-you-wanted-to-know-about-tachanun/ |archivedate=2011-07-18 }}</ref>\n\nIt is said that when Rebbe Elimelech came before the heavenly tribunal, he stated that \"unfortunately, I didn't pray or learn Torah\", the judge then proclaimed \"if so then you have to be taken to hell!\", the angels carried Rebbe Elimelech to what he thought was [[Hell]] but was really [[Heaven]], Rebbe Elimelech then said \"How merciful is our [[Father in heaven]], He made hell so good, just imagine what heaven must be like!\"\n\n==Noam Elimelech==\nAs is common amongst great Rabbis, he is most commonly known by the name of his popular book ''Noam Elimelech'', a commentary on the Torah. This book is one of the principal works of [[Hasidism]]. The sefer was called ''Sefer Shel Tzadikim'', (a Book for the Righteous) by Rabbi [[Shneur Zalman of Liadi]] (founder of the [[Lubavitch]] dynasty).\n\nThe book has asterisks or stars placed in seemingly random places over words.  Tradition has it that these stars have some meaning. In ''Devarim Areivim'' (another [[Hasidic]] classic), the author, Rabbi Dov Ehrmann, wrote: \"In the first edition of the sefer, there are in many places small stars which allude to some secret meaning\". The [[Klausenberg (Hasidic dynasty)|Klausenberger]] [[Rebbe]] once said that the stars in the heavens are a commentary to the stars in the book ''Noam Elimelech''. As such, all subsequent printings have included these stars.\n\nRabbi Elimelech also wrote ''Tzetl Koton'', a seventeen-point program on how to be a good Jew, and ''Hanhagos HaAdam'', a list of [[Minhag|customs]] for all pious Jews to follow.\n\n===Three Hasidic mystical paths===\n[[Image:Lizhenskgrave.jpg|thumb|200px|right|The [[Biala (Hasidic dynasty)|Biala]] Rebbe of America praying in the [[Ohel (grave)|Ohel]] of Rabbi Elimelech. His grave is venerated in pilgrimage by \"Mainstream\"-Polish [[Hasidic dynasties|dynasties]] and their followers, as their spiritual path in Hasidism descends from his influence]]\nA Hasidic aphorism<ref>In ''Transforming Darkness into Light: Kabbalah and Psychology'' (Teachings of Kabbalah Series), [[Yitzchak Ginsburgh]], Gal Einai Pub.</ref> describes three paths of mysticism in the Hasidic movement, formed by three works of Hasidic thought. [[Nachman of Breslov]]'s ''Likkutei Moharan'' is described as the Hasidic book of the great, giving hope and encouragement to those trapped in problems, through Rabbi Nachman's innovative creativity and the personal [[Hitbodedut|articulation]] of one's problems to God. [[Schneur Zalman of Liadi]]'s ''[[Tanya]]'' is subtitled the Hasidic book for the intermediate person, who has ease to intellectually [[Hisbonenus|contemplate]] and internalise [[Hasidic thought]], free from distracting troubles. In this [[Habad]] path, the Tzadik's primary role is to teach the esoteric dimension of Hasidism in intellectual understanding. ''Noam Elimelech'' is seen as the formative book of the righteous [[Tzadik]]. It instructs select people of spiritual ability how to become Hasidic mystical leaders, while advocating attachment to the Tzadik by the common folk. Because of this, ''Noam Elimelech'' influenced the Mainstream Hasidic proliferation of the Tzadik, who embodies and channels the [[Ayin and Yesh|Ayin-Yesh]] Divine flow of blessing to this world. The [[Chozeh of Lublin]] (1745-1815) developed further the dynamics of this process. Meanwhile, the mid-19th century [[Simcha Bunim of Peshischa|Peshischa]]-[[Menachem Mendel of Kotzk|Kotzk]] spiritual development in Hasidism and its influence, is excluded from this description. It left aside ''Tzaddikism'' and mystical focus in favour of personal autonomy, introspection and Rabbinic [[Torah study]] in the spirit of Hasidic spiritual inwardness. The ''Yid HaKodosh'' of [[Przysucha]] in Poland began this trend when he broke away from the Chozeh of Lublin's Tzadik focused spiritual path.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://lizensk.com ''Rabbi Elimelech of Lizhensk'' ]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080612150258/http://www.jnul.huji.ac.il/dl/books/html/bk1194026.htm ''Digitized 1st Edition Hebrew Noam Elimelech'']\n* [https://he.wikisource.org/wiki/%D7%A0%D7%95%D7%A2%D7%9D_%D7%90%D7%9C%D7%99%D7%9E%D7%9C%D7%9A ''Noam Elimelech text on Hebrew Wikisource'']\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080514125433/http://www.targum.com/files/zweckersampler.pdf ''Noam Elimelech in English samples'']\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080511213206/http://www.targum.com/files/zweckerprayer.pdf ''Tefilah Kodem HaTefillah'']\n* [http://770live.com/En770/nigunim/nigunPlay.asp?nigunId=Dovid_Hurwitz/212.rm&gif=212 A Hassidic Tune attributed to Rabbi Elimelech of Lizensk]\n* [http://www.chassidusonline.com/noam-elimelech-article-mishpacha.pdf ''Rebbe Elimelech Stories'']\n* [http://www.hebrewbooks.org/3933 ''Ohel Elimelech Hebrew Tales about Rebbe Elimelech'']\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-rel|jw}}\n{{Succession box| before= [[Dov Ber of Mezeritch|Magid of Mezritsh]] | title=Hasidic Rebbes| years=1772\u20131786 | after=[[Yaakov Yitzchak of Lublin|Chozeh of Lublin]], Rabbi [[Yisroel Hopsztajn|Yisroel of Kozhnitz]]}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Elimelech Of Lezhinsk}}\n[[Category:1717 births]]\n[[Category:1787 deaths]]\n[[Category:18th-century rabbis]]\n[[Category:Hasidic rebbes]]\n[[Category:Hasidic rabbis in Europe]]\n[[Category:Jews from Galicia (Eastern Europe)]]\n[[Category:Polish Orthodox rabbis]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox rebbe\n| title           = Elimelech of Lezajsk\n| image           = Ohel Le\u017cajsk 01.jpg\n| caption         = [[kever (grave)]] of Rabbi Elimelech of Lizhensk\n| birth_name       = Elimelech Weisblum\n| main_work       = Noam Elimelech\n| predecessor     = [[Dov Ber of Mezeritch]]\n| successor       = [[Yaakov Yitzchak of Lublin|Chozeh of Lublin]], [[Yisroel Hopsztajn|Yisroel of Kozhnitz]]\n| spouse = Shprintza,  Gittel\n| children          = Rabbi Elazar, Rabbi Eliezer Lipa, Reb Yaakov, Mirish, Esther - Ethel\n\n| dynasty     = Lizhensk\n| father          = Eliezer Lipman\n| mother          = Mirel dit Mirish\n| birth_date      = 1717\n| birth_place     = [[Tykocin]], [[Polish-Lithuanian Commonwealth|Kingdom of Poland]]\n| death_date      = March 11, 1787\n| death_place     = [[Le\u017cajsk]], [[Kingdom of Galicia and Lodomeria]]\n| place of burial = Le\u017cajsk, [[Poland]]\n|\n}}\n\n'''Elimelech Weisblum of Lizhensk''' (1717\u2013March 11, 1787<ref>See image of gravestone at e.g. http://2.bp.blogspot.com/_fTh0xyZ1FRQ/R-rEbh5TgVI/AAAAAAAABA4/h3023o7lqXI/s400/elimelech.jpg which gives the year as \u05ea' \u05e0' \u05e6' \u05d1' \u05d4' which is 547, short for the Jewish year 5,547, or 1787.</ref>) was a [[rabbi]] and one of the great founding [[Rebbe]]s of the [[Hasidic Judaism|Hasidic movement]]. He was known after his hometown, [[Le\u017cajsk]] ({{lang-yi|\u05dc\u05d9\u05d6\u05e9\u05e2\u05e0\u05e1\u05e7|translit=Lizhensk}}) near [[Rzesz\u00f3w]] in [[Poland]]. He was part of the inner \"Chevraya Kadisha\" (Holy Society) school of the [[Maggid]] Rebbe [[Dov Ber of Mezeritch]] (second leader of the Hasidic movement), who became the decentralised, third generation leadership after the passing of Rebbe Dov Ber in 1772. Their dissemination to new areas of [[Eastern Europe]] led the movement's rapid revivalist expansion.\n\nRebbi Elimelech authored the classic [[Hasidic philosophy|work]] ''Noam Elimelech''. It developed the Hasidic theory of the [[Tzaddik]] into the full doctrine of \"''Practical/Popular Tzaddikism''\". This shaped the social role of [[Ayin and Yesh|mystical]] [[Rebbe|leadership]], characteristic of the \"''Mainstream Hasidic''\" path. He was the founder of Hasidism in [[Poland]]-[[Galicia (Eastern Europe)|Galicia]], and numerous leaders and [[Hasidic dynasties|dynasties]] emerged from his disciples in the early 19th century, including the [[Chozeh of Lublin]], the [[Maggid of Koznitz]] and [[Menachem Mendel of Rimanov]], one of the three \"Fathers of Polish Hasidism\". Because of this, Rebbi Elimelech is venerated by the \"Mainstream\" path in Hasidism, predominant especially in Poland, who descend from his influence.\n\n==Biography==\nRebbe Elimelech was born in [[Galicia (Central Europe)|Galicia]] (Central Europe), which was located in the Kingdom of Poland that was part of the [[Polish-Lithuanian Commonwealth]]. He died in [[Le\u017cajsk]] on the 21st of [[Adar]]. He was known as a [[Tzadik]] who devoted his life to studying and teaching the [[Torah]], as well as encouraging people to draw closer in return to God.\n\n===The brothers Rabbi Elimelech and Reb Zushya===\nRebbe Elimelech was a prominent student of the [[Dovber of Mezeritch|Maggid of Mezeritch]], and was brought under his tutelage by his brother the famous Rebbe Reb [[Meshulam Zushya of Anipoli]]. Both brothers are central figures in Hasidic tradition and Reb Zushya is especially beloved for his sincerity and fervour. The two offered a contrast in the model of the Hasidic [[Rebbe]], with Elimelech the ascetic scholar, and Zushya giving the impression of the charismatic \"saintly simpleton\", although he too was well versed in [[Hasidic philosophy]]. Of all the students in the Maggid's \"Holy Society\" it is told that only Zushya could contain his [[dveikus]] (fervour) and remain in the room as the Maggid revealed fiery new teachings. The other students would faint or run out of the room in ecstasy.<ref>Cited in ''The Great Maggid'' by [[Jacob Immanuel Schochet]]. Kehot Publications</ref> The two brothers would travel together in mystical exile of [[Teshuvah|repentance]] to atone on behalf of the whole Jewish people and the exile of the [[Shechinah]] (Divine Presence). Famous Hasidic tales are told of their encounters.\n<blockquote>\nOn one occasion, Rabbi Elimelech and Reb Zushya were staying at an inn. Each night, gentile peasants would enter their room and jestingly beat the one who lay nearest the fireside, Reb Zushya. One night, Rabbi Elimelech offered to change places with his brother so that he could take the beatings instead. Suggesting that Reb Zushya had suffered enough of this \"Divine admonishment\", the agreement was made and Rabbi Elimelech lay next to the fire instead. That night, the common gentiles again entered to begin their jest. This time, however, one of them said that the one by the fire had taken his fair share of the treatment, and now it would be better to jest with the other one! Again Reb Zushya took the beatings. Afterwards, he told his brother that whatever is decided in Heaven transpires!\n</blockquote>\n\n===Hasidic Leadership===\nAfter the death of the [[Dovber of Mezeritch|Maggid of Mezeritch]], the Hasidic movement avoided one centralised leader, as had characterised it under the [[Baal Shem Tov]] and the Maggid. Instead the great leadership of students of the Maggid dispersed across Eastern Europe, from Poland to Russia, taking with them their different interpretations of Hasidism. Nonetheless, in this third generation, Rabbi Elimelech was considered by most of the Maggid's students and followers as his successor. He began the dissemination of Hasidism in Poland, which subsequently increased to a much greater extent under his foremost disciple, the [[Yaakov Yitzchak of Lublin|Chozeh of Lublin]].\n\nMany of Rebbe Elimelech's students (talmidim) went on to be Rebbes in their own right. The most famous are the [[Chozeh of Lublin]], Rebbe [[Menachem Mendel of Rimanov]], the [[Kozhnitzer Maggid]], the [[Apter Rov]] and Rabbi [[Kalonymus Kalman Epstein|Kalonymus Kalman Halevi Epstein]], author of ''Maor Vashemesh''.\n\nTo this day his grave in [[Le\u017cajsk]], [[Poland]], is visited by thousands of those faithful to Hasidism, particularly on the anniversary of his death, the 21st of the Hebrew month of [[Adar]] (in leap years, commemorated twice, in Adar I and Adar II).<ref>David M. Gitlitz & Linda Kay Davidson \u2018\u2019Pilgrimage and the Jews\u2019\u2019 (Westport: CT: Praeger, 2006), 112-115.</ref> In 2012, approximately 6,000 pilgrims <ref>http://www.rp.pl/artykul/10,838345-Chasydzi-pielgrzymuja-do-grobu-cadyka.html</ref> came to visit the site on the anniversary coming from Israel, Ukraine, Hungary, Germany, Holland, France, Great Britain, Canada and the USA.<ref>http://www.nowiny24.pl/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20120315/LEZAJSK/120319740</ref> In most Chasidic [[minyan]]im, [[Tachanun]] is omitted on the Noam Elimelech's [[Bereavement in Judaism#Annual remembrances|Yartzeit]].<ref>See {{cite web |url=http://woodstocktom.com/2009/12/everything-you-wanted-to-know-about-tachanun/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-03-08 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110718081857/http://woodstocktom.com/2009/12/everything-you-wanted-to-know-about-tachanun/ |archivedate=2011-07-18 }}</ref>\n\nIt is said that when Rebbe Elimelech came before the heavenly tribunal, he stated that \"unfortunately, I didn't pray or learn Torah\", the judge then proclaimed \"if so then you have to be taken to hell!\", the angels carried Rebbe Elimelech to what he thought was [[Hell]] but was really [[Heaven]], Rebbe Elimelech then said \"How merciful is our [[Father in heaven]], He made hell so good, just imagine what heaven must be like!\"\n\n==Noam Elimelech==\nAs is common amongst great Rabbis, he is most commonly known by the name of his popular book ''Noam Elimelech'', a commentary on the Torah. This book is one of the principal works of [[Hasidism]]. The sefer was called ''Sefer Shel Tzadikim'', (a Book for the Righteous) by Rabbi [[Shneur Zalman of Liadi]] (founder of the [[Lubavitch]] dynasty).\n\nThe book has asterisks or stars placed in seemingly random places over words.  Tradition has it that these stars have some meaning. In ''Devarim Areivim'' (another [[Hasidic]] classic), the author, Rabbi Dov Ehrmann, wrote: \"In the first edition of the sefer, there are in many places small stars which allude to some secret meaning\". The [[Klausenberg (Hasidic dynasty)|Klausenberger]] [[Rebbe]] once said that the stars in the heavens are a commentary to the stars in the book ''Noam Elimelech''. As such, all subsequent printings have included these stars.\n\nRabbi Elimelech also wrote ''Tzetl Koton'', a seventeen-point program on how to be a good Jew, and ''Hanhagos HaAdam'', a list of [[Minhag|customs]] for all pious Jews to follow.\n\n===Three Hasidic mystical paths===\n[[Image:Lizhenskgrave.jpg|thumb|200px|right|The [[Biala (Hasidic dynasty)|Biala]] Rebbe of America praying in the [[Ohel (grave)|Ohel]] of Rabbi Elimelech. His grave is venerated in pilgrimage by \"Mainstream\"-Polish [[Hasidic dynasties|dynasties]] and their followers, as their spiritual path in Hasidism descends from his influence]]\nA Hasidic aphorism<ref>In ''Transforming Darkness into Light: Kabbalah and Psychology'' (Teachings of Kabbalah Series), [[Yitzchak Ginsburgh]], Gal Einai Pub.</ref> describes three paths of mysticism in the Hasidic movement, formed by three works of Hasidic thought. [[Nachman of Breslov]]'s ''Likkutei Moharan'' is described as the Hasidic book of the great, giving hope and encouragement to those trapped in problems, through Rabbi Nachman's innovative creativity and the personal [[Hitbodedut|articulation]] of one's problems to God. [[Schneur Zalman of Liadi]]'s ''[[Tanya]]'' is subtitled the Hasidic book for the intermediate person, who has ease to intellectually [[Hisbonenus|contemplate]] and internalise [[Hasidic thought]], free from distracting troubles. In this [[Habad]] path, the Tzadik's primary role is to teach the esoteric dimension of Hasidism in intellectual understanding. ''Noam Elimelech'' is seen as the formative book of the righteous [[Tzadik]]. It instructs select people of spiritual ability how to become Hasidic mystical leaders, while advocating attachment to the Tzadik by the common folk. Because of this, ''Noam Elimelech'' influenced the Mainstream Hasidic proliferation of the Tzadik, who embodies and channels the [[Ayin and Yesh|Ayin-Yesh]] Divine flow of blessing to this world. The [[Chozeh of Lublin]] (1745-1815) developed further the dynamics of this process. Meanwhile, the mid-19th century [[Simcha Bunim of Peshischa|Peshischa]]-[[Menachem Mendel of Kotzk|Kotzk]] spiritual development in Hasidism and its influence, is excluded from this description. It left aside ''Tzaddikism'' and mystical focus in favour of personal autonomy, introspection and Rabbinic [[Torah study]] in the spirit of Hasidic spiritual inwardness. The ''Yid HaKodosh'' of [[Przysucha]] in Poland began this trend when he broke away from the Chozeh of Lublin's Tzadik focused spiritual path.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://lizensk.com ''Rabbi Elimelech of Lizhensk'' ]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080612150258/http://www.jnul.huji.ac.il/dl/books/html/bk1194026.htm ''Digitized 1st Edition Hebrew Noam Elimelech'']\n* [https://he.wikisource.org/wiki/%D7%A0%D7%95%D7%A2%D7%9D_%D7%90%D7%9C%D7%99%D7%9E%D7%9C%D7%9A ''Noam Elimelech text on Hebrew Wikisource'']\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080514125433/http://www.targum.com/files/zweckersampler.pdf ''Noam Elimelech in English samples'']\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080511213206/http://www.targum.com/files/zweckerprayer.pdf ''Tefilah Kodem HaTefillah'']\n* [http://770live.com/En770/nigunim/nigunPlay.asp?nigunId=Dovid_Hurwitz/212.rm&gif=212 A Hassidic Tune attributed to Rabbi Elimelech of Lizensk]\n* [http://www.chassidusonline.com/noam-elimelech-article-mishpacha.pdf ''Rebbe Elimelech Stories'']\n* [http://www.hebrewbooks.org/3933 ''Ohel Elimelech Hebrew Tales about Rebbe Elimelech'']\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-rel|jw}}\n{{Succession box| before= [[Dov Ber of Mezeritch|Magid of Mezritsh]] | title=Hasidic Rebbes| years=1772\u20131786 | after=[[Yaakov Yitzchak of Lublin|Chozeh of Lublin]], Rabbi [[Yisroel Hopsztajn|Yisroel of Kozhnitz]]}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Elimelech Of Lezhinsk}}\n[[Category:1717 births]]\n[[Category:1787 deaths]]\n[[Category:18th-century rabbis]]\n[[Category:Hasidic rebbes]]\n[[Category:Hasidic rabbis in Europe]]\n[[Category:Jews from Galicia (Eastern Europe)]]\n[[Category:Polish Orthodox rabbis]]\n", "name_user": "Oliszydlowski", "label": "safe", "comment": "no link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elimelech_of_Lizhensk"}
{"title_page": "List of major crimes in Singapore", "text_new": "{{Inc-up|date=April 2019}}\n{{use Singapore English|date=August 2019}}\n{{short description|wikimedia list article}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2019}}\n\nThe following is a list of '''major [[Crime in Singapore|crimes in Singapore]]'''. They are arranged in chronological order.\n\nMajor crimes such as homicide, kidnapping, firearm-related, aggravated sexual crime like rape and sexual assault by penetration, bomb and explosive-related and other major sensitive crimes are investigated by Major Crime Division of [[Criminal Investigation Department (Singapore)|Criminal Investigation Department (CID)]] in the [[Singapore Police Force]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.police.gov.sg/about-us/organisational-structure/specialist-staff-departments/criminal-investigation-department|title=Specialist Staff Departments|website=Singapore Police Force|language=en|access-date=2019-04-06|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190120143100/https://www.police.gov.sg/about-us/organisational-structure/specialist-staff-departments/criminal-investigation-department|archive-date=20 January 2019|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Drug-related crimes like drug trafficking are handled by the [[Central Narcotics Bureau]]. White-collar crimes like fraud and misappropriation of finances are handled by the [[Commercial Affairs Department]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.police.gov.sg/about-us/organisational-structure/specialist-staff-departments/commercial-affairs-department|title=Specialist Staff Departments|website=Singapore Police Force|language=en|access-date=2019-10-16}}</ref> while corruption offences are under the purview of the [[Corrupt Practices Investigation Bureau]]. Criminals which are of concern to the national security of Singapore are firmly dealt with by the [[Internal Security Department (Singapore)|Internal Security Department]] via the [[Internal Security Act (Singapore)|Internal Security Act]] and other laws.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mha.gov.sg/isd/about-isd|title=About ISD|website=Ministry of Home Affairs|language=en|access-date=2019-10-17}}</ref>\n\n==1960s==\n\n===1963===\n* 12 July 1963: detainees at the prison on [[Pulau Senang]] started a riot and killed prison officer Daniel Stanley Dutton and three of his assistants. 64 were accused of murder and rioiting. After a five-month-long trial, 18 men were convicted of murder and hanged in Changi Prison on 29 October 1965. Another 29 men were also found guilty of rioting.<ref>{{cite web|last=Cornelius-Takahama|first=Vernon|url=http://infopedia.nl.sg/articles/SIP_728_2005-01-19.html|title=Pulau Senang|publisher=National Library Board, Singapore|date=2001|accessdate=20 November 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130313050528/http://infopedia.nl.sg/articles/SIP_728_2005-01-19.html|archivedate=13 March 2013}}</ref>\n* 27 August 1963: Sunny Ang Soo Kuan allegedly murdered his girlfriend, Jenny Cheok Cheng Kid, during a scuba-diving trip in the straits between [[Sisters' Islands]]. He was found guilty in a jury trial, sentenced to death, and hanged on 6 February 1967.<ref name=\"straitstimes.com\">{{cite news|title=Guilty As Charged: Sunny Ang found guilty of girlfriend's murder though body was never found|url=http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/guilty-as-charged-sunny-ang-found-guilty-of-girlfriends-murder-though-body|newspaper=The Straits Times|location=Singapore|date=16 May 2016|accessdate=16 May 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160516050602/http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/guilty-as-charged-sunny-ang-found-guilty-of-girlfriends-murder-though-body|archive-date=2016-05-16|url-status=live}}</ref> Cheok's body was never found.<ref>{{cite web|author1=Jasli, Tettyana|author2=Chew, Valerie|url=http://infopedia.nl.sg/articles/SIP_1789_2011-09-26.html|title=The Sunny Ang murder case|publisher=National Library Board, Singapore|accessdate=20 November 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130102145524/http://infopedia.nl.sg/articles/SIP_1789_2011-09-26.html|archivedate=2 January 2013}}</ref>\n\n'''1968'''\n\n*24 May 1968: 19-year-old Ong Beang Leck was last seen alive by his father as he left his father's shop. Later on, Ong's father received two separate phone calls on 26 May and 5 June in which the caller claimed he had kidnapped Ong and demanded a ransom from the elder Ong to free his son. A ransom of $20000 was eventually negotiated and paid, but still, there was no sign of Ong. A week after the ransom was paid, a rental car owner found one of the cars he rented out three weeks before had a foul-smelling odour. Tests revealed that the smell was that of blood. The person who last rented the car was found to be 24-year-old Richard Lai Chun Seng. Lai confessed that he, along with four others, was part of a kidnapping, in which the victim was none other than the missing youth Ong Beang Leck. Lai also stated that he took part in the plan as he needed money to save his failing business, and that he thought the plan was to lure Ong into the rental car, render the youth unconscious and held him hostage until the ransom was paid; however, on the night of 25 June 1968, as soon as Ong entered the car, Lai was shocked to see the three of his four other accomplices taking out weapons he was unaware of and attacked Ong, which led to the boy's death. This relevation led to the arrest of the other four accomplices; one of them was Ong's 24-year-old close friend Lee Chor Pet, the others were 29-year-old Chow Sien Cheong, 32-year-old Lim Kim Kwee, and 23-year-old Ho Kee Fatt (the latter two had ran off to Malaysia before their arrest by the Royal Malaysian Police). Lee led the police to a manhole in Jurong, where Ong's highly decomposed body was found. Lee, Lim and Ho, who were the three people assaulting Ong right from the back of the car, were charged with the murder of the youth. The three were found guilty of murder and sentenced to death on 11 June 1970, and all the three men were hanged on 27 January 1973. Lai, who became the prosecution's main witness, was subsequently jailed for 4 years for his involvement in both the ransom negotiation and the abduction of Ong. For possessing the ransom money, Chow was also given a 4-year jail sentence as well.\n\n==1970s==\n\n===1970===\n* 6 January 1970: 31-year-old dance hostess Mimi Wong Weng Siu (\u9ec4\u5a49\u79c0) and 37-year-old sweeper Sim Woh Kum (\u51bc\u677e\u9526) in late 1969 were convicted of murder of a Mrs Watanabe and sentenced to death on 7 December 1970. Wong became the first woman to receive the capital punishment from a Singapore court.<ref>{{cite news|title=Guilty As Charged: Dance hostess Mimi Wong murdered her Japanese lover\u2019s wife|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/guilty-as-charged-dance-hostess-mimi-wong-murdered-her-japanese-lovers-wife|newspaper=The Straits Times|location=Singapore|date=14 May 2016|accessdate=14 May 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160517103525/http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/guilty-as-charged-dance-hostess-mimi-wong-murdered-her-japanese-lovers-wife|archive-date=2016-05-17|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===1971===\n* 29 December 1971: Businessman Ngo Cheng Poh and two of his employees were killed by a group of 10 men, who also robbed them of 120 gold bars. All were charged with murder.<ref>{{cite news|title=Guilty As Charged: Seven who killed for 120 gold bars hanged|url=http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/guilty-as-charged-seven-who-killed-for-120-gold-bars-hanged|newspaper=The Straits Times|location=Singapore|date=16 May 2016|accessdate=16 May 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160516054911/http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/guilty-as-charged-seven-who-killed-for-120-gold-bars-hanged|archive-date=2016-05-16|url-status=live}}</ref> Seven of the ten men were convicted of murder and hanged on 28 February 1975 while the remaining three were put under indefinite detention.<ref>{{cite web|last=Tok|first=Cherylyn|url=http://infopedia.nl.sg/articles/SIP_1753_2011-02-14.html|title=Gold Bar Murders|publisher=National Library Board, Singapore|accessdate=20 November 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130313045835/http://infopedia.nl.sg/articles/SIP_1753_2011-02-14.html|archivedate=13 March 2013}}</ref>\n\n===1972===\n* 18 September 1972: A 22-year-old seamstress Cheng Li Zhen was walking along [[Queenstown, Singapore|Queenstown]] with her sister when she suddenly screamed and collapsed to the ground with blood oozing out from her chest. It was only after she was in the hospital that they found that it was a gunshot wound. She never regained consciousness and died in the hospital soon after. The case remains unsolved.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Mystery of Queenstown 1972{{!}}My Queenstown|url = http://goodmorningyesterday.blogspot.sg/2009/04/mysterious-shooting-incident-in.html|website = myqueenstown.blogspot.sg|accessdate = 2015-10-18|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150924012522/http://goodmorningyesterday.blogspot.sg/2009/04/mysterious-shooting-incident-in.html|archive-date = 2015-09-24|url-status = live}}</ref>\n* 24 November 1972: Gunman Lim Ban Lim, who killed 27-year-old Corporal Koh Chong Thye on 23 June 1968, was ambushed by police officers in the vicinity of Block 6 near Golden City Theatre. Officers shot Lim three times in his body in a fire fight, killing Lim. His aide Chua Ah Kow shot himself dead during a gunfight three weeks later at Tank Road.<ref>{{cite news|title=Guilty As Charged: Lim Ban Lim was most wanted gunman in Singapore and Malaysia in 1960s|url=http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/guilty-as-charged-lim-ban-lim-was-most-wanted-gunman-in-singapore-and|newspaper=The Straits Times|location=Singapore|date=16 May 2016|accessdate=16 May 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160515114826/http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/guilty-as-charged-lim-ban-lim-was-most-wanted-gunman-in-singapore-and|archive-date=2016-05-15|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===1974===\n* 9 May 1974: 44-year-old Sim Joo Keow strangled her 53-year-old sister-in-law Quek Lee Eng over $2,000, before dismembering her body and keeping her torso in two earthen jars in her home. Quek's head and arms were found in a parcel near the Kallang River bank. Sim was sentenced to 10 years in jail in January 1975, after being convicted of manslaughter and hiding evidence.<ref>{{cite news|title=Guilty As Charged: Sim Joo Keow strangled sister-in-law, chopped up her body|url=http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/guilty-as-charged-sim-joo-keow-strangled-sister-in-law-chopped-up-her-body|newspaper=The Straits Times|location=Singapore|date=16 May 2016|accessdate=16 May 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160515105714/http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/guilty-as-charged-sim-joo-keow-strangled-sister-in-law-chopped-up-her-body|archive-date=2016-05-15|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===1975===\n* July 1975: District Judge E.C. Foenander sentenced Suhaymi Harith, 40, Khalil Mohammed Dol, 39, Wassan Sakeebun, 45, and Wagiman Abdullah, 47 a total of 64 years in jail plus 144 strokes of the cane. All four pleaded guilty to 228 charges of housebreaking, robbery and theft committed between 5 January 1973 and 13 June 1975.<ref>{{cite news|title=Guilty As Charged: Serial robbers, dressed in only their swimming trunks, terrorised residents|url=http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/guilty-as-charged-serial-robbers-dressed-in-only-their-swimming-trunks|newspaper=The Straits Times|location=Singapore|date=16 May 2016|accessdate=16 May 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160517111748/http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/guilty-as-charged-serial-robbers-dressed-in-only-their-swimming-trunks|archive-date=2016-05-17|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===1978===\n* 25 April 1978: 18-year-old police national serviceman [[Lee Kim Lai]]<ref>{{cite news|title=Guilty As Charged: Three friends who wanted to become robbers killed 2 men to get a gun|url=http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/guilty-as-charged-three-friends-who-wanted-to-become-robbers-killed-2-men-to|newspaper=The Straits Times|location=Singapore|date=16 May 2016|accessdate=16 May 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160515103958/http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/guilty-as-charged-three-friends-who-wanted-to-become-robbers-killed-2-men-to|archive-date=2016-05-15|url-status=live}}</ref> was abducted by three men from his sentry post at [[Mount Vernon, Singapore|Mount Vernon]] and forced into a taxi. They killed him for his service revolver and also killed the taxi driver. The three men were convicted of murder and hanged on 24 February 1984.<ref>{{cite news|title=Murderer's last gift \u2014 his eyes|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article/straitstimes19840226-1.2.28.aspx|newspaper=The Straits Times|location=Singapore|date=26 February 1984|accessdate=16 March 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160318222353/http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article/straitstimes19840226-1.2.28.aspx|archive-date=2016-03-18|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*August 1978: Siti Aminah binte Jaffar, 24, a former barmaid and Anwar Ali Khan was caught for trafficking 43.5g of diamorphine (pure heroin), which exceeds the mandatory death penalty of 15g. Both were eventually sentenced to death. Anwar was hanged in 1983 after President Devan rejected his plea of clemency. Siti was spared with the death penalty and placed her under life imprisonment after President Devan accepted her plea of clemency. Siti became the first woman about to be sentenced to death for drug trafficking, but spared due to an accepted plea of clemency.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article/straitstimes19830219.2.33.1.aspx|title=Drugs woman told she will not hang|access-date=2016-10-28|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161029115820/http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article/straitstimes19830219.2.33.1.aspx|archive-date=2016-10-29|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===1979===\n* 6 January 1979: Four children between the ages of five and ten were [[Geylang Bahru family murders|found brutally slashed to death]] in their [[Housing and Development Board|HDB]] flat in [[Geylang|Geylang Bahru]]. The case remains unsolved.<ref>{{cite web|last=Kutty|first=N. G.|url=http://newspapers.nl.sg/Digitised/Article/straitstimes19790107.2.3.aspx|title=Four kids slashed to death...|newspaper=The Straits Times|location=Singapore|date=7 January 1979|accessdate=20 November 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121107051236/http://newspapers.nl.sg/Digitised/Article/straitstimes19790107.2.3.aspx|archive-date=2012-11-07|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Jasli|first=Tettyana|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/infopedia/articles/SIP_1872_2012-02-28.html|title=Geylang Bahru family murders|publisher=National Library Board, Singapore|accessdate=25 January 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141228000842/http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/infopedia/articles/SIP_1872_2012-02-28.html|archive-date=2014-12-28|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==1980s==\n\n===1980===\n*3 October 1980: PC Nawi bin Saini and another policeman spotted 25-year-old Malaysian Seow Lam Seng and his accomplice 30-year-old Lee Ah Fatt loitering suspiciously just meters from a bank along [[Katong|Tanjong Katong]] Road.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tnp.sg/news/singapore/msian-man-charged-firearm-possession-after-38-years-run|title=M'sian man charged with firearm possession after 38 years on the run|last=ALKHATIB|first=SHAFFIQ|date=2018-03-27|website=The New Paper|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180327002520/https://www.tnp.sg/news/singapore/msian-man-charged-firearm-possession-after-38-years-run|archive-date=27 March 2018|access-date=2019-11-11}}</ref> When the duo were searched and screened, Lee allegedly drew his pistol and pointed at the officers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thesundaily.my/archive/how-law-caught-fugitive-38-years-later-NUARCH537784|title=How the law caught up with fugitive 38 years later|last=|first=|date=5 April 2018|website=www.thesundaily.my|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191111212405/https://www.thesundaily.my/archive/how-law-caught-fugitive-38-years-later-NUARCH537784|archive-date=11 November 2019|access-date=2019-11-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/fugitive-returns-to-crime-scene-after-38-years|title=Fugitive returns to crime scene after 38 years|last=Chua|first=Ilyda|date=2018-03-29|website=The Straits Times|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180406122235/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/fugitive-returns-to-crime-scene-after-38-years|archive-date=6 April 2018|access-date=2019-11-11}}</ref> PC Nawi then drew his revolver and fired three shots at Lee. Lee continued to struggle with the officers despite being shot while Seow took advantage of the officers' distraction and fled. Seow also discarded his gun as he fled.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article/straitstimes19801004-1.2.4|title=Gunman shot dead near Katong bank|last=Lai|first=Yew Kong|date=4 October 1980|website=|publisher=The Straits Times|via=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/|access-date=11 November 2019}}</ref> Lee succumbed to his injuries in hospital while Seow fled to Malaysia and was on the run for 38 years. On 22 March 2018, 63-year-old Seow was nabbed in [[Penang]] by the Royal Malaysian Police and extradited to Singapore two days later.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/after-38-years-on-the-run-man-wanted-for-firearms-offence-nabbed-in-penang|title=After 38 years on the run, man wanted for firearms offence nabbed in Penang|last=Boh|first=Samantha|date=2018-03-25|website=The Straits Times|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180330224646/http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/after-38-years-on-the-run-man-wanted-for-firearms-offence-nabbed-in-penang|archive-date=30 March 2018|access-date=2019-11-11}}</ref> On 26 March 2018, Seow was charged for unlawful possession of firearms.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.todayonline.com/singapore/63-year-old-run-illegal-possession-pistol-caught-after-38-years|title=63-year-old on the run for illegal possession of pistol caught after 38 years|last=LOW|first=YOUJIN|date=25 March 2018|website=TODAYonline|access-date=2019-11-11}}</ref>\n\n===1981===\n* 25 January and 7 February 1981: Notoriously dubbed as the [[Toa Payoh ritual murders|Adrian Lim ritual murders]] and widely remembered by Singaporeans up till today,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mustsharenews.com/unbelievable-crimes-singapore/|title=10 Most Unbelievable Crimes That Happened In Singapore / Toa Payoh ritual murders|last=Kash|first=Saba|date=2018-05-05|website=Must Share News|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://goodyfeed.com/5-murder-cases-in-spore-that-will-shock-you/|title=5 Murder Cases in S\u2019pore that will Shock you / Toa Payoh ritual murders (1981)|last=|first=|date=2015-09-28|website=Goody Feed|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://remembersingapore.org/2011/01/24/headlines-that-shook-singapore/|title=Headlines that shook Singapore (since 1955) / Adrian Lim Murders|last=|first=|date=2011-01-24|website=Remember Singapore|language=en|access-date=2019-10-22}}</ref> Lim, a self-professed [[Mediumship|medium]], together with his two accomplices, Catherine Tan Mui Choo and Hoe Kah Hong murdered two children, purportedly as blood sacrifices in some ritual. All three of them were found guilty of murder and sentenced to death. They were hanged on 25 November 1988.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Munoo|first1=Rajendra|title=Adrian Lim Murders|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/infopedia/articles/SIP_71_2005-02-02.html?s=adrian%20lim|publisher=National Library Board, Singapore|accessdate=25 January 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160202103907/http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/infopedia/articles/SIP_71_2005-02-02.html?s=adrian%20lim|archive-date=2016-02-02|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/guilty-as-charged-adrian-lim-and-his-2-holy-wives-kidnapped-tortured-and|title=Guilty As Charged: Adrian Lim and his 2 'holy' wives kidnapped, tortured and killed 2 children|last=|first=|date=2016-05-15|website=The Straits Times|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190216003913/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/guilty-as-charged-adrian-lim-and-his-2-holy-wives-kidnapped-tortured-and|archive-date=2019-02-16|access-date=2019-10-22}}</ref>\n*20 September 1981: 22-year-old Ramu Annadavascan and his 16-year-old accomplice Rathakrishnan Ramasamy assaulted 45-year-old boilerman Kalingam Mariappan with a rake. The assault ensued from an argument between both Ramu and Kalingam. Afterwards, the two then proceeded to pour petrol onto the unconscious Kalingam, and set fire on him, causing Kalingam to be burned to death. Both were later found guilty of murder; Ramu was condemned to death and he headed to the gallows on 19 September 1986, while Rathakrishnan, who was under the age of 18 when he committed the murder, was spared the gallows and detained indefinitely at the President's pleasure. After serving nearly 20 years, Rathakrishnan was released from prison in September 2001.\n\n===1983===\n* 30 June and 23 July 1983: Known as the Andrew Road triple murders, Sek Kim Wah, a 19-year-old [[National service in Singapore|conscript]], broke into the home of businessman Robert Tay Bak Hong at Andrew Road on 23 July with the aid of his accomplice, 19-year-old Malaysian Nyu Kok Meng. They were armed with a rifle Sek had stolen from Nee Soon camp. All five victims: Tay, his wife, their Filipino maid, Tay's daughter and her tutor were confined to a bedroom. They proceeded to rob Tay's family of their jewellery and cash out money from their bank accounts. While Nyu was guarding the victims, Sek decided to murder all five victims by escorting them one-by-one out of the bedroom in a bid to erase witnesses. Sek proceeded to struck Tay and his wife with a chair and strangled them. Sek also strangled their maid. In all, Sek murdered 3 people. Nyu discovered Sek's murder intentions only when he caught him in the act in another room. Fearing that Tay's daughter and her tutor would be next, Nyu carried the rifle with him and locked the bedroom door upon dashing in. When Sek's repeated requests to open the door was denied by Nyu, Sek immediately fled. Nyu then released Tay's daughter and her tutor. Nyu fled to Malaysia before he surrendered and was extradited to Singapore. Sek was arrested at his sister's home on 29 July, where he attempted suicide when police were closing in on him. During the trial, when asked how he felt when strangling Tay's wife, Sek brought up an incident when he was nearly strangled by someone at the Singapore Boys\u2019 Home until he blacked out. Sek said: \u201cAt first I felt discomfort. Then it was very thrilling... as if the lights were being switched on and off.\u201d (Adapted from a 2016 Straits Times recollection article<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/guilty-as-charged-serial-murderer-sek-kim-wah-found-it-thrilling-to-strangle|title=Guilty As Charged: Serial murderer Sek Kim Wah found it 'thrilling' to strangle victims|last=Jalelah|first=Abu Baker|date=2016-05-15|website=The Straits Times|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190216151418/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/guilty-as-charged-serial-murderer-sek-kim-wah-found-it-thrilling-to-strangle|archive-date=2019-02-16|access-date=2019-10-23}}</ref>) However, his encounter at the Boys' Home was found to be made up.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://video.toggle.sg/en/video/series/true-files-s2/ep2/367407|title=True Files S2|website=Toggle|access-date=2019-10-23}}</ref> Nyu was acquitted of murder, but charged with armed robbery and sentenced to life imprisonment and six strokes of cane. Prior to the Andrew Rd triple murders, Sek had also murdered two other people in [[Marine Parade]] by strangling them before disposing their bodies near [[Seletar Reservoir]] on 30 June. Sek was found guilty of murder and according to the Straits Times article: Sek thanked the court for the sentence, saying that he had always wanted to die on the gallows. Eventually, he was hanged on 9 December 1988 for the murder of all five victims.<ref>{{cite news|title=Andrew Road murders: 19-year-old is charged|url=http://newspapers.nl.sg/Digitised/Article/straitstimes19830731-1.2.2.aspx|newspaper=The Straits Times|location=Singapore|date=31 July 1983|accessdate=25 January 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131112213359/http://newspapers.nl.sg/Digitised/Article/straitstimes19830731-1.2.2.aspx|archive-date=2013-11-12|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Andrew Road murders: Two for trial|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article/straitstimes19840322.2.102.aspx|newspaper=The Straits Times|location=Singapore|date=22 March 1984|accessdate=25 January 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160202124533/http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article/straitstimes19840322.2.102.aspx|archive-date=2016-02-02|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Execution By Hanging: 9/12/1988 Sek Kim Wah \u2013 Singapore|url=http://www.truecrimelibrary.com/crime_series_show.php?id=1041&series_number=13|website=True Crime Library|accessdate=25 January 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121213165536/http://www.truecrimelibrary.com/crime_series_show.php?id=1041&series_number=13|archivedate=13 December 2012}}</ref>\n\n===1984===\n* 12 December 1984: Ayakanno Marithamuthu disappearance remained a mystery and his 'murder' was famously dubbed the [[Death of Ayakannu Marithamuthu|curry murder]]. Marithamuthu, a caretaker at the [[Public Utilities Board]] holiday chalets in [[Changi]], was allegedly bludgeoned to death in the [[Orchard Road]] Presbyterian Church. His body was suspected to be dismembered, cooked in curry, packed in plastic bags and disposed in rubbish bins along the roads. However, his remains and evidence of the murder were never found. His wife and her three brothers were charged in court in 1987 but released in the same year due to lack of evidence. The brothers were arrested again and released in June 1991 after spending four years in prison.<ref name=\"Other gruesome murders that took place in Singapore\" /> The case remains unsolved till today.\n\n===1985===\n*22 May 1985: Winnifred Teo Suan Lie, an 18-year-old [[Catholic Junior College]] student, was the victim of a rape and murder case. On 22 May, she left her house for a jog, but never returned home. Her mother made a police report. Teo's naked body was later found lying in undergrowth off Old Holland Road. She suffered multiple stab wounds on her neck. Her body showed signs of a fierce but futile protest, probably made when she was trying to fight off her killer(s). An autopsy showed that she had been sexually assaulted, and died of massive bleeding from the stab wounds. The murderer(s) were never discovered. The case remains unsolved.{{citation needed|date=January 2016}}\n*18 December 1985: Known as Ah Huat, Lim Keng Peng had committed theft and fled from the scene of crime. When he was spotted by detective Goh Ah Khia who had earlier attended to the crime, Lim fired a shot at detective Goh's chest and fled. Detective Goh died afterwards. The murder sparked a manhunt for Lim and he was also responsible for the shooting of a restaurant owner in a robbery attempt in April that year.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://scontent-lht6-1.cdninstagram.com/v/t51.2885-15/e35/51762376_144486183227255_8482172687112765112_n.jpg?_nc_ht=scontent-lht6-1.cdninstagram.com&_nc_cat=111&oh=76ab619d5d51dd99ed0000563f97a109&oe=5E8292A8&ig_cache_key=MTk3NDAxNTU4MzQyNDgyNDgxOQ==.2|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191120032433/https://scontent-lht6-1.cdninstagram.com/v/t51.2885-15/e35/51762376_144486183227255_8482172687112765112_n.jpg?_nc_ht=scontent-lht6-1.cdninstagram.com&_nc_cat=111&oh=76ab619d5d51dd99ed0000563f97a109&oe=5E8292A8&ig_cache_key=MTk3NDAxNTU4MzQyNDgyNDgxOQ==.2|url-status=dead|archive-date=2019-11-20|title=Two killings pointed to Ah Huat|last=Chong|first=Elena|date=1980s|work=The Straits Times|access-date=20 November 2019}}</ref> He evaded detection from the police until on 3 May 1988, he was confronted by the police at a coffee shop in Clementi.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.keshvani.com/print/obituary/stephenkoh.html|title=ASP (Retd) Stephen Koh \u2013 Goodbye to an SPF Legend ...: Keshvani Online|last=Keshvani|first=Nisar|date=|website=www.keshvani.com|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191120033728/https://www.keshvani.com/print/obituary/stephenkoh.html|archive-date=20 November 2019|access-date=20 November 2019}}</ref> While they attempted to arrest Lim, Lim managed to pull out his gun. However, the three police officers who confronted him each fired a shot at Lim. Lim did not survive the ordeal.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://video.toggle.sg/en/video/series/crimewatch-2003/ep1/410732|title=Crimewatch 2003, Episode 1|last=|first=|date=|website=Toggle|access-date=20 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n'''1988'''\n\n*16 February 1988: Upon hearing that his elderly foster father Tan Ai Soon was severely assaulted, the angered 22-year-old Koh Swee Beng gathered Tan's 3 sons Tan Eng Chye, Tan Eng Poh and Tan Eng Geok, the Tan brothers' brother-in-law Ng Eng Guan and their friend Ong Hong Thor to confront 31-year-old Tay Kim Teck, the man who assaulted the elder Tan. They then chased the man and beat him up. During the beating, Koh fatally stabbed Tay twice, leading to Tay's death within minutes. All were later arrested and charged with murder; however, only Koh was found guilty of murder and sentenced to death while the other five had their charges reduced to rioting and they each received a jail term of 2 years and 4 strokes of the cane. Koh was eventually granted clemency by the President of Singapore and had his death sentence commuted to life imprisonment.\n\n\n===1989===\n\n* 15 February 1989: In one of the rare cases involving the [[List of Singapore police officers killed in the line of duty|death of a policeman on duty]], two men were attempting to break into a shop unit at Block 107, Tampines St 11 in the wee hours when they were spotted by two policemen following a tip-off by a member of the public. When confronted, 29-year-old Ong Yeow Tian ran off while one of the policeman, Police Constable (PC) Chua Yeu Hua arrested his accomplice. The other policeman, 22-year-old PC Mirza Abdul Halim chased after Ong. Ong managed to hide in the bushes before launching an assault at PC Mizra. Ong used his weapon to stab PC Mizra before PC Mizra took out his revolver in an attempt to defend himself. Ong overpowered PC Mizra and shot him in the head before fleeing the scene together with the revolver. Ong fled in a taxi before it was sighted by another two policemen, Sergeant Omar Amin and PC Benny Goh. The taxi was pulled over and out of a sudden, Ong use the stolen revolver to fire at them. In return, PC Goh successfully shot Ong in the abdomen before he managed to flee. The [[Police Tactical Unit (Singapore)|Police Task Force]] was activated to hunt for Ong. When one of the groups of the Police Task Force was patrolling, Ong who was hiding managed to shoot one of the man on patrol who was saved by a bulletproof vest. He was eventually subdued and arrested. PC Mizra went into a coma. He was given the rare field promotion to the rank of Corporal before Corporal Mizra passed away a day after the shooting. Ong's accomplice received jail and caning while Ong was found guilty for unlawful discharge of firearms and sentenced to death. Ong's appeal was dismissed and he was hanged on 25 November 1994.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article/newpaper19890215-1.2.3.3|title=Gunfight in Tampines: Cop, suspect shot|last=Ng|first=Wan Ching|date=1989-02-15|work=The New Paper (Singapore)|access-date=2019-10-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://video.toggle.sg/en/video/series/crimewatch-1995/ep7/432007|title=Crimewatch 1995|website=Toggle|access-date=2019-10-14}}</ref> Such incident has resulted in the introduction of snatch-resistant holster in later years.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tnp.sg/news/singapore/man-grabs-gun-shoots-police-officer-khoo-teck-puat-hospital|title=Man grabs gun, shoots police officer at Khoo Teck Puat Hospital / Past cases of gun-snatching|last=Tan|first=Judith|last2=Sen|first2=Ng Jun|date=2015-06-21|website=The New Paper|language=en|access-date=2019-10-14}}</ref>\n*11 April 1989: 50 year old Ibrahim Masod abetted Liow Han Heng, 44 to kidnap Liow\u2019s ex-boss 56 year old Phang Tee Wah, they lured Phang to come to Thompson Plaza and discuss, he was eventually lured to Liow\u2019s house in Yishun, Liow and Ibrahim found him dead on the next day, Phang\u2019s body was found decomposed on 15 April 1989, they were arrested and sentenced to death. Liow died of heart failure before hanged, Ibrahim\u2019s appeal of clemency was rejected and hanged on 1994.\n*2 October 1989: A 17-year-old student from Mayflower Secondary School, Liang Shan Shan, was reported missing by her parents. She was last seen at her school, boarding her school bus at 1 pm. 12 days later, her highly decomposed body was discovered by NS servicemen undergoing their training exercises at Yishun Industrial Park. Forensic pathologist Chao Tzee Cheng could not ascertain the cause of death: he could not tell whether it was a suicide, murder or accident due to the corpse's state of severe decomposition. Nevertheless, the police investigations narrowed down to one suspect: Liang's school bus driver Oh Laye Koh. Oh was then charged with her murder, purely based on circumstantial evidence. He was initially acquitted of her murder at the end of his trial in 1992; however, the prosecution appealed against his acquittal, pointing out how Oh, despite his insistence that he did not kill Liang or know her whereabouts, was able to lead police to the place where Liang's bag and books were, which was some distance away from where her body was found; Oh claimed he went to fix his brakes at 1 pm when the girl was last seen alive, but it was found that he went there at 9 am; and lastly, he even contacted and tried to convince the witnesses to testify on his behalf that they did not see his bus that day. The appeal was accepted, and the re-trial started on 27 April 1994. Oh chose to remain silent when he was told to make his defence. Judicial Commissioner Amarjeet Singh concluded from Oh's decision to remain silent and also his failure to provide evidence \"arose from a consciousness of guilt in the face of the circumstantial evidence\". In JC Singh's words towards Oh, \"I am constrained to draw an irresistible inference that you were the last person with the deceased and you had intentionally caused her death and that the deceased's death was not suicidal or accidental. Although the prosecution was unable to identify the unlawful act, it is not necessary, in my opinion, always to do so.\" As such, on 3 May 1994, Oh was found guilty and convicted of Liang's murder and he was subsequently sentenced to death. Oh's appeal was dismissed on 29 June 1994, and he was executed by hanging on 19 May 1995.\n\n==1990s==\n\n===1990===\n* 15 May 1990: Tan Ah Hong and James Soh Fook Leong were stabbed by two men after chatting on the spiral steps of the Amber Beacon Tower at [[East Coast Park]]. They managed to make their way to a nearby restaurant for help. Soh, who was stabbed in the back, survived the ordeal. Tan died before the police arrived. She was stabbed in the neck, just below the ear. The murderers were never found and the case remains unsolved.{{citation needed|date=January 2015}}\n\n===1991===\n* 4 May 1991: Filipino domestic worker [[Flor Contemplacion]] murdered another Filipino domestic worker, Della Maga, and Nicholas Huang, the four-year-old son of Maga's employer. She was sentenced to death in January 1993 and hanged on 17 March 1995. The incident caused diplomatic relations between Singapore and the Philippines to be strained for some years.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Chew|first1=Valerie|title=Flor Contemplacion|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/infopedia/articles/SIP_1551_2009-07-31.html|publisher=National Library Board, Singapore|accessdate=25 January 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150107061231/http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/infopedia/articles/SIP_1551_2009-07-31.html|archive-date=2015-01-07|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* September 1991: Dutchman [[Johannes van Damme]] was arrested at [[Changi Airport]] after the police found 9.5 pounds of heroin in his suitcase. He was found guilty of drug trafficking, sentenced to death, and hanged on 23 September 1994.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Shenon|first1=Philip|title=Singapore Executes a Dutch Engineer Arrested on Drug Charges|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1994/09/24/world/singapore-executes-a-dutch-engineer-arrested-on-drug-charges.html|newspaper=The New York Times|accessdate=25 January 2015|date=24 September 1994|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150209204916/http://www.nytimes.com/1994/09/24/world/singapore-executes-a-dutch-engineer-arrested-on-drug-charges.html|archive-date=2015-02-09|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===1993===\n* September 1993: Chong Poh Choon, a [[Republic of Singapore Navy|Navy]] regular, murdered his three children at their [[Housing Development Board|HDB]] flat in [[Bukit Batok]]. Chong was eventually sentenced to life imprisonment.<ref>{{cite news|title=Dad who killed children jailed for life|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article/straitstimes19940910-1.2.39.12.aspx|newspaper=The Straits Times|accessdate=25 January 2015|date=10 September 1994|location=Singapore|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160202114445/http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article/straitstimes19940910-1.2.39.12.aspx|archive-date=2016-02-02|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n*4 December 1993 - 26-year-old Maniam S/O Rathinswamy and his accomplice S.S. Asokan, were both sentenced to death for the murder of illegal moneylender Tan Heng Hong. Some time in November 1992, both Maniam and Asokan murdered Tan and drove Tan's car to Mandai, burning it together with Tan's corpse. Despite the charred remains, Tan's identity was ascertained, as well as the cause of death: the late forensic pathologist Professor Chao Tzee Cheng identified that the cause of Tan's death was a cut artery on his neck. Maniam, who was eventually arrested and tried, claimed that on the night of Tan's murder, while the three of them were arguing violently over letting Tan to pay back Asokan's commission over a pen he sold to Tan, Asokan became so agitated that he picked up the axe Maniam bought the day before to kill Tan, and it was Asokan's idea to burn the corpse, proclaiming his innocence. However, Asokan, who fled to Malaysia and got extradited back to Singapore to face trial, stated that Maniam told him to grab the axe and kill Tan when he refused to pay the commission, saying that he did not mean to hit or kill him, and that he was only following Maniam's orders. Justice Sinnathuray rejected their defences and stating that if they had no intention to kill, the weapons would not have been brought in the first place, and satisfied that they both shared a common intention to murder Tan, therefore he convicted both of them as charged. The two men were eventually hanged on 9 December 1995.\n\n===1994===\n* 6 June 1994 : Known as the Oriental Hotel Murder, two Japanese tourists Fujii Isae, 49 and Miyoko Takishita, 56, were robbed by two Malay men, 25-year-old Abdul Nasir bin Amer Hamsah and 32-year-old Abdul Rahman bin Arshad. The two acquaintances, who came to the Oriental Hotel for a job interview, saw the Japanse tour group which Fujii and Takashita were with, and deciding to rob them. Takashita was assaulted by Abdul Rahman and she pretended to faint from the assault. Fujii, however, was severely assaulted by Abdul Nasir. As he was trying to escape, he lost his balance and accidentally stepped onto Fujii's face. This led to a facial fracture and caused Fujii to suffocate to death. Both men were not arrested until when two years later, Abdul Nasir was arrested for attempting to rob and suffocate a taxi driver. His fingerprints were then tested and found to match those found at the crime scene, and thus he was charged with the murder of Fujii. Abdul Rahman, who was later found to be in prison serving a 20-month jail sentence for theft, was also charged with murder, though he later pleaded guilty to robbery with hurt, and sentenced to 10 years' jail with 16 strokes of the cane. Abdul Nasir was eventually found guilty of robbery with hurt and sentenced to 18 years' jail and 18 strokes of the cane. However, it was not the end of Abdul Nasir's ordeal, as he had to go back to court to face a kidnapping charge, which he committed together with drug trafficker Low Theng Gee during the period of his remand before the trial, where they briefly kidnapped two officers before being abducted. Abdul Nasir was later convicted of kidnapping and sentenced to life imprisonment with 12 strokes of the cane in January 1997. Justice T. S. Sinnathuray ordered Abdul Nasir's life sentence to run consecutively with the jail term he received for robbing Fujii, meaning Abdul Nasir had to serve a total of 38 years in prison (At that time, life imprisonment in Singapore was defined as a 20-year jail sentence). Abdul Nasir filed an appeal for his two jail terms to run concurrently, but it was dismissed on 20 August 1997. However, Chief Justice Yong Pung How decided that the definition of life imprisonment should be considered as a term of imprisonment for a convict's remaining natural life instead of 20 years' imprisonment, and this amendment will apply to future cases. Abdul Nasir was not affected by this and hence his life term remained as a jail term of 20 years, and he would still be spending 38 years in prison.\n\n===1995===\n* 26 February 1995: Britain's oldest merchant bank [[Barings Bank]] collapsed due to Briton [[Nick Leeson]]'s trading activities, who lost $1.4 billion by speculating on the [[Singapore International Monetary Exchange]], primarily using [[futures contracts]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Barings Bank collapses from Nick Leeson's losses |url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/history/events/e7cb71fe-b7b9-445e-b5d1-655bf301d6a8|website=NLB|accessdate=20 July 2019|date=26 February 1995}}</ref> He was arrested on 23 November 1995 after fleeing Singapore for 272 days. Subsequently, Nick Leeson pleaded guilty to two charges out of three charges of forgery and eight charges of cheating and was sentenced to 6\u00bd years in prison.<ref>{{cite news|title=Guilty As Charged: Rogue trader Nick Leeson brought down Britain's oldest merchant bank Barings|url=http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/guilty-as-charged-rogue-trader-nick-leeson-brought-down-britains-oldest|newspaper=The Straits Times|location=Singapore|accessdate=16 May 2016|date=16 May 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160516050310/http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/guilty-as-charged-rogue-trader-nick-leeson-brought-down-britains-oldest|archive-date=2016-05-16|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* 8 March 1995: Briton [[John Martin Scripps|John Martin]] murdered South African Gerard George Lowe in River View Hotel, dismembered his body, and disposed the body parts in the [[Singapore River]]. He was found guilty of murder and hanged on 19 April 1996.<ref name=\"Other gruesome murders that took place in Singapore\">{{cite news|title=Other gruesome murders that took place in Singapore|url=http://news.asiaone.com/News/AsiaOne+News/Crime/Story/A1Story20120403-337375.html|newspaper=The New Paper|location=Singapore|accessdate=25 January 2015|date=4 April 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150104164706/http://news.asiaone.com/News/AsiaOne+News/Crime/Story/A1Story20120403-337375.html|archivedate=4 January 2015}}</ref>\n\n===1996===\n\n* 4 October 1996: 29-year-old Zulkarnain Bin Kemat murdered his drinking and smoking partner, 51-year-old Madam Jetkor Miang Singh at her flat in Ang Mo Kio. Zulkarnain and Madam Jetkor were arguing before Zulkarnain stabbed her neck with a pocket nail knife and kicked her repeatedly. To conceal his crime, Zulkarnain wiped the table containing his fingerprints. He also discarded the ashtray, but failed to discard the cigarette butts which contain his saliva. The case was initially unsolved as police could not establish concrete evidence that Zulkarnian murdered Madam Jetkor and [[DNA profiling]] was not fully reliable. Over the years as DNA profiling becomes more accurate and faster, collection of DNA samples from all convicts was made mandatory in 2002.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sso.agc.gov.sg/Acts-Supp/45-2002/Published/20021226?DocDate=20021226|title=Registration of Criminals (Amendment) Act 2002 - Singapore Statutes Online|last=|first=|date=26 December 2002|website=sso.agc.gov.sg|language=en|access-date=10 November 2019}}</ref> The case reopened in November 2003, which matched the DNA sample found on the cigarette to Zulkarnian. In 2005, 37-year-old Zulkarnian was charged with culpable homicide and sentenced to 8 years imprisonment and 6 strokes of the cane. His sentence ran concurrently with his sentence of 6.5 years and 3 strokes of the cane for consuming drugs, which was imposed in September 2000.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.corpun.com/sgj00502.htm|title=Done in by DNA|last=Fong|first=Tanya|last2=Chong|first2=Elena|date=1 February 2005|publisher=The Straits Times|via=www.corpun.com|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191110145404/https://www.corpun.com/sgj00502.htm|archive-date=10 November 2019|access-date=10 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://video.toggle.sg/en/video/series/crimewatch-2005/ep2/411119|title=Crimewatch 2005, Episode 2|last=|first=|date=|website=Toggle|access-date=10 November 2019}}</ref> After his release, he was arrested again and currently serving a life sentence for drug trafficking in 2013.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.supremecourt.gov.sg/docs/default-source/module-document/judgement/pp-v-zulkarnain-and-others-16-july-2018-final-for-release-pdf.pdf|title=[2018] SGHC 161, Criminal Case No. 43 of 2016|last=|first=|date=16 July 2018|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191110150424/https://www.supremecourt.gov.sg/docs/default-source/module-document/judgement/pp-v-zulkarnain-and-others-16-july-2018-final-for-release-pdf.pdf|archive-date=10 November 2019|access-date=10 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n===1997===\n* 18 June 1997: A woman, Komala Karuppiah was murdered at Block 505 Serangoon North Avenue 4. Her husband, Kannan s/o Marie, who had came back from a trip to Tapah, Perak for a wedding with his son, Sashi, had called the police to report the murder. At first, the police had suspected it was a robbery gone wrong, but after asking Kannan's son, Sashi, Kannan confessed that he had killed Komala after a dispute over a gold ring he had bought for the bride in the marriage. \n\n*20 June 1997: Known as the \"Duck Den Murder\", 19-year-old Malaysian youth and male prostitute Lim Chin Chong murdered his 65-year-old employer and duck den operator Low Cheng Quee (a duck den is known as a brothel for male prostitutes). Lim fled to Malaysia and was on the run for nearly 20 days, seeking refuge in the homes of his acquaintances and relatives before his arrest by the Royal Malaysian Police on 9 July 1997. He was later extradited to Singapore and charged with the murder of Low. On 1 December 1997, after the end of a 6-day-long trial from 24 November 1997, Justice Kan Ting Chiu found Lim guilty of murder and sentenced him to death. Lim was hanged on 23 October 1998, after the rejection of his appeal against the sentence.\n\n===1998===\n* 11 January 1998: A Bulgarian student, 26-year-old Iordanka Apostolova, was involved in an argument with 22-year-old Shaiful Edham Adam at a housing unit in Depot Road. Adam chopped Ms Apostolova's throat together with the help of his friend, 26-year-old Norishyam Mohamed Ali. Shaiful's wife, Hezlinda A Rahman together with the two of them help to dispose her body at a canal near Tenah Merah Ferry Road. Her body was discovered on 13 January, which led to the arrest of Shaiful and Hezlinda. Norishyam surrendered to the police shortly after. Both Shaiful and Norishyam were found guilty of murder and sentenced to death. They were hanged on 2 July 1999 while Hezlinda was sentenced to 6 years imprisonment for helping to dispose Ms Apostolova's body.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/former-detective-richard-lim-beng-gee-65-dies-5-high-profile-cases-he-helped|title=Former detective Richard Lim Beng Gee, 65, dies: 5 high-profile cases he helped crack / BULGARIAN WOMAN'S BODY FOUND IN CANAL, CASE SOLVED IN 36 HOURS|last=Lee|first=Min Kok|date=2016-01-19|website=The Straits Times|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191012154003/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/former-detective-richard-lim-beng-gee-65-dies-5-high-profile-cases-he-helped|archive-date=2019-10-12|access-date=2019-10-12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://video.toggle.sg/en/video/series/true-files-s1/ep13/366934|title=True Files S1|website=Toggle|access-date=2019-10-12}}</ref>\n*7 May 1998: Two men were consuming [[heroin]] at a rubbish centre under a flat in [[Woodlands, Singapore|Woodlands]] when they were spotted by two policemen. In the midst of scuffle, one of the suspects was arrested while the other, 40-year-old Tan Cheng Lock, Anthony snatched a revolver from one of the officer and shot him in the thigh before breaking free. He seek refuge at his mother's flat in Chai Chee before the police located him. The [[Special Tactics and Rescue (Singapore)|Special Tactics and Rescue (STAR)]] unit raided the flat the following night. During the raid, Tan use the stolen revolver to shoot himself to death before police could arrest him.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tnp.sg/news/singapore/man-grabs-gun-shoots-police-officer-khoo-teck-puat-hospital|title=Man grabs gun, shoots police officer at Khoo Teck Puat Hospital / Past cases of gun snatching|last=Tan|first=Judith|last2=Ng|first2=Jun Sen|date=2015-06-21|website=The New Paper|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170507033844/http://www.tnp.sg/news/singapore/man-grabs-gun-shoots-police-officer-khoo-teck-puat-hospital|archive-date=2017-05-07|access-date=2019-10-12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://video.toggle.sg/en/video/series/crimewatch-1999/ep1/433256|title=Crimewatch 1999|last=|first=|date=31 March 1999|website=Toggle|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191012061122/https://video.toggle.sg/en/series/crimewatch-1999/ep1/433256|archive-date=2019-10-12|access-date=2019-10-12}}</ref>\n*20 April 1998: 23-year-old Malaysian freelance assistant cameraman and prop assistant Jonaris Badlishah killed 42-year-old make-up artist Sally Poh Bee Eng over a Rolex wrist watch. He was hanged on 8 Dec 1998 after a 19-day trial.<ref>{{cite news|title=Guilty As Charged: Jonaris Badlishah killed to get a Rolex for girlfriend|url=http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/guilty-as-charged-jonaris-badlishah-killed-to-get-a-rolex-for-girlfriend|newspaper=The Straits Times|location=Singapore|accessdate=16 May 2016|date=16 May 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160515220659/http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/guilty-as-charged-jonaris-badlishah-killed-to-get-a-rolex-for-girlfriend|archive-date=2016-05-15|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===1999===\n*21 April 1999: At Phoenix Garden, retired Inspector T Maniam was found dead after being beaten to death. The witnesses, a maid and his youngest step-daughter, Fairos Banu provided with evidence. Although the maid's evidence proved inconclusive, it helped them to find the vehicle the murderers used and his step-daughter's evidence proved that one of the murderers was her mother's boyfriend that was beaten by Maniam after he saw them walking hand in hand near his home in 1996. The mastermind of the murder, his wife had thought of murdering him as the home he lived with her and his stepdaughters as it had a value of $1.5 million. She had thought that once he died, the house would be hers, since she was a joint owner. She and two others involved were arrested and sentenced to hang.\n* 9 September 1999: At Sian Tuan Ave, a 14-year-old daughter of a wealthy car dealer was kidnapped by 3 kidnappers: Chinese nationals Zhou Jian Guang and Shi Song Jing, aged 26 and 29 respectively together with their mastermind, 33 year-old Singaporean Vincent Lee Chuan Leong. She was kept in a rented house while they demanded S$500,000 for her release. The sum was re-negotiated to S$330,000 and paid to them before she was released on the morning of 12 September. Just 20 minutes after her release, Lee was arrested at his flat. Separately, the two Chinese nationals were arrested on 14 September. They were all found guilty of kidnapping and sentenced to life imprisonment.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/former-detective-richard-lim-beng-gee-65-dies-5-high-profile-cases-he-helped|title=Former detective Richard Lim Beng Gee, 65, dies: 5 high-profile cases he helped crack / TEENAGE GIRL KIDNAPPED WHILE WALKING HOME|last=Lee|first=Min Kok|date=2016-01-19|website=The Straits Times|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191012154609/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/former-detective-richard-lim-beng-gee-65-dies-5-high-profile-cases-he-helped|archive-date=2019-10-12|access-date=2019-10-14}}</ref>\n\n==2000s==\n===2000===\n\n* 8/26 August 2000: Three men: 34-year-old Wan Kamil Mohamed Shafian, 35-year-old Ibrahim Mohamed and 30-year-old Rosli Ahmat decided to commit robberies using weapons and firearms they had bought. They intended to use a taxi as a getaway vehicle and so on the morning of 8 August, they targeted a taxi driven by 42-year-old Koh Ngiap Yong(\u8bb8\u4e1a\u8363). They told Koh to drive the taxi to Chestnut Drive before handcuffing him. Wan Kamil ordered Rosli Ahmat to stab Koh with a bayonet before they unlocked the handcuff. In the process, they dropped a handcuff key. They drove to Woodlands and intended to commit robberies, before backing out due to the presence of [[Closed-circuit television|CCTV]]<nowiki/>s.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/former-detective-richard-lim-beng-gee-65-dies-5-high-profile-cases-he-helped|title=Former detective Richard Lim Beng Gee, 65, dies: 5 high-profile cases he helped crack / TAXI DRIVER KILLED BY THREE MEN|last=Lee|first=Min Kok|date=2016-01-19|website=The Straits Times|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191012154609/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/former-detective-richard-lim-beng-gee-65-dies-5-high-profile-cases-he-helped|archive-date=2019-10-12|access-date=2019-10-22}}</ref> Koh's<nowiki/> body was discovered the <nowiki/>following morning, but the murder became unsolved due to limited leads until another murder occurred on the evening of 26 August. At an overhead bridge at Jalan Kukoh, a money changer was robbed and shot twice by Wan Kamil, together with the help of his accomplice Ibrahim Mohamed. The stolen phone (From the deceased money changer) they used after the murder was traced by police. All three of them were arrested on 15 October 2000 by STAR officers. The taxi driver's murder was traced to them when the handcuffs and keys recovered at Wan Kamil's flat did not tally with each other. On 5 September 2001, all three of them were found guilty of murder and sentenced to death. They were hanged on 25 October 2002.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://video.toggle.sg/en/video/series/crimewatch-2002/ep10/411133|title=Crimewatch 2002|website=Toggle|access-date=2019-10-22}}</ref>\n\n===2001===\n*6 January 2001: 45-year-old Zaiton binte Abu Bakar, a divorcee, was murdered at her home, was found by her daughter Norjanna after she came back from clearing her work at her uncle's accountancy firm and visiting her father. The suspect, 29-year-old Othman Hassan, was found to have murdered her after police inspected his home and found belongings owned by Zaiton. He had murdered her when he went to her home to fix faulty taps and return a debt he owed, but when an argument about the debt escalated, he stabbed her six times in the abdomen and then ransacked her belongings. He was sentenced to nine years of jail and 12 strokes of the cane.\n* 14 May 2001: 34-year-old Anthony Ler Wee Teang made headlines for hiring a youth to assassinate his wife, 30-year-old Annie Leong Wai Mun. Ler approached four youths and offered them a reward of S$100,000 to kill Leong, who was in the midst of divorcing him. A 15-year-old whom Ler had known for five years accepted the offer. Ler manipulated the youth to carry out the deed and after several failed attempts, the youth fatally stabbed Leong with a knife given to him by Ler. Ler was found guilty of conspiring and abetting the murder of Leong and was hanged on 13 December 2002. The youth was spared the death sentence because he was under 18 years old when he killed Leong and placed under indefinite detention under the President's pleasure.<ref>{{cite news|title=Devil with a smile|url=http://news.asiaone.com/news/crime/devil-smile?page=0%2C0|newspaper=The Straits Times|location=Singapore|accessdate=25 January 2015|date=5 October 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170407030133/http://news.asiaone.com/news/crime/devil-smile?page=0%2C0|archive-date=2017-04-07|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Teen who killed Anthony Ler's wife in 2001 appeals for clemency after 16 years behind bars |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/teen-who-killed-anthony-lers-wife-in-2001-appeals-for-clemency-after-16-years |accessdate=20 July 2019 |publisher=The Straits Times |date=25 November 2017}}</ref> On 2 November 2018, the youth, at 32 years of age, was released after his petition for clemency was granted by [[President of Singapore|President]] [[Halimah Yacob]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/annie-leongs-teen-killer-gets-clemency-after-17-years-in-jail|title=Teen who killed Anthony Ler's wife gets clemency after 17 years in jail|last=hermes|date=2018-12-13|website=The Straits Times|language=en|access-date=2019-04-04|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181214235554/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/annie-leongs-teen-killer-gets-clemency-after-17-years-in-jail|archive-date=14 December 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n*10 August 2001: A day before the wedding of 33-year-old businessman Tay Teng Joo, he was kidnapped by 45-year-old Chng Teo Heng together with the assistance of his accomplices, 52-year-old businesswoman Agnes Ng Lei Eng and 42-year-old freelance painter Ng Soon Teck. Tay was blindfolded and driven around in a car while they demanded a ransom of S$4 million. The sum was eventually reduced to S$1.22 million and Tay was released. It wasn't long before police nabbed all three suspects after a police report was made in 24 hours. Despite spending only S$903, the police managed to recover the money. They were all sentenced to life imprisonment, with Chng given an additional six strokes of cane for using a knife when abducting Tay into the car.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/three-previous-cases-of-kidnapping-for-ransom-over-13-years|title=Three previous cases of kidnapping for ransom over 13 years|last=Lim|first=Yan Liang|date=2014-01-10|website=The Straits Times|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191013160407/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/three-previous-cases-of-kidnapping-for-ransom-over-13-years|archive-date=2019-10-13|access-date=2019-10-13}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://video.toggle.sg/en/video/series/crimewatch-2002/ep3/411123|title=Crimewatch 2002|website=Toggle|access-date=2019-10-13}}</ref>\n*2 October 2001: A man robbed and stabbed a 28-year-old woman, Ms Soh San in a lift at Bukit Batok. She died from her injuries while the robber fled with S$30. Despite appeals for eyewitnesses from an episode of [[Crimewatch (Singaporean TV series)|Crimewatch]], the case remains unsolved.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://video.toggle.sg/en/video/series/crimewatch-2001/ep9/411107|title=Crimewatch 2001|last=|first=|date=|website=Toggle|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190921191347/https://video.toggle.sg/en/video/series/crimewatch-2001/ep9/411107|archive-date=2019-09-21|access-date=2019-09-21}}</ref> The man went on to commit other offences in the following years while police have no knowledge of his unconfessed killing. On 17 November 2013, the case reopened when 28-year-old Gunasegaran Ramasamy surrendered himself and confessed to the 2001 killing out of guilt. He was 16 years of age when he killed Ms Soh. Initially charged with murder, his charge was reduced to robbery with hurt. He was sentenced to 10 years imprisonment and 12 strokes of the cane.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/man-gets-10-years-and-12-strokes-of-the-cane-for-stabbing-woman-in-2001-lift|title=Man gets 10 years and 12 strokes of the cane for stabbing woman in 2001 lift robbery|last=Chong|first=Elena|date=2017-03-20|website=The Straits Times|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190921190922/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/man-gets-10-years-and-12-strokes-of-the-cane-for-stabbing-woman-in-2001-lift|archive-date=2019-09-21|access-date=2019-09-21}}</ref>\n*9-24 December 2001: A terrorist group, [[Jemaah Islamiyah]] (JI) plot to [[Singapore embassies attack plot|bomb several targets in Singapore]] such as US-aligned foreign embassies and [[Yishun MRT station]] were uncovered by the Internal Security Department, leading to an arrest of 15 JI Singaporeans that month. In subsequent years, about 40 more Singaporean JIs or JI-linked individuals were arrested.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/opinion/ji-arrests-15-years-later|title=JI arrests: 15 years later|last=Jayakumar|first=Shashi|date=2016-12-09|website=The Straits Times|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191004175741/https://www.straitstimes.com/opinion/ji-arrests-15-years-later|archive-date=2019-10-04|access-date=2019-10-28}}</ref>\n*\n\n===2002===\n* 2 January 2002: British financial adviser Michael McCrea murdered his friend Kho Nai Guan and Kho's girlfriend, Lan Ya Ming, in Kho's apartment in Pinewood Garden. With the help of his girlfriend, Audrey Ong, and two others, McCrea disposed Kho and Lan's bodies in a car and abandoned it at the car park in [[Orchard Towers]]. McCrea and Ong fled from Singapore on 5 January and were arrested in Melbourne in June after being on the run for about six months. Ong was deported to Singapore and sentenced in February 2003 to 12 years imprisonment, while McCrea was extradited to Singapore in 2005 and sentenced to 24 years imprisonment in June 2006.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Tan|first1=Yee Lin|title=Orchard Towers double murder|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/infopedia/articles/SIP_1603_2009-10-31.html|publisher=National Library Board, Singapore|accessdate=25 January 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150210053321/http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/infopedia/articles/SIP_1603_2009-10-31.html|archive-date=2015-02-10|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* December 2002: Australian [[Van Tuong Nguyen]] was convicted of carrying about 400 grams of heroin at [[Changi Airport]] while travelling from Cambodia to Australia and sentenced to death on 20 March 2004 by the [[High Court of Singapore|High Court]]. After a failed appeal to the [[Court of Appeal of Singapore|Court of Appeal]] and despite pleas for clemency from the Australian government, Nguyen was hanged on 2 December 2005.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/asia-pacific/4487366.stm|title=Australian executed in Singapore|date=2 December 2005|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=26 January 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141129075117/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/asia-pacific/4487366.stm|archive-date=2014-11-29|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===2003===\n\n* 21 March/8 April 2003: Already wanted for sex-related offences by Malaysian police, 28-year-old Malaysian Suresh Nair Vellayutham raped a clinic assistant in a cubicle of a female toilet on the morning of 21 March 2003. Then on the afternoon of 8 April 2003 at the Grand Hyatt hotel, he rushed into a hotel room where two air stewardess just entered and raped the 31-year-old air stewardess twice while molesting her 30-year-old colleague. Suresh was arrested on 11 April 2003. He was found guilty of rape, molestation and threatening his victims. He was sentenced to 26 years jail and 40 strokes of the cane.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/regional/2004/11/25/tormented-by-a-malaysian-serial-rapist|title=Tormented by a Malaysian serial rapist|last=|first=|date=2004-11-25|website=The Star Online|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191025200009/https://www.thestar.com.my/news/regional/2004/11/25/tormented-by-a-malaysian-serial-rapist|archive-date=2019-10-25|access-date=2019-10-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2003/11/30/malaysian-jailed-for-raping-singapore-stewardess|title=Malaysian jailed for raping Singapore stewardess|last=|first=|date=2003-11-30|website=The Star Online|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191025194147/https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2003/11/30/malaysian-jailed-for-raping-singapore-stewardess|archive-date=2019-10-25|access-date=2019-10-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://video.toggle.sg/en/video/series/true-files-s4/ep1/367500|title=True Files S4|website=Toggle|access-date=2019-10-25}}</ref>\n*25 December 2003: A 7-year-old girl was briefly kidnapped by two kidnappers: 35-year-old Tan Ping Koon and 42-year-old Chua Ser Lian. She was in the landed house at Yio Chu Kang when Chua sneaked in and took the girl into a car driven by Tan. A catering assistance caught them in the act and took down the license plate number. The info was relayed to the catering assistance's husband and when he spotted the getaway car, he decided to trail after them in his own vehicle. The two kidnappers realised they were followed and released the girl at Tampines. However, the two kidnappers called the girl's father the following day and demanded S$1 million from him or they would hurt her family. The sum of S$70,000 was eventually agreed and paid to them before Tan and Chua were subsequently arrested. They were both found guilty of kidnapping and sentenced to life imprisonment with three strokes of cane.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mothership.sg/2018/01/kidnap-cases-singapore/|title=Last 2 times children were kidnapped off the streets in S\u2019pore: 1999 & 2003|last=Lay|first=Belmont|date=2019-10-14|website=Mothership.sg|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191014114330/https://mothership.sg/2018/01/kidnap-cases-singapore/|archive-date=2019-10-14|access-date=2019-10-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://video.toggle.sg/en/video/series/crimewatch-2004/ep9/411072|title=Crimewatch 2004|website=Toggle|access-date=2019-10-14}}</ref>\n\n===2004===\n* 2 April 2004: 44-year-old Chia Teck Leng was sentenced to 42 years in jail by High Court Judge Tay Yong Kwang after swindling four foreign banks out of $117 million from 1999 to 2003 using his position as the financial manager of [[Asia Pacific Breweries]] (APB).<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/guilty-as-charged-chia-teck-leng-led-a-double-life-and-cheated-banks-of | title=Guilty As Charged: Chia Teck Leng led a double life and cheated banks of millions | publisher=Straits Times | date=16 May 2016 | accessdate=16 May 2016 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160517061212/http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/guilty-as-charged-chia-teck-leng-led-a-double-life-and-cheated-banks-of | archive-date=2016-05-17 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Longest jail term for the worst case of commercial fraud |url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/infopedia/articles/SIP_422_2005-01-25.html |publisher=NLB |accessdate=20 July 2019}}</ref>\n* 10 October 2004: Eight-year-old Huang Na was [[Murder of Huang Na|found dead and stuffed inside a box]] at [[Telok Blangah Hill Park]]. Malaysian Took Leng How, an acquaintance of Huang's mother, was found guilty of murder and sentenced to death on 27 August 2005. Took was hanged on 3 November 2006 after failing to overturn his conviction at the [[Court of Appeal of Singapore|Court of Appeal]] and after [[President of Singapore|President]] [[S. R. Nathan]] rejected his plea for clemency.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Tan|first1=Yee Lin|title=Huang Na murder|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/infopedia/articles/SIP_1604_2009-10-31.html|publisher=National Library Board, Singapore|accessdate=25 January 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150110042757/http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/infopedia/articles/SIP_1604_2009-10-31.html|archive-date=2015-01-10|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* November 2004: Nigerian [[Iwuchukwu Amara Tochi]] was arrested at Changi Airport for carrying 100 capsules containing heroin. He was hanged on 26 January 2007 after failing to overturn his conviction at the Court of Appeal and after President S. R. Nathan rejected his plea for clemency.<ref>{{cite news|title=Young Tochi hanged for heroin smuggling|url=http://www.smh.com.au/news/world/young-tochi-hanged-for-heroin-smuggling/2007/01/26/1169594481223.html|publisher=The Sydney Morning Herald|date=26 January 2007|accessdate=26 January 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160209074955/http://www.smh.com.au/news/world/young-tochi-hanged-for-heroin-smuggling/2007/01/26/1169594481223.html|archive-date=2016-02-09|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===2005===\n* 15\u201316 June 2005: Known as the [[Kallang]] body parts murder, factory supervisor Leong Siew Chor (\u6881\u5c11\u521d) murdered his lover, Chinese national Liu Hong Mei who was an ethnic Manchu woman from [[Northeastern China]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://news.sohu.com/20050620/n226015193.shtml|title=22\u5c81\u957f\u6625\u59d1\u5a18\u65b0\u52a0\u5761\u906d\u788e\u5c38 \u5acc\u72af\u5468\u4e94\u5c06\"\u8fc7\u5802\"-\u641c\u72d0\u65b0\u95fb\u4e2d\u5fc3|website=news.sohu.com}}</ref> and dismembered her body into seven parts. He dumped her body parts at multiple places across the island, such as [[Kallang River]]. He also stole her credit card and withdrew $2,000 from her bank account after having sex with her. He was arrested on 17 June 2005 and sentenced to death on 19 May 2006. Leong was hanged on 30 November 2007 after President S. R. Nathan rejected his plea for clemency.<ref name=\"Other gruesome murders that took place in Singapore\" /><ref>{{cite web|last1=Tok|first1=Cherylyn|title=Kallang body parts murder|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/infopedia/articles/SIP_1793_2011-03-17.html|publisher=National Library Board, Singapore|accessdate=25 January 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141227143223/http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/infopedia/articles/SIP_1793_2011-03-17.html|archive-date=2014-12-27|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* 7 September 2005: Filipino domestic worker Guen Garlejo Aguilar killed another Filipino domestic worker, Jane Parangan La Puebla, over a sum of S$2,000 that La Puebla owed her. She hid La Puebla's body in her room for two days before dismembering it and dumping the body parts near [[Orchard MRT station]] and [[MacRitchie Reservoir]]. The court found her guilty of manslaughter and sentenced her to 10 years imprisonment in May 2006.<ref name=\"Other gruesome murders that took place in Singapore\" />\n\n===2006===\n* 15 February 2006: In the first crime involving firearms since 2000, Tan Chor Jin, nicknamed the \"One-eyed Dragon\" forcefully entered the flat of Lim Hock Soon, a nightclub owner. He seized Lim's family valuables before tying up Lim, his wife, his daughter and Lim's maid. He then proceeded to shoot and kill Lim, where five of the six bullets hit Lim. He managed to flee the country with the help of his accomplice, Ho Yueh Keong. He was nabbed by the [[Royal Malaysian Police]] 10 days later at a hotel in Kuala Lumpur before being extradited back to Singapore on 1 March 2006. Initially charged with murder, his charge was amended to discharging of firearm. During the trial, Tan choose to be unrepresented. In one of his defence, he claimed that Lim was about to hit him with a chair and thus shot Lim in self-defence. But his defence fell flat when the prosecution noted that Lim was tied up and could not have lifted the chair. On 22 May 2007, he was found guilty and sentenced to hang. (Under Singapore law, offenders charged with unlawful discharge of firearms will be sentenced to death, even with no intention to kill.)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sso.agc.gov.sg/Act/AOA1973|title=Arms Offences Act - Singapore Statutes Online|last=|first=|date=|website=sso.agc.gov.sg|language=en|access-date=2019-10-13}}</ref> The Court of Appeal also dismissed Tan's appeal against his death sentence on 30 January 2008.<ref>{{cite web|title=Tan Chor Jin v Public Prosecutor [2008] 4 SLR 306; [2008] SGCA 32|url=http://www.singaporelaw.sg/sglaw/laws-of-singapore/case-law/free-law/court-of-appeal-judgments/13530-tan-chor-jin-v-public-prosecutor-2008-4-slr-306-2008-sgca-32|website=SingaporeLaw.sg|accessdate=25 January 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160130170543/http://www.singaporelaw.sg/sglaw/laws-of-singapore/case-law/free-law/court-of-appeal-judgments/13530-tan-chor-jin-v-public-prosecutor-2008-4-slr-306-2008-sgca-32|archive-date=30 January 2016|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> He was subsequently executed on 9 January 2009.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Teo|first1=Wan Gek|title=Donor 'designated kidney expressly' for Tang|newspaper=The Straits Times|location=Singapore|url=http://news.asiaone.com/News/the+Straits+Times/Story/A1Story20090111-113780.html|accessdate=25 January 2015|date=11 January 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160131175029/http://news.asiaone.com/News/the+Straits+Times/Story/A1Story20090111-113780.html|archive-date=31 January 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=The suspected murderer who shocked Singapore|url=http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/world/archives/2007/01/22/2003345842|accessdate=25 January 2015|agency=Taipei Times|date=22 January 2007|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140607153720/http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/world/archives/2007/01/22/2003345842|archive-date=2014-06-07|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/guilty-as-charged-one-eyed-dragon-tan-chor-jin-shot-nightclub-owner|title=Guilty As Charged: 'One-eyed Dragon' Tan Chor Jin shot nightclub owner|last=Hoe|first=Pei Shan|date=2016-05-17|website=The Straits Times|language=en|access-date=2019-10-13}}</ref> His accomplice, Ho, was charged on 15 July 2015 for harbouring Tan out of Singapore.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Alkhatib |first1=Shaffiq |url=https://www.tnp.sg/news/singapore-news/man-charged-harbouring-one-eyed-dragon |title=Man charged with harbouring 'One-Eyed Dragon' |website=The New Paper |access-date=13 October 2019 |date=15 July 2015}}</ref> Ho pleaded guilty on 8 August 2016.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Hussain |first1=Amir |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/one-eyed-dragon-tan-chor-jins-accomplice-found-guilty-after-9-years-on-the |title='One-eyed Dragon' Tan Chor Jin's accomplice found guilty after 9 years on the run |website=The Straits Times |access-date=13 October 2019 |date=8 August 2016}}</ref> Two days later, he was sentenced to a 20-month jail term.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Hussain |first1=Amir |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/one-eyed-dragon-tan-chor-jins-accomplice-jailed-20-months-after-9-years-on |title='One-eyed Dragon' Tan Chor Jin's accomplice jailed 20 months after 9 years on the run |website=The Straits Times |access-date=13 October 2019 |date=10 August 2016}}</ref>\n*June 2006: Lawyer David Rasif fled with S$11.3 million of his clients' money, one of the largest amount misappropriated by a rogue Singaporean lawyer. He was last seen by his wife in [[Bangkok]], [[Thailand]] on 5 June 2006. About S$7.4 million in cash and gold have been recovered and as of today, he is still at large.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.asiaone.com/singapore/fugitive-david-rasifs-daughter-new-face-first-runner|title=Fugitive David Rasif's daughter is New Face first runner-up / Who is David Rasif?|last=Yeoh|first=Wee Teck|date=2013-10-25|website=AsiaOne|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191016120749/https://www.asiaone.com/singapore/fugitive-david-rasifs-daughter-new-face-first-runner?nopaging=1|archive-date=2019-10-16|access-date=2019-10-16}}</ref>\n\n===2007===\n* 1 July 2007: 16-year-old teenager Muhammad Nasir Abdul Aziz was ordered by his lover, 24-year-old Aniza Binte Essa to murder her husband, 29-year-old Manap Sarlip. That early morning, Manap was stabbed nine times by Nasir at the lift landing area and just outside the husband and wife housing unit in Whampoa. Both Nasir and Aniza were arrested shortly after. Aniza initially faced the death penalty for abetting murder, which was later reduced to abetting manslaughter. A psychiatrist discovered she had a mental disorder that diminished her responsibility for the murder. She was sentenced to 9 years jail while Nasir pleaded guilty to murder. As he was under 18 years old when he killed Manap, he was spared the gallows and hence indefinitely detained under the President's pleasure.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.asiaone.com/News/AsiaOne+News/Crime/Story/A1Story20080415-59971.html|title=Teen detained under the President's pleasure for murder of lover's husband|last=|first=|date=|website=www.asiaone.com|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080523192115/https://www.asiaone.com/News/AsiaOne%2BNews/Crime/Story/A1Story20080415-59971.html|archive-date=2008-05-23|access-date=2019-10-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.asiaone.com/print/News/The+Straits+Times/Story/A1Story20080415-59845.html|title=Teen, 17, pleads guilty but won't be hanged|last=Lum|first=Selina|date=2008-04-15|website=www.asiaone.com|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080610120146/http://www.asiaone.com/print/News/The%2BStraits%2BTimes/Story/A1Story20080415-59845.html|archive-date=2008-06-10|access-date=2019-10-29}}</ref>\n\n===2008===\n* 27 February 2008: In a rare case of a criminal escaping from prison, [[Jemaah Islamiyah]] terrorist [[Mas Selamat Kastari]] discreetly escaped from the now defunct Whitley Road Detention Centre, sparking a nation-wide manhunt. He managed to flee Singapore across to Johor via a handmade floating device on 3 March 2008 and eventually hid himself in Skudai, Johor for about a year before he was arrested by Malaysia's Counter Terrorism Division on 1 April 2009.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/asia/se-asia/mas-selamat-hid-butter-used-mineral-water-bottles-in-escape-malaysia-police|title=Mas Selamat hid butter, used mineral water bottles in escape: Malaysia police|last=|first=|date=2017-03-26|website=The Straits Times|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180713051346/https://www.straitstimes.com/asia/se-asia/mas-selamat-hid-butter-used-mineral-water-bottles-in-escape-malaysia-police|archive-date=2018-07-13|access-date=2019-10-28}}</ref> He was repatriated back to Singapore on 24 September 2010 and detained indefinitely under the Internal Security Act.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.channelnewsasia.com/stories/afp_singapore/view/1083131/1/.html|title=Mas Selamat repatriated, detained under Singapore's ISA - Channel NewsAsia|last=|first=|date=2010-09-24|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111207031310/http://www.channelnewsasia.com/stories/afp_singapore/view/1083131/1/.html|archive-date=2011-12-07|access-date=2019-10-28}}</ref>\n*6 March 2008: 43-year-old Lim Bock Song had stabbed his drinking partner to death before fleeing to [[Outram Park MRT station]]. Following information by eyewitnesses, two policemen sighted Lim at the station's [[North East MRT line|North East Line]] platform. When confronted, Lim brandished his knife and advanced towards Staff Sergeant (SSG) Azli Othman. Despite SSG Azli drawing his revolver and warning Lim not to advance further, Lim charged towards SSG Azli before firing a shot at his chest. He was pronounced dead at the scene and a coroner's inquiry in 2010 concluded that SSG Azli's action was justified.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/shangri-la-shooting-police-shootings-very-rare-in-singapore|title=Shangri-La shooting: Police shootings very rare in Singapore / March 6, 2008|last=Goy|first=Priscilla|date=2015-06-01|website=The Straits Times|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191022154127/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/shangri-la-shooting-police-shootings-very-rare-in-singapore|archive-date=2019-10-22|access-date=2019-10-22}}</ref>\n*27 July - 23 August 2008: 18-year-old Fabian Adiu Edwin and 25-year-old Ellarry Puling, both Malaysian nationals, committed a series of robberies by targeting six victims between 27 July and 23 August that year. Their vicious robberies led to the death of one of their victims, 35-year-old security guard Loh Ee Hui. On 23 August, Fabian used a wooden stick to smack at Loh's head three times and stomped on his chest, while Ellarry acted as a lookout. Loh died in hospital from skull fractures. On 7 September that year, Fabian was arrested, followed by Ellarry the next day. In September 2011, Fabian was found guilty of murder and given the mandatory death sentence. However, in 2012, the mandatory death penalty law was revised. It reduces the sentence of death, for those convicted of drug trafficking or murder, to life imprisonment if conditions were met.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/murderer-fails-to-escape-the-gallows-6-other-cases-involving-the-revised|title=Murderer fails to escape the gallows: 6 other cases involving the revised death penalty laws|last=Abu Baker|first=Jalelah|date=16 January 2015|website=The Straits Times|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180321155910/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/murderer-fails-to-escape-the-gallows-6-other-cases-involving-the-revised|archive-date=21 March 2018|access-date=24 November 2019}}</ref> This enabled Fabian to undergo a retrial and on 17 July 2013, he became the first person to have his death sentence commuted to life imprisonment under the revised death penalty. His young age and low IQ were factors which spared him from the gallows, although Fabian will also receive 24 strokes of the cane.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://sg.news.yahoo.com/malaysian-escapes-gallows-singapore-law-reform-065353712.html|title=Malaysian escapes gallows after Singapore law reform|last=|first=|date=17 July 2013|website=sg.news.yahoo.com|publisher=AFP News|language=en-SG|via=Yahoo Singapore|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191125145940/https://sg.news.yahoo.com/malaysian-escapes-gallows-singapore-law-reform-065353712.html|archive-date=25 November 2019|access-date=2019-11-24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.asiaone.com/node/28592|title=Murderer escapes death sentence|last=Lum|first=Selina|date=19 July 2013|website=asiaone.com|publisher=The Straits Times|language=en|via=AsiaOne|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191125150111/https://www.asiaone.com/node/28592|archive-date=25 November 2019|access-date=24 November 2019}}</ref> In March 2012, Ellarry was found guilty of robbery with hurt and sentenced to 19 years imprisonment and 24 strokes of the cane.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://i88.photobucket.com/albums/k173/corpuncom/archive3/23949bxm.jpg|title=Man gets 19 years for part in violent robberies|last=Lum|first=Selina|date=25 November 2019|work=The Straits Times|access-date=24 November 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191125145804/https://i88.photobucket.com/albums/k173/corpuncom/archive3/23949bxm.jpg|archive-date=25 November 2019}}</ref>\n*19 September 2008: Famously known as the Yishun triple murder, Chinese national Wang Zhijian murdered his lover Zhang Meng, 41, Zhang's daughter Feng Jianyu, 17, and Zhang's flatmate Yang Jie, 36, in Zhang's house. He also attempted to murder Yang's daughter, Li Meilin, 15.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.asiaone.com/News/AsiaOne%2BNews/Crime/Story/A1Story20080919-88727.html |title=Three dead in Yishun killing frenzy |website=Asiaone |access-date=14 October 2019 |date=19 September 2008}}</ref> At the end of the trial on 30 November 2012, he was sentenced to death for only Yang's murder while successfully raising the defence of diminished responsibility for the murder of the other two.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Phua |first1=Amanda |url=https://www.asiaone.com/News/Latest%2BNews/Singapore/Story/A1Story20121201-387103.html |title=Yishun triple murderer 'tried to silence the witnesses': Judge |website=Asiaone |access-date=14 October 2019 |date=1 December 2012}}</ref> On 30 November 2014, during the cross-appeal between Wang and the prosecution, Wang's appeal against the death sentence was rejected while the prosecution's appeal was allowed, which made Wang guilty of all three murders.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Lum |first1=Selina |url=https://www.asiaone.com/singapore/yishun-murders-death-penalty-stands |title=Yishun murders: Death penalty stands |website=Asiaone |access-date=14 October 2019 |date=1 December 2014}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title = Yishun triple murders: A look back at the case|url = http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/yishun-triple-murders-a-look-back-at-the-case|website = The Straits Times|accessdate = 2015-10-18|last = migration|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20151107054145/http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/yishun-triple-murders-a-look-back-at-the-case|archive-date = 2015-11-07|url-status = live}}</ref>\n\n===2009===\n* April 2009: Chinese national Wang Wenfeng was sentenced to death for murdering taxi driver Yuen Swee Hong. Although he failed in his appeal against his sentence in the Court of Appeal in July 2012, he was re-sentenced to life imprisonment and caning in 2013 after changes to the law took effect that year.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lee|first1=Amanda|title=Man spared the gallows despite killing cabbie|newspaper=Today|location=Singapore|url=http://www.todayonline.com/singapore/man-spared-gallows-despite-killing-cabbie|accessdate=25 January 2015|date=14 November 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160129231901/http://www.todayonline.com/singapore/man-spared-gallows-despite-killing-cabbie|archive-date=2016-01-29|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==2010s==\n\n===2010===\n*29 May 2010: Four East Malaysians from Sarawak: 21-year-old Micheal Garing, 31-year-old Tony Anak Imba, 20-year-old Hairee Landak and 19-year-old Donny Meluda decided to commit a vicious robbery spree.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.asiaone.com/singapore/i-asked-why-he-had-parang|title='I asked why he had parang'|last=ALKHATIB|first=SHAFFIQ|date=19 October 2013|website=AsiaOne|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190407084855/https://www.asiaone.com/singapore/i-asked-why-he-had-parang|archive-date=7 April 2019|access-date=2019-04-07}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/kallang-slashings-jail-for-man-who-fled-singapore-killing-10946450|title=Kallang slashings: Jail for man who fled Singapore after construction worker killing|last=Lam|first=Lydia|date=19 November 2018|website=CNA|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181120125710/https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/kallang-slashings-jail-for-man-who-fled-singapore-killing-10946450|archive-date=20 November 2018|access-date=2019-04-07|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Armed with assorted weapons, ranging from [[Parang (knife)|parang]] to tap handle, they prowled Sims Ave and Kallang area at night. They brutally assaulted three separate male victims without warning and robbed them, with each of them sustaining serious injuries. Then their fourth target, 41-year-old construction worker Shanmuganathan Dillidurai, was kicked off from his bicycle and repeatedly slashed. Dillidurai died at the scene. All, but Meluda were soon arrested as Meluda fled to Malaysia hours after the crimes were committed. On 18 January 2013, Landak was sentenced to 33-year jail and 24 strokes of cane for armed robbery with hurt.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/sarawak-cleaner-jailed-33-years-for-role-in-2010-kallang-slashings|title=Sarawak cleaner jailed 33 years for role in 2010 'Kallang slashings'|last1=Lum|first1=Selina|date=18 January 2013|website=The Straits Times|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191013164100/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/sarawak-cleaner-jailed-33-years-for-role-in-2010-kallang-slashings|archive-date=13 October 2019|access-date=31 October 2019}}</ref> On 20 April 2015, Garing, who was armed with a 58&nbsp;cm parang when he viciously attacked the fourth victim, was found guilty of murder and sentenced to death. Tony was also convicted of murder, however he was spared the gallows and was sentenced to life imprisonment and 24 strokes of cane.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/death-and-life-in-prison-for-two-men-from-sarawak-convicted-of-2010-kallang|title=Death and life in prison for two men from Sarawak convicted of 2010 Kallang slashings|last1=Hoe|first1=Pei Shan|date=20 April 2015|website=The Straits Times|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180207072532/http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/death-and-life-in-prison-for-two-men-from-sarawak-convicted-of-2010-kallang|archive-date=7 February 2018|access-date=31 October 2019}}</ref> The prosecution's appeal to impose the stiffer death sentence on Tony and Garing's appeal to lower his sentence to life imprisonment were both turned down by the Court of Appeal on 27 February 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/kallang-slashings-duos-sentences-upheld-by-appeal-court|title=Kallang slashings: Duo's sentences upheld by appeal court|last=Lum|first=Selina|date=2017-02-27|website=The Straits Times|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190407085105/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/kallang-slashings-duos-sentences-upheld-by-appeal-court|archive-date=7 April 2019|access-date=2019-11-12}}</ref> Meluda was caught on 14 January 2017 when he attempted to enter Sarawak from Kuala Lumpur after being on the run for more than six years,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/final-suspect-in-deadly-2010-kallang-slashings-arrested-in-msia-handed-over|title=Final suspect in deadly 2010 Kallang slashings arrested in Malaysia; handed over to Singapore police|last=|first=|date=18 January 2017|website=The Straits Times|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191013154608/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/final-suspect-in-deadly-2010-kallang-slashings-arrested-in-msia-handed-over|archive-date=13 October 2019|access-date=13 October 2019}}</ref> and was extradited to Singapore on 18 January 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.asiaone.com/singapore/kallang-slashings-appeal-court-defers-judgment-pair-convicted-murder|title=Kallang slashings: Appeal court defers judgment for pair convicted of murder|last=Lum|first=Selina|date=2017-01-26|website=AsiaOne|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191112173023/https://www.asiaone.com/singapore/kallang-slashings-appeal-court-defers-judgment-pair-convicted-murder|archive-date=12 November 2019|access-date=2019-11-12}}</ref> He was initially charged for murder on 20 January 2017,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/fourth-man-charged-with-2010-kallang-murder|title=Fourth man charged with 2010 Kallang murder after 6 years on the run|last1=Alkhatib|first1=Shaffiq Idris|date=20 January 2017|website=The Straits Times|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190407085052/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/fourth-man-charged-with-2010-kallang-murder|archive-date=7 April 2019|access-date=13 October 2019}}</ref> which was eventually reduced to armed robbery with hurt. On 19 November 2018, Meluda was sentenced to 33-year jail and 24 strokes of cane.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/last-member-of-gang-in-kallang-slashings-gets-33-years-jail-caning|title=Last member of gang in Kallang slashings gets 33 years' jail, caning|last=Lum|first=Selina|date=2018-11-20|website=The Straits Times|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181120034818/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/last-member-of-gang-in-kallang-slashings-gets-33-years-jail-caning|archive-date=20 November 2018|access-date=2019-04-07|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Garing was executed on the morning of 22 March 2019 after his appeal for clemency failed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/asia/se-asia/malaysian-convicted-of-murder-executed-in-singapore|title=Malaysian convicted of murder is executed in Singapore|last=|first=|date=2019-03-22|website=The Straits Times|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190327145003/https://www.straitstimes.com/asia/se-asia/malaysian-convicted-of-murder-executed-in-singapore|archive-date=27 March 2019|access-date=2019-04-07|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/kallang-slashings-malaysian-micheal-garing-2010-murder-executed-11370142|title=Kallang slashings: Malaysian convicted of 'savage, merciless' 2010 murder is executed|last=|first=|date=22 March 2019|website=CNA|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191113062246/https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/kallang-slashings-malaysian-micheal-garing-2010-murder-executed-11370142?cid=FBcna|archive-date=13 November 2019|access-date=13 November 2019}}</ref>\n*3 July 2010: Calvin Tan Jian Wei, Edwin Tan Jian An and Ho Boon Sheng intoxicated an 18-year-old pub waitress and raped her in a hotel in Jiak Chuan Road on the night of 3\u20134 July 2010. They were arrested in the morning of 4 July and sentenced in 2015 to imprisonment and caning.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lim|first1=Yvonne|title=Brothers jailed for assisting in rape of pub waitress|url=http://www.todayonline.com/singapore/brothers-jailed-assisting-rape-pub-waitress|accessdate=13 January 2015|publisher=MediaCorp Press Ltd|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150111215845/http://www.todayonline.com/singapore/brothers-jailed-assisting-rape-pub-waitress|archive-date=2015-01-11|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*30 October 2010: [[Republic Polytechnic]] student, Darren Ng, was involved in a 'staring' incident with a group of teenage gang members. He was then brutally attacked by them at [[NTUC Downtown East|Downtown East]] mall in [[Pasir Ris]] and later died in hospital. A total of 12 youths were charged for rioting and culpable homicide. They were sentenced to between 3 and 12 years jail, with all receiving caning of between 3 and 12 strokes.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://i88.photobucket.com/albums/k173/corpuncom/archive3/23914bxm.jpg|title=Jailed for Downtown east fight (First person convicted)|last=Chong|first=Elena|date=2012-03-07|work=The Straits Times|access-date=2019-10-13|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191013114220/https://i88.photobucket.com/albums/k173/corpuncom/archive3/23914bxm.jpg|archive-date=13 October 2019|via=https://www.corpun.com/}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://i88.photobucket.com/albums/k173/corpuncom/archive3/23970bxm.jpg|title=Downtown East case: 2nd youth jailed, ordered to be caned|last=Huang|first=Claire|date=2012-05-05|work=TODAY (Singapore)|access-date=2019-10-13|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191013114222/https://i88.photobucket.com/albums/k173/corpuncom/archive3/23970bxm.jpg|archive-date=13 October 2019|via=https://www.corpun.com/}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://i88.photobucket.com/albums/k173/corpuncom/archive3/24068axm.jpg|title=Four more youths charged for Downtown East riot|last=|first=|date=2012-07-19|work=TODAY (Singapore)|access-date=2019-10-13|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191013114214/https://i88.photobucket.com/albums/k173/corpuncom/archive3/24068axm.jpg|archive-date=13 October 2019|via=https://www.corpun.com/}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://i88.photobucket.com/albums/k173/corpuncom/archive3/24106bxm.jpg|title=Five youths jailed, caned over Downtown East murder|last=Lum|first=Selina|date=2012-09-08|work=The Straits Times|access-date=2019-10-13|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191013114219/https://i88.photobucket.com/albums/k173/corpuncom/archive3/24106bxm.jpg|archive-date=13 October 2019|via=https://www.corpun.com/}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://i88.photobucket.com/albums/k173/corpuncom/archive3/24125bxm.jpg|title=Youth involved in gang clash gets jail, caning (Last person convicted)|last=Singh|first=Khushwant|date=2012-09-25|work=The Straits Times|access-date=2019-10-13|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191013114221/https://i88.photobucket.com/albums/k173/corpuncom/archive3/24125bxm.jpg|archive-date=13 October 2019|via=https://www.corpun.com/}}</ref>\n\n===2011===\n*16 May 2011: The dead body of Ruliyawati, an Indonesian domestic worker, was discovered in the rooftop water tank of a flat in [[Woodlands, Singapore|Woodlands]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Indonesian maid's body found in Woodlands rooftop water tank|url=http://news.asiaone.com/News/AsiaOne+News/Singapore/Story/A1Story20110516-279169.html|accessdate=27 December 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150104173405/http://news.asiaone.com/News/AsiaOne+News/Singapore/Story/A1Story20110516-279169.html|archive-date=2015-01-04|url-status=live}}</ref> A coroner's inquest found that she had drowned herself but the two wounds on her back were caused by her boyfriend, Bangladeshi national Mohammed Repon Mostafa. Repon, who was initially accused of her death, was granted a discharge not amounting to an acquittal in 2013.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Jalelah Abu Baker|title=Water tank death: Maid drowned but two wounds were caused by boyfriend|newspaper=The Straits Times|url=http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/water-tank-death-maid-drowned-but-two-wounds-were-caused-by-boyfriend|accessdate=23 January 2016|date=May 2, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160208003110/http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/water-tank-death-maid-drowned-but-two-wounds-were-caused-by-boyfriend|archive-date=2016-02-08|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===2012===\n*28 May 2012: The police found the body of Mallika Jesudasan, 56, with neck injuries in a flat in [[Bukit Batok]]. Jesudasan was said to have been killed in a bedroom by her 31-year-old son, Sujay Solomon Sutherson, believed to be mentally ill.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Suspect in Bukit Batok murder charged|url = http://news.asiaone.com/News/Latest+News/Singapore/Story/A1Story20120529-349002.html|website = news.asiaone.com|accessdate = 2015-10-27|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160217054550/http://news.asiaone.com/News/Latest+News/Singapore/Story/A1Story20120529-349002.html|archive-date = 2016-02-17|url-status = live}}</ref> Sujay was convicted of culpable homicide not amounting to murder on 15 September 2015 and sentenced to life imprisonment.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Siau|first1=Ming En|title=Man who slit his mum's throat sentenced to life imprisonment|url=http://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/cy-man-who-slit-mum-s/2129376.html|accessdate=23 January 2016|agency=Channel News Asia|date=16 September 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160131104058/http://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/cy-man-who-slit-mum-s/2129376.html|archive-date=2016-01-31|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===2013===\n*10 July 2013: Staff Sergeant Iskandar bin Rahmat murdered 67-year-old Tan Boon Sin and his 42-year-old son Tan Chee Heong. The body of the elder Tan was found in his home at Hillside Drive in Kovan while the body of his son was dragged under a car for 1&nbsp;km from the home before being dislodged outside [[Kovan MRT station]].<ref>{{Cite web|title = 'I was fearing for my life': Kovan double murders accused claims self-defence|url = http://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/i-was-fearing-for-my-life/2228116.html|accessdate = 2015-12-02|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20151205162528/http://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/i-was-fearing-for-my-life/2228116.html|archive-date = 2015-12-05|url-status = live}}</ref> Justice [[Tay Yong Kwang]] of the [[High Court of Singapore|High Court]] found Iskandar guilty of murder on 4 December 2015 and sentenced him to death.<ref>{{cite web|title=Public Prosecutor v Iskandar bin Rahmat [2015] SGHC 310|url=http://www.singaporelawwatch.sg/slw/attachments/74322/%5B2015%5D%20SGHC%20310.pdf|website=Singapore Law Watch|accessdate=23 January 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160129084708/http://www.singaporelawwatch.sg/slw/attachments/74322/%5B2015%5D%20SGHC%20310.pdf|archive-date=2016-01-29|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*16 November 2013: Tuti Aeliyah, a 28-year-old Indonesian domestic helper, stabbed and strangled her employer's daughter, 16-year-old Shameera Basha Noor Basha, to death.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Domestic helper charged with murder for allegedly stabbing employer's daughter to death|url = http://www.todayonline.com/singapore/domestic-helper-charged-murder-allegedly-stabbing-employers-daughter-death|website = TODAYonline|accessdate = 2015-10-27|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160129231911/http://www.todayonline.com/singapore/domestic-helper-charged-murder-allegedly-stabbing-employers-daughter-death|archive-date = 2016-01-29|url-status = live}}</ref> She was initially charged with murder, but the charge was reduced to culpable homicide after she was diagnosed to be suffering from severe depression with psychotic symptoms. The High Court found her guilty and sentenced her to 12 years imprisonment in May 2015.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lum|first1=Selina|title=Maid jailed 12 years for strangling 16-year-old girl with pinafore|newspaper=The Straits Times|url=http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/maid-jailed-12-years-for-strangling-16-year-old-girl-with-pinafore|accessdate=23 January 2016|date=25 May 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160208003023/http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/maid-jailed-12-years-for-strangling-16-year-old-girl-with-pinafore|archive-date=2016-02-08|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*25 November 2013: 44-year-old Lim Ann Nee allegedly drowned her 17-month-old son, Emilien Lacroix, in the sea off [[East Coast Park]] and was charged with murder. She was found to be suffering from acute transient psychotic disorder and had her charge reduced to culpable homicide in 2014. On 24 March 2015, she was given a discharge not amounting to an acquittal.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Chong|first1=Elena|title=Woman given a discharge over son's death as she was of unsound mind then|newspaper=The Straits Times|url=http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/woman-given-a-discharge-over-sons-death-as-she-was-of-unsound-mind-then|accessdate=23 January 2016|date=24 March 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160208002959/http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/woman-given-a-discharge-over-sons-death-as-she-was-of-unsound-mind-then|archive-date=2016-02-08|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*8 December 2013: Known as the [[2013 Little India riot|Little India riot]], it was Singapore's first riot since [[1969 race riots of Singapore|1969]]. About 400 men rioted in [[Little India, Singapore|Little India]] after an earlier fatal bus accident resulted in a fatality. 28 men were arrested at the scene, of whom four were released. 52 Indian nationals and one Bangladeshi national were repatriated.\n*12 December 2013: 33-year-old Jasvinder Kaur's decapitated body was found in Whampoa River. The body was topless and missing two arms, only dressed in a pair of black pants. 25-year-old forklift driver Gursharan Singh, was charged with murder, while the other suspect, 33-year-old Harvinder Singh, Kaur's husband, is on the run and on [[Interpol]]'s wanted list.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Headless body murder an organised crime of passion: Coroner's report|url = http://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/headless-body-murder-an/2013196.html|website = Channel NewsAsia|accessdate = 2015-10-27|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20151102061417/http://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/headless-body-murder-an/2013196.html|archive-date = 2015-11-02|url-status = live}}</ref> In July 2015, a coroner's court found that Kaur had been murdered by Harvinder Singh. In April 2015, Gursharan Singh was sentenced to 30 months imprisonment for assisting Harvinder Singh in disposing Kaur's body and for failing to make a police report.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Ho|first1=Olivia|title=Headless woman killed by hubby: Court|newspaper=The Straits Times|url=http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/headless-woman-killed-by-hubby-court|accessdate=23 January 2016|date=29 July 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160208001225/http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/headless-woman-killed-by-hubby-court|archive-date=2016-02-08|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*28-29 December: 37-year-old Dexmon Chua Yizhi was murdered in a van, with his body found in Lim Chu Kang on 1 January 2014. 2 suspects, 53-year-old Chia Kee Chen and 64-year-old Chua Leong Aik were charged with murder, with the third suspect, Djatmiko Febri Irwansyah (late 20s), having fled Singapore.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Chong |first1=Elena |title=Man charged with murder at Choa Chu Kang multi-storey carpark |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/man-charged-with-murder-at-choa-chu-kang-multi-storey-carpark |accessdate=15 December 2019 |publisher=The Straits Times |date=2 January 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Lim |first1=Yan Liang |title=Choa Chu Kang Murder: Second man charged and remanded for further investigations |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/choa-chu-kang-murder-second-man-charged-and-remanded-for-further-investigations |accessdate=14 July 2019 |publisher=The Straits Times |date=10 January 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Lim Chu Kang murder: Police seek Indonesian man |url=https://www.todayonline.com/singapore/lim-chu-kang-murder-police-seek-indonesian-man |accessdate=14 July 2019 |agency=Todayonline |date=3 January 2014}}</ref> In January 2016, Chua was jailed for five years for his role in the murder.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Law |first1=Elizabeth |title=Revenge attack so savage it left bloodstains on van's ceiling |url=https://www.tnp.sg/news/singapore/revenge-attack-so-savage-it-left-bloodstains-vans-ceiling |accessdate=14 July 2019 |publisher=The New Paper |date=9 January 2016}}</ref> In August 2017, Chia was sentenced to life in jail.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Chelvan |first1=Vanessa Paige |title=Man convicted of murder for beating wife\u2019s former lover to death |url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/man-convicted-of-murder-for-beating-wife-s-former-lover-to-death-7574916 |accessdate=14 July 2019 |publisher=The Straits Times |date=17 January 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Ng |first1=Kelly |title=Businessman who killed wife's ex-lover spared the gallows, jailed for life |url=https://www.todayonline.com/singapore/businessman-who-killed-wifes-ex-lover-jailed-life |accessdate=14 July 2019 |publisher=Todayonline |date=4 August 2017}}</ref> However, the prosecution appealed, which was allowed by the apex court. It overturned the life sentence, sentencing Chia to death.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Lum |first1=Selina |title=Businessman who murdered wife's ex-lover sentenced to death upon prosecution's appeal |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/apex-court-hands-down-death-penalty-to-businessman-for-murdering-wifes-ex |accessdate=14 July 2019 |publisher=The Straits Times |date=27 June 2018}}</ref> Djatmiko Febri Irwansyah is still on the run.\n\n===2014===\n*8 January 2014: In the first such case of kidnapping after a decade of hiatus, 41-year-old Lee Sze Yong and 50-year-old Heng Chen Boon kidnapped 79-year-old Ng Lye Poh along Hougang Ave 8. One of Mdm Ng's son is Mr Lim Hock Chee, who is the chief executive officer of [[Sheng Siong]], a well-known supermarket chain in Singapore. That morning, Lee tricked Mdm Ng to get into a car before blindfolding her. He then demanded from Mr Lim a ransom of S$20 million. The sum was eventually reduced to S$2 million and Mdm Ng was released at Seletar West Camp area at around midnight. Both Lee and Heng were arrested shortly after Mdm Ng's release. The S$2 million ransom was fully recovered at Sembawang park, the place where the kidnappers ordered Lim to drop the ransom.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.asiaone.com/singapore/sheng-siong-kidnap-elderly-victim-was-led-car-and-later-blindfolded|title=Sheng Siong kidnap: Elderly victim was led to car and later blindfolded|last=Lum|first=Selina|date=2016-09-02|website=AsiaOne|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191013152420/https://www.asiaone.com/singapore/sheng-siong-kidnap-elderly-victim-was-led-car-and-later-blindfolded|archive-date=2019-10-13|access-date=2019-10-13}}</ref> Heng, who was originally charged with kidnapping, had his charge reduced. In May 2015, he pleaded guilty to abetting Lee to abduct Ng, and was sentenced to three years imprisonment. In November 2016, Lee was charged with kidnapping and sentenced to life imprisonment and 3 strokes of cane.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Alkatib|first1=Shaffiq|title=Lawyers of Sheng Siong kidnapping accomplice say he was too trusting of friend he helped|url=http://news.asiaone.com/news/singapore/lawyers-sheng-siong-kidnapping-accomplice-say-he-was-too-trusting-friend-he-helped|website=Asia One|accessdate=23 January 2016|date=14 May 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160217054513/http://news.asiaone.com/news/singapore/lawyers-sheng-siong-kidnapping-accomplice-say-he-was-too-trusting-friend-he-helped|archive-date=2016-02-17|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/sheng-siong-kidnapping-life-imprisonment-caning-for-kidnapper-7652602|title=Sheng Siong kidnapping: Life imprisonment, caning for kidnapper|last=Paige Chelvan|first=Vanessa|date=2019-10-13|website=CNA|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191013152749/https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/sheng-siong-kidnapping-life-imprisonment-caning-for-kidnapper-7652602|archive-date=2019-10-13|access-date=2019-10-13}}</ref>\n*4 June 2014: 51-year-old Andrea Tay Su Lin killed her 75-year-old mother, Rosaline Lim, at their flat in [[Ang Mo Kio]]. She then committed suicide by throwing herself out from the window. Tay had a poor relationship with her mother, whom she blamed for her grandmother's death.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Chong|first1=Elena|title=Ang Mo Kio double death: Woman killed mum and took her own life, says coroner|newspaper=The Straits Times|url=http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/ang-mo-kio-double-death-woman-killed-mum-and-took-her-own-life-says-coroner|accessdate=23 January 2016|date=3 December 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160208003048/http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/ang-mo-kio-double-death-woman-killed-mum-and-took-her-own-life-says-coroner|archive-date=2016-02-08|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*11 June 2014: A body without legs was found in a luggage at Syed Alwi Road, [[Little India, Singapore|Little India]]. Two Pakistani men were arrested as suspects in the case.<ref>{{cite news|title=Grisly legless body find: Two Pakistanis held for murder|url=http://www.todayonline.com/singapore/grisly-legless-body-find-two-pakistanis-held-murder|accessdate=27 December 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140617093704/http://www.todayonline.com/singapore/grisly-legless-body-find-two-pakistanis-held-murder|archive-date=2014-06-17|url-status=live}}</ref> On 17 February 2016, they were found guilty of murder and sentenced to death.<ref>{{cite news|title=Legless body in suitcase: Duo found guilty, to hang for murder|newspaper=The Straits Times|url=http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/legless-body-in-suitcase-duo-found-guilty-to-hang-for-murder?xtor=CS1-10#link_time=1487299045|accessdate=18 February 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181002051947/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/legless-body-in-suitcase-duo-found-guilty-to-hang-for-murder?xtor=CS1-10#link_time=1487299045|archive-date=2 October 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n*21 August 2014: 80-year-old Char Chin Fah was accused of murdering his daughter-in-law, 54-year-old Ong Guat Leng, in their home in [[Tampines]]. Chin was remanded at Complex Medical Centre in [[Changi]] for psychiatric assessment in August 2014. He was sentenced to 8 years in jail in 2016.<ref>{{cite news|last=Poh|first=Ian|title=Tampines murder case: 80-year-old accused remanded for psychiatric evaluation|newspaper=The Straits Times|url=http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/tampines-murder-case-80-year-old-accused-remanded-for-psychiatric-evaluation|accessdate=23 January 2016|date=27 August 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160208003011/http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/tampines-murder-case-80-year-old-accused-remanded-for-psychiatric-evaluation|archive-date=2016-02-08|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*20 November 2014: 40-year-old Jackson Lim Hou Peng was accused of murdering a Vietnamese woman, 32-year-old Tran Cam Ny, in a flat in [[Ang Mo Kio]]. On 19 December 2014, Lim was found to be \"not of unsound mind\" after an extended period of psychiatric evaluation and was due to be tried in court.<ref>{{cite news|last=Lim|first=Yvonne|title=Man accused of murdering Vietnamese woman fit to plead in court|newspaper=Today|url=http://www.todayonline.com/singapore/man-accused-murdering-vietnamese-woman-fit-plead-court|accessdate=23 January 2016|date=19 December 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160130060213/http://www.todayonline.com/singapore/man-accused-murdering-vietnamese-woman-fit-plead-court|archive-date=2016-01-30|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*29 November 2014 - 9 January 2015: A 31-year-old man raped his 14-year-old daughter multiple times over a period of 3 months in their family flat at Punggol. The case came to light after a police report was filed when her boyfriend at that time arranged her to see their school counsellor. On 14 November 2018, the man was sentenced to 26-year jail and 24 strokes of cane.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/technician-found-guilty-of-raping-teenage-daughter|title=Technician found guilty of raping teenage daughter|last=hermesauto|date=2018-10-15|website=The Straits Times|language=en|access-date=2019-04-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181103102518/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/technician-found-guilty-of-raping-teenage-daughter|archive-date=3 November 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/man-who-raped-teenage-daughter-gets-26-years-jail-24-strokes|title=Man who raped teenage daughter gets 26 years' jail, 24 strokes|last=hermesauto|date=2018-11-14|website=The Straits Times|language=en|access-date=2019-04-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190218225314/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/man-who-raped-teenage-daughter-gets-26-years-jail-24-strokes|archive-date=18 February 2019|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n*17 December 2014: Zheng Xianghua, a Chinese national, stabbed himself after allegedly killing Wang Xueyan, also a Chinese national, in a flat in [[Tampines]]. He was charged with murder on 20 December 2014,<ref>{{Cite web|title=Man charged in Tampines murder case|url=http://news.asiaone.com/news/crime/man-charged-tampines-murder-case|website=Asia One|accessdate=23 January 2016|date=21 December 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160217063137/http://news.asiaone.com/news/crime/man-charged-tampines-murder-case|archive-date=2016-02-17|url-status=live}}</ref> but the charge was subsequently reduced to culpable homicide not amounting to murder, and Zheng was sentenced to 9 years' imprisonment on 11 April 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Truck driver jailed 9 years for killing wife he suspected of having affair|url=http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/truck-driver-jailed-9-years-for-killing-wife-he-suspected-of-having-affair|website=The Straits Times|accessdate=26 May 2016|date=11 April 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160416225430/http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/truck-driver-jailed-9-years-for-killing-wife-he-suspected-of-having-affair|archive-date=2016-04-16|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===2015===\n* 13 April 2015: Annie Ee Yu Lian, a 26-year-old waitress, died from acute fat [[embolism]] as a result of systematic abuse from her flatmates in a flat at Woodlands for 8 months. The couple, Tan Hui Zhen and her husband Pua Hak Chuan, were charged with voluntarily causing grievous hurt with a dangerous weapon resulting in Ee's death and were sentence to 16.5 years and 14 years jail respectively on 1 December 2017. In addition, Pua was given 14 strokes of the cane.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sg.news.yahoo.com/couple-admits-causing-flatmates-death-systematic-abuse-145204129.html|title=Couple admit to causing flatmate\u2019s death through \u2018systematic\u2019 abuse|access-date=2018-01-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180112101217/https://sg.news.yahoo.com/couple-admits-causing-flatmates-death-systematic-abuse-145204129.html|archive-date=2018-01-12|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*1 June 2015: Known as the [[Shooting of Taufik Zahar|Shangri-La shooting]], a car driven by 34-year-old Mohamad Taufik Zahar took an incorrect turn and ended up at a high security checkpoint. Fearing arrest and drugs being uncovered, he was told to speed off by one of his passengers. [[Gurkha Contingent|Gurkha officers]] neutralised the threat by firing five shots. One of the bullets shot Taufik to death before the car came to a halt.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/shangri-la-shooting-car-took-wrong-turn-into-security-zone|title=Shangri-La shooting: Car took wrong turn into security zone|last=Hussain|first=Amir|date=2016-01-27|website=The Straits Times|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190210221156/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/shangri-la-shooting-car-took-wrong-turn-into-security-zone|archive-date=2019-02-10|access-date=2019-10-22}}</ref> In 2016, a coroner's inquiry ruled Taufik's death as 'a lawful killing'.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/drivers-death-in-shangrila-la-shooting-case-ruled-a-lawful-killing|title=Driver's death in Shangri-La shooting case ruled 'a lawful killing'|last=Pang|first=Xue Qiang|date=2016-04-22|website=The Straits Times|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190704133939/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/drivers-death-in-shangrila-la-shooting-case-ruled-a-lawful-killing|archive-date=2019-07-04|access-date=2019-10-22}}</ref>\n*20 June 2015: Known as the [[Khoo Teck Puat Hospital]] (KTPH) shooting, it is another rare case involving a policeman's revolver being snatched. 24-year-old Muhammad Iskandar Sa\u2019at was arrested on 19 June 2015 for theft of motor vehicle and was escorted to KTPH by two policemen when he claimed to have chest pain. His grip restraints were loosened on his left arm and right wrist for blood drawing and minimising discomfort respectively. While one of the policeman left the examination room to break fast, 31-year-old Staff Sergeant (SSG) Muhammad Sadli Razali was on his mobile phone. Iskandar out of a sudden assaulted SSG Sadli and attempted to escape. As SSG Sadli held on to his legs, Iskandar snatched SSG Sadli's revolver. Even when Iskandar was pinned to the ground, he fired three shots at SSG Sadli. Iskandar was eventually subdued. SSG Sadli suffered gunshot wounds on his left thumb and right root. Iskandar was charged on 22 June 2015 for unlawful discharge of firearms<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/man-charged-over-unlawful-discharge-of-a-firearm-in-khoo-teck-puat-hospital|title=Man charged over unlawful discharge of a firearm in Khoo Teck Puat hospital shooting|last=Rei|first=Kurohi|date=2015-06-22|website=The Straits Times|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190703025426/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/man-charged-over-unlawful-discharge-of-a-firearm-in-khoo-teck-puat-hospital|archive-date=3 July 2019|access-date=2019-11-12}}</ref> and on 19 March 2018, Iskandar was sentenced to life imprisonment and 18 strokes of the cane.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/man-who-shot-police-officer-gets-life-term-in-jail-caning|title=Man who snatched police officer's revolver and fired three shots gets life term in jail, caning|last=K.C.|first=Vijayan|date=2018-03-20|website=The Straits Times|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190703025407/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/man-who-shot-police-officer-gets-life-term-in-jail-caning|archive-date=3 July 2019|access-date=2019-11-12}}</ref>\n*5 October 2015: Belgian national Philippe Graffart allegedly murdered his five-year-old son, Keryan Graffart, at their D'Leedon condominium along Farrer Road.<ref>{{cite news|title=Singapore police extend investigation of Belgian charged with son's murder|url=http://www.bangkokpost.com/news/asean/782849/singapore-police-extend-investigation-of-belgian-charged-with-son-murder|accessdate=2 December 2015|agency=AFP}}</ref> The murder charge was later reduced to culpable homicide, and found that he suffered from major depressive disorder during a custody battle. On 1 August, Philippe pleaded guilty and was sentenced to five years jail on 22 August 2016.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Chelvan |first1=Vanessa Paige |title=D'Leedon murder: Belgian expat admits to killing 5-year-old son |url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/d-leedon-murder-belgian-expat-admits-to-killing-5-year-old-son-7881934 |accessdate=14 July 2019 |publisher=CNA |date=1 August 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Belgian expat jailed for 5 years for killing son |url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/belgian-expat-jailed-for-5-years-for-killing-son-7863634 |accessdate=14 July 2019 |publisher=CNA |date=22 August 2016}}</ref>\n*22 November 2015: 26-year-old Neo Chun Zheng murdered former [[Scoot]] air stewardess, 23-year-old Soh Yuan Lin, by stabbing her in the neck with a knife outside his HDB flat in [[Boon Lay]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lee|first1=Pearl|title=Man charged with murder of former air stewardess|url=http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/man-charged-with-murder-of-former-air-stewardess|accessdate=3 December 2015|publisher=Straits Times|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151202050005/http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/man-charged-with-murder-of-former-air-stewardess|archive-date=2015-12-02|url-status=live}}</ref> Neo pleaded guilty to culpable homicide and was sentenced to 13 years jail on 12 November 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/boon-lay-killing-possessive-man-gets-13-years-jail-for-stabbing-former-air|title=Boon Lay killing: Possessive man gets 13 years' jail for stabbing former air stewardess|last=hermesauto|date=2018-11-12|website=The Straits Times|language=en|access-date=2019-04-05|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190211132000/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/boon-lay-killing-possessive-man-gets-13-years-jail-for-stabbing-former-air|archive-date=11 February 2019|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n*30 December 2015: 64-year-old general practitioner Wee Teong Boo sexually assaulted a 23-year-old student in his clinic when she went for a consultation. Initially charged with rape, the courts found him guilty of sexual assault by penetration, based on his admission that he inserted his ungloved finger, lubricated with his saliva into her vagina and that he had erectile dysfunction. As the victim was molested by Wee a month prior to the incident as well, Wee was also convicted of molestation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tnp.sg/news/singapore/doctor-cleared-rape-guilty-sexual-assault|title=Doctor cleared of rape but guilty of sexual assault|last=Lum|first=Selina|last2=|first2=|date=2019-02-26|website=The New Paper|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190226060408/https://www.tnp.sg/news/singapore/doctor-cleared-rape-guilty-sexual-assault|archive-date=2019-02-26|access-date=2019-10-22}}</ref> On 27 February 2019, Wee was sentenced to 10-year jail.<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/doctor-gets-10-years-jail-for-sexually-assaulting-and-molesting-patient-in|title=Doctor gets 10 years' jail for sexually assaulting and molesting patient in his clinic|last=Lum|first=Selina|date=2019-02-27|website=The Straits Times|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190309071048/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/doctor-gets-10-years-jail-for-sexually-assaulting-and-molesting-patient-in|archive-date=9 March 2019|access-date=2019-04-07|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===2016===\n*14 February 2016: 47-year-old Singaporean Loh Suan Lit murdered 57-year old Teck Whye Chin Long Kong Temple helper Tan Poh Huat.<ref>{{cite news|title=47-year-old Singaporean charged with Teck Whye temple murder|url=http://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/video/47-year-old-singaporean/2552822.html|accessdate=7 March 2016|publisher=CNA|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160307221409/http://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/video/47-year-old-singaporean/2552822.html|archive-date=2016-03-07|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Man charged with Teck Whye temple murder brought to various crime scenes|url=http://razor.tv/section/77922/vertical.html?movideo_p=77922&movideo_m=1467786|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160307163421/http://razor.tv/section/77922/vertical.html?movideo_p=77922&movideo_m=1467786|url-status=dead|archive-date=7 March 2016|publisher=The New Paper|accessdate=7 March 2016}}</ref> The charge was later reduced to a count of culpable homicide in addition to an unrelated charge for burgling a food stall. Loh was sentenced to a total of 14 years jail and six strokes of the cane on 15 January 2018.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Lum |first1=Selina |title=Jobless man who killed temple helper in aborted burglary gets 14 years' jail, caning |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/jobless-man-who-killed-temple-helper-in-aborted-burglary-gets-14-years-jail |accessdate=14 July 2019 |publisher=The Straits Times |date=15 January 2018}}</ref>\n*25 February 2016: 50-year-old coffee-shop assistant Khor Tzoong Meng murdered 38-year-old Ang Kim Keat at Blk 23 [[Hougang]] Avenue 3.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Ong|first1=Justin|title=Coffeeshop assistant charged for Hougang murder|url=http://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/coffeeshop-assistant/2550538.html|accessdate=7 March 2016|publisher=CNA|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160307164337/http://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/coffeeshop-assistant/2550538.html|archive-date=2016-03-07|url-status=live}}</ref> The murder charge was later reduced to culpable homicide. Khor pleaded guilty and was sentenced to eight years jail on 31 July 2017.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Lum |first1=Selina |title=Coffeeshop assistant jailed 8 years for fatal slashing of patron over self-service policy |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/coffeeshop-assistant-jailed-8-years-for-fatal-slashing-of-patron-over-self |accessdate=14 July 2019 |publisher=The Straits Times |date=31 July 2017}}</ref> \n*13 March 2016: 68-year-old Kong Peng Yee murdered his wife 63-year-old Wong Chik Yeok at [[Compassvale]] Crescent.<ref>{{cite news|title=Man charged with wife's murder|url=http://news.asiaone.com/news/crime/man-charged-wifes-murder|accessdate=16 March 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160317072512/http://news.asiaone.com/news/crime/man-charged-wifes-murder|archive-date=2016-03-17|url-status=live}}</ref> The murder charge was reduced to culpable homicide as he suffered from a psychotic episode during the time of crime. On 16 October 2017, Kong was sentenced to two years jail.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Chelvan |first1=Vanessa Paige |title=69-year-old retiree pleads guilty to stabbing wife to death |url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/69-year-old-retiree-pleads-guilty-to-stabbing-wife-to-death-9197928 |accessdate=14 July 2019 |publisher=CNA |date=8 September 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Lum |first1=Selina |title=Judge gives man shortest sentence of 2 years\u2019 jail for killing wife |url=https://www.tnp.sg/news/singapore/judge-gives-man-shortest-sentence-2-years-jail-killing-wife |accessdate=14 July 2019 |publisher=The New Paper |date=17 October 2017}}</ref> The case was appealed to the Court of Appeal, which increased the sentence to six years jail on 27 June 2018.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Lum |first1=Selina |title=Court of Appeal decides on more jail time for man who killed wife in psychotic episode |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/court-of-appeal-decides-on-more-jail-time-for-man-who-killed-wife-in |accessdate=14 July 2019 |publisher=The Straits Times |date=27 June 2018}}</ref>\n*21 March 2016: 47-year-old Boh Soon Ho was charged on 7 April 2016<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/man-to-be-charged-with-murder-of-woman-in-circuit-road-flat|title=Man, 47, charged with murder of woman in Circuit Road flat|last=Hussain|first=Amir|date=2016-04-07|website=The Straits Times|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190207060624/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/man-to-be-charged-with-murder-of-woman-in-circuit-road-flat|archive-date=2019-02-07|access-date=2019-10-22}}</ref> for strangling his 28-year-old girlfriend, Chinese national Zhang Huaxiang to death. He fled to Malaysia before he was arrested by the Royal Malaysian Police and brought back to Singapore to face trial, which is ongoing.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/circuit-road-murder-trial-accused-said-he-spent-money-on-nurse-but-got|title=Circuit Road murder trial: Accused said he spent money on nurse but got nothing|last=Lum|first=Selina|date=2019-09-19|website=The Straits Times|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190921163611/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/circuit-road-murder-trial-accused-said-he-spent-money-on-nurse-but-got|archive-date=2019-09-21|access-date=2019-10-22}}</ref>\n*8 May 2016: 30-year-old maid Maryani Usman Utar punched and straggled one-year-old Richelle Teo Yan Jia over what she perceived as poor treatment by her employers. Charged with culpable homicide not amounting to murder, Maryani was sentenced to 7-year jail in 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/indonesian-maid-charged-over-death-of-1-year-old-girl-in-simei-flat|title=Indonesian maid charged over death of 1-year-old girl in Simei flat|last=hermesauto|date=2016-05-10|website=The Straits Times|language=en|access-date=2019-04-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190213105008/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/indonesian-maid-charged-over-death-of-1-year-old-girl-in-simei-flat|archive-date=13 February 2019|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/maid-who-claimed-she-was-stressed-jailed-seven-years-for-causing-toddlers|title=Maid who claimed she was stressed jailed seven years for causing toddler's death|last=hermesauto|date=2018-11-22|website=The Straits Times|language=en|access-date=2019-04-07}}</ref>\n*{{Anchor|David Roach}}7 July 2016: In the rare case of a bank robbery in recent years, 27-year-old Canadian David James Roach robbed a [[Standard Chartered]] bank in Holland Village. He presented a note to the bank teller stating that he had a weapon before he making off with S$30,000. Roach immediately fled to Bangkok after the robbery. The Thai authorities arrested Roach, and subsequently charged him of violating their foreign exchange act and for money laundering. Roach was given a 14-month sentence in jail and the money was seized by the Thai authorities.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.chiangraitimes.com/singapore-bank-robber-david-james-roach-gets-11-months-for-violating-thailands-currency-regulations.html|title=Singapore Bank Robber David James Roach Gets 11 Months for Violating Thailand\u2019s Currency Regulations \u2013 CTN News \u2013 Chiang Rai Times|website=www.chiangraitimes.com|access-date=2019-04-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180219061508/http://www.chiangraitimes.com/singapore-bank-robber-david-james-roach-gets-11-months-for-violating-thailands-currency-regulations.html|archive-date=19 February 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Singapore was unsuccessful at requesting an extradition from the Thai authorities as the two countries have no relevant treaty. Upon his release on 11 January 2018, Roach was deported to Canada via London. Singapore requested Britain the extradition of Roach on the same day, which led to Roach being detained while in transit at London.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.todayonline.com/singapore/stanchart-robbery-suspect-detained-uk-spore-seeking-extradition|title=StanChart bank robbery suspect detained in UK; S\u2019pore seeking extradition|website=TODAYonline|access-date=2019-04-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180321045733/http://www.todayonline.com/singapore/stanchart-robbery-suspect-detained-uk-spore-seeking-extradition|archive-date=21 March 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> To secure the extradition, Singapore authorities assured the British authorities that Roach would not be caned if he is found guilty.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.todayonline.com/singapore/spore-agrees-not-cane-alleged-stanchart-robber-if-uk-extradites-him|title=S'pore agrees not to cane alleged StanChart robber if UK extradites him|website=TODAYonline|access-date=2019-04-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180327101900/http://www.todayonline.com/singapore/spore-agrees-not-cane-alleged-stanchart-robber-if-uk-extradites-him|archive-date=27 March 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> A London court of law found that the extradition request satisfied all requirements on 29 August 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.todayonline.com/singapore/uk-court-approves-singapores-request-extradite-stanchart-robbery-suspect|title=UK court approves Singapore\u2019s request to extradite StanChart robbery suspect|website=TODAYonline|access-date=2019-04-07}}</ref> On 23 October 2018, Britain's Secretary of State ordered the extradition. However, Roach filed an appeal against the extradition order on 31 October 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/stanchart-robbery-suspect-files-appeal-against-extradition-from-uk-to|title=StanChart robbery suspect files appeal against extradition from UK to Singapore|last=Tan|first=Tam Mei|date=2018-11-08|website=The Straits Times|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190208100156/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/stanchart-robbery-suspect-files-appeal-against-extradition-from-uk-to|archive-date=8 February 2019|access-date=2019-04-07|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The appeal was dismissed in February 2020,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thechronicleherald.ca/news/provincial/cape-breton-man-to-be-extradited-to-singapore-to-face-charges-related-to-a-bank-robbery-409880/|title=Cape Breton man to be extradited to Singapore to face charges related to a bank robbery {{!}} The Chronicle Herald|last=Montgomery|first=Sharon|website=www.thechronicleherald.ca|language=en|access-date=2020-03-17}}</ref> and Roach was extradited and was handed over to [[Singapore Police Force]]'s custody on 16 February 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/stanchart-robber-david-roach-extradited-singapore-uk-12545390|title=StanChart robbery: Suspect David Roach extradited to Singapore from UK|website=CNA|language=en|access-date=17 March 2020|date=17 March 2020}}</ref> He was charged the next day with the robbery, as well as unlawfully removing the money out of Singapore.<ref>{{Cite web|last1=Lam|first1=Lydia|url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/stanchart-robbery-david-roach-charged-singapore-offences-12548178|title=StanChart robbery: David Roach charged in Singapore almost 4 years after alleged offences|website=CNA|language=en|access-date=17 March 2020|date=17 March 2020}}</ref>\n*9 July 2016: 64-year-old Toh Sia Guan allegedly caused the death of 52-year-old coffee shop helper Goh Eng Thiam. Goh was found at Geylang Lorong 23 lying motionless on the floor.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/geylang-lor-23-murder-64-year-old-suspect-taken-to-crime-scenes|title=Geylang Lorong 23 murder: 64-year-old suspect taken to crime scenes|last=hermesauto|date=2016-07-27|website=The Straits Times|language=en|access-date=2019-04-05|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161107084706/http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/geylang-lor-23-murder-64-year-old-suspect-taken-to-crime-scenes|archive-date=7 November 2016|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n*11 July 2016: 42-year-old Chua Meng Guan was stabbed repeatedly to death outside a pub at Jalan Besar by 50-year-old Oh Beng Yam. Oh then fled to Johor after the stabbing. As of 2018, Oh remained at large with his last known location being in Thailand.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/2016-stabbing-death-suspect-still-at-large-2-years-after-fleeing-singapore|title=2016 stabbing death suspect still at large 2 years after fleeing Singapore|last=hermesauto|date=2018-03-22|website=The Straits Times|language=en|access-date=2019-04-05}}</ref>\n*12 July 2016: Leslie Khoo Kwee Hock was charged for murdering his 31-year-old girlfriend, Cui Yajie, an engineer from Tianjin. He burnt her body for a few days, and only a few pieces of charred fabric and a brassiere hook remained.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/news/asia/southeast-asia/article/3001553/singaporean-man-leslie-khoo-kwee-hock-denies|title=Strangled, dumped and burned: Chinese woman\u2019s death in Singapore|date=2019-03-13|website=South China Morning Post|language=en|access-date=2019-03-14|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190313112925/https://www.scmp.com/news/asia/southeast-asia/article/3001553/singaporean-man-leslie-khoo-kwee-hock-denies|archive-date=2019-03-13|url-status=live}}</ref> He was found guilty of murder<ref>{{Cite web|last1=Lam|first1=Lydia|url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/gardens-by-the-bay-murder-trial-leslie-khoo-cui-yajie-guilty-11729532|title=Gardens by the Bay murder: Man found guilty of killing China mistress, burning her body|date=18 July 2019|publisher=CNA|access-date=20 August 2019}}</ref> and sentenced to life in jail on 19 August 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|last1=Lam|first1=Lydia|url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/gardens-by-the-bay-murder-leslie-khoo-sentenced-jail-cui-yajie-11819850|title=Gardens by the Bay murder: Man gets life imprisonment for killing mistress, burning her body|date=19 August 2019|publisher=CNA|access-date=20 August 2019}}</ref>\n*13 July 2016: 50-year-old Thennarasu Karupiah assaulted 55-year-old Arokiasamy Paul Rajoo at Taj Mahal Bollywood Music Lounge at Boat Quay. Arokiasamy died 3 days later due to the injuries sustained. In 2018, Thennarasu pleaded guilty to culpable homicide not amounting to murder and was sentenced to 15 years and five months jail.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/ex-gang-member-imprisoned-for-deadly-assault|title=Ex-gang member imprisoned for deadly assault|last=hermes|date=2018-10-02|website=The Straits Times|language=en|access-date=2019-04-05|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181002123740/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/ex-gang-member-imprisoned-for-deadly-assault|archive-date=2 October 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n*25/26 July 2016: 58 year-old Prema S Naraynasamy and her daughter 36-year-old Gaiyathiri Murugaiyan allegedly killed 24-year-old Myanmar domestic worker Piang Ngaih Don at Block 145 Bishan Street 11 sometime between Jul 25 and 26. They were charged with murder.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/two-women-charged-with-murder-at-bishan-7919676|title=Two women charged with murder at Bishan|website=CNA|language=en|access-date=2019-04-05|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170924144651/http://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/two-women-charged-with-murder-at-bishan-7919676|archive-date=24 September 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n*11 October 2016: 41-year-old Lim Ying Siang set fire to two styrofoam boxes at Block 493 market in Jurong West in the wee hours. The fire raged and burned the entire market. It also caused damages to two coffee shops nearby. 56 stall owners at Block 493 market lost their stalls and assets, with the overall loses from all parties amounting to more than S$6 million. Lim was arrested on 13 October 2016<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/police-arrest-suspect-in-jurong-west-market-fire|title=Police arrest suspect in Jurong West market fire|last=Seow|first=Bei Yi|date=15 October 2016|website=The Straits Times|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180622061658/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/police-arrest-suspect-in-jurong-west-market-fire|archive-date=22 June 2018|access-date=19 November 2019}}</ref> and on 20 March 2018, he was sentenced to 11.5 years jail and 3 strokes of cane for  committing mischief by fire and drug consumption.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/man-gets-1112-years-jail-for-jurong-west-market-fire-that-led-to-6-million-in|title=Man gets 11\u00bd years' jail for Jurong West market fire that led to more than $6 million in damage and losses|last=Alkhatib|first=Shaffiq Idris|date=20 March 2018|website=The Straits Times|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180322195016/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/man-gets-1112-years-jail-for-jurong-west-market-fire-that-led-to-6-million-in|archive-date=22 March 2018|access-date=19 November 2019}}</ref> A temporary market was set up for displaced stallholders,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/2-storey-complex-to-replace-fire-ravaged-jurong-west-market-7528352|title=2-storey complex to replace fire-ravaged Jurong West market|last=Chan|first=Luo Er|date=1 January 2017|website=CNA|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191119101848/https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/2-storey-complex-to-replace-fire-ravaged-jurong-west-market-7528352|archive-date=19 November 2019|access-date=19 November 2019}}</ref> with the new market sitting on the affected site which opened in December 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/jurong-central-plaza-opens-replaces-market-destroyed-in-2016-11077938|title=Jurong Central Plaza opens, replaces market destroyed in 2016 fire|last=Goh|first=Nabila|date=1 January 2019|website=CNA|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190102114250/https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/jurong-central-plaza-opens-replaces-market-destroyed-in-2016-11077938|archive-date=2 January 2019|access-date=19 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n===2017===\n* 20 January 2017: 41-year-old Teo Ghim Heng got into an argument with his wife before strangling and burning both his pregnant wife, 39-year-old Choong Pei Shan, and their four-year-old daughter Teo Zi Ning at their flat in Woodlands.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/woodlands-double-deaths-man-charged-with-murder-of-wife-appears-in-court-for|title=Woodlands double deaths: Man charged with murder of wife appears in court for first time|last=Shaffiq Idris Alkhatib|date=2017-02-06|website=The Straits Times|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190403100141/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/woodlands-double-deaths-man-charged-with-murder-of-wife-appears-in-court-for|archive-date=3 April 2019|url-status=live|access-date=2019-04-03|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Their charred bodies were found 8 days later, on the first day of Chinese New Year. Teo was charged with the murder of his wife and daughter. The third charge for the murder of his unborn child is stood down for now.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/woodlands-murder-teo-ghim-heng-strangled-pregnant-wife-daughter-11682212|title=Woodlands double deaths: Man strangled pregnant wife with towel before killing 4-year-old daughter|last=Lam|first=Lydia|date=2019-07-02|website=CNA|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190702070416/https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/woodlands-murder-teo-ghim-heng-strangled-pregnant-wife-daughter-11682212|archive-date=2019-07-02|access-date=2019-10-23}}</ref>\n*26 April 2017: 39-year-old Bangladeshi construction worker, Das Ratan Chandra, was arrested for having sex with a 12-year-old girl in a forested area in Lower Peirce Reservoir Park. On 12 April 2019, Chandra was found guilty of 3 counts of statutory rape and was sentenced to 22-year jail and 18 strokes of cane.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/construction-worker-raped-12-year-old-girl-lower-peirce-11437364|title=Construction worker gets jail, caning for raping 12-year-old girl thrice at reservoir|website=CNA|language=en|access-date=2019-04-12}}</ref>\n*10 May 2017: 48-year-old cleaner Paramjit Singh Minder Singh raped a 61-year-old factory operator at knifepoint in a female toilet at her workplace. He was charged with one count of aggravated rape and two counts of aggravated sexual assault by penetration and sentenced to 18-year jail with 24 strokes of cane.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/cleaner-who-raped-factory-worker-62-gets-18-years-jail-and-24-strokes-of-the|title=Cleaner who raped factory worker, 62, gets 18 years' jail and 24 strokes of the cane|last=hermesauto|date=2018-11-16|website=The Straits Times|language=en|access-date=2019-04-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190216101526/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/cleaner-who-raped-factory-worker-62-gets-18-years-jail-and-24-strokes-of-the|archive-date=16 February 2019|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n*21 June 2017: 41-year-old Indonesian maid Khasanah murdered 79-year-old Chia Ngim Fong and his wife, 78-year-old Madam Chin Sek Fah at their flat in Bedok Reservoir.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.todayonline.com/singapore/double-murder-bedok-reservoir-road|title=Couple in late 70s found murdered in Bedok Reservoir home|website=TODAYonline|access-date=2019-04-03|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190403100132/https://www.todayonline.com/singapore/double-murder-bedok-reservoir-road|archive-date=3 April 2019|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> She fled Singapore for [[Batam]] before she was arrested in Indonesia.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/asia/se-asia/bedok-double-murder-suspect-shares-how-she-fled-singapore|title=Bedok double murder: Indonesian suspect shared how she fled Singapore|last=hermesauto|date=2017-07-01|website=The Straits Times|language=en|access-date=2019-04-03|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190403102244/https://www.straitstimes.com/asia/se-asia/bedok-double-murder-suspect-shares-how-she-fled-singapore|archive-date=3 April 2019|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> She was not extradited on the basis of the principle of personaliteit, which states that any citizen arrested in Indonesia for crimes overseas would be processed with its own legal system. Singapore authorities are working with Indonesia on this case.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/bedok-double-murder-maid-arrested-in-indonesia-will-not-be-sent-8987968|title=Bedok double murder: Maid arrested in Indonesia will not be sent to Singapore|website=CNA|language=en|access-date=2019-04-03|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190403103136/https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/bedok-double-murder-maid-arrested-in-indonesia-will-not-be-sent-8987968|archive-date=3 April 2019|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n* 10 July 2017: 69-year-old Tan Nam Seng stabbed his son-in-law 38-year-old Spencer Tuppani in Telok Ayer St. Tuppani ran and collapsed 70m away, outside an eatery on Boon Tat St. Tan also prevented others from rendering help to Tuppani<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/boon-tat-street-stabbing-69-year-old-man-charged-with-murder-of-9022130|title=Boon Tat Street stabbing: 69-year-old man charged with murder of son-in-law|website=CNA|language=en|access-date=2019-04-03|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190403103134/https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/boon-tat-street-stabbing-69-year-old-man-charged-with-murder-of-9022130|archive-date=3 April 2019|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> which caused Tuppani to die in hospital shortly after. Tan was charged with murder on 12 July and was remanded for three weeks for psychiatric evaluation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/boon-tat-street-murder-accused-remanded-for-three-more-weeks-for-psychiatric|title=Boon Tat Street murder accused remanded for three more weeks for psychiatric assessment|last=hermesauto|date=2017-08-03|website=The Straits Times|language=en|access-date=2019-04-03|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190403100128/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/boon-tat-street-murder-accused-remanded-for-three-more-weeks-for-psychiatric|archive-date=3 April 2019|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n*18 November 2017: A 51-year-old security guard raped his niece's 24-year-old Indonesian maid in his niece's flat. He was sentenced to 10.5 years of jail, with 6 months of it in lieu of caning as he is aged above 50. Names are withheld to protect the identity of the victim.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/man-jailed-1012-years-for-raping-assaulting-maid|title=Man jailed 10\u00bd years for raping, assaulting maid|last=hermes|date=2019-03-19|website=The Straits Times|language=en|access-date=2019-04-06}}</ref>\n*30 December 2017: 29-year-old cleaner Jayselan N Chandrasegar stabbed and slashed his 26-year-old pregnant wife Mayuri Krishnakuma along Lorong 16 Geylang.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/man-29-charged-after-stabbing-wife-in-geylang|title=Man, 29, charged after stabbing wife in Geylang|last=hermesauto|date=2018-01-01|website=The Straits Times|language=en|access-date=2019-04-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180207060215/http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/man-29-charged-after-stabbing-wife-in-geylang|archive-date=7 February 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The unborn baby was not hurt in the attack. On 11 December 2018, Jayselan was convicted of causing grievous hurt to Mayuri with a weapon, and for failing to provide his urine sample after he was caught for suspected drug-related offences. He was sentenced to 7-year jail and 6 strokes of cane.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/cleaner-gets-jail-cane-for-stabbing-wife|title=Cleaner gets jail, cane for stabbing wife|last=hermes|date=2018-12-12|website=The Straits Times|language=en|access-date=2019-04-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181212150827/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/cleaner-gets-jail-cane-for-stabbing-wife|archive-date=12 December 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===2018===\n* 19 July 2018: The ITE examinations director, 56-year-old Low Hwee Geok, was found dead at the [[ITE College Central]] campus carpark after she was allegedly stabbed by her ex-husband.<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Tay |first1=Tiffany Fumiko |last2=Tan |first2=Tam Mei |last3=Ng |first3=Keng Gene |last4=Koh |first4=Fabian |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/woman-found-dead-man-injured-in-ite-college-central-campus-carpark |title=ITE College Central murder: 56-year-old director of exams division allegedly stabbed by ex-husband |website=The Straits Times |access-date=28 November 2019 |date=19 July 2018}}</ref> The ex-husband, 66-year-old Seet Cher Hng, was arrested on 20 July 2018<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Tan |first1=Tam Mei |last2=Low |first2=De Wei |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/ite-college-central-murder-victim-56-was-a-school-director-whom-friends-said-was-well |title=ITE College Central murder: Police arrest 66-year-old man who allegedly stabbed ex-wife |website=The Straits Times |access-date=28 November 2019 |date=20 July 2018}}</ref> and charged with murder the following day.<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Tan |first1=Tam Mei |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/murder-on-ite-campus-suspect-charged-in-hospital |title=Murder on ITE campus: Suspect charged in hospital |website=The Straits Times |access-date=28 November 2019 |date=21 July 2018}}</ref>\n* 29 July 2018: 58-year-old Balachandran Kothandapani, 34-year-old Farizal Rahmat, and 44-year-old Murugan Joseph assaulted 32-year-old cook Revi Jose Vibin at a [[Roti prata|prata]] shop in Clementi. In an argument for not getting free prata, Balachandran slashed Revi. Murugan was sentenced to 13-month jail, in lieu of 6 strokes of cane as he was medically unfit. Farizal was sentenced to 8 months jail and 6 strokes of cane, in addition to a 400-day jail for committing the offence on remission order. Balachandran Kothandapani was sentenced to one-year jail with 3 months in lieu of 6 strokes of cane as he was above 50 and cannot be caned.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/man-admits-to-being-part-of-trio-who-attacked-cook-with-knife-after-not|title=Man admits to being part of trio who attacked cook with knife after not getting free prata|last=hermesauto|date=2019-03-28|website=The Straits Times|language=en|access-date=2019-04-06|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190329124136/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/man-admits-to-being-part-of-trio-who-attacked-cook-with-knife-after-not|archive-date=29 March 2019|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Elangovan |first1=Navene |title=Jail, caning for second man who took part in attack on prata stall\u2019s cook |url=https://www.todayonline.com/singapore/jail-caning-second-man-who-took-part-attack-prata-stalls-cook |accessdate=14 July 2019 |publisher=Todayonline |date=29 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Tang |first1=Louisa |title=No free prata: Jail for third man involved in attack on Indian food stall's cook |url=https://www.todayonline.com/singapore/jail-third-man-involved-attack-prata-stall-cook |accessdate=14 July 2019 |publisher=Todayonline |date=4 April 2019}}</ref>\n*19 November 2018: 64-year-old father Tan Tian Chye allegedly killed his 35-year-old daughter Desiree Tan Jiaping in his flat at Block 171 Bedok South Road. He was charged with murder and was undergoing psychiatric evaluation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/man-charged-with-daughters-murder|title=Man charged with daughter's murder|last=hermes|date=2018-11-21|website=The Straits Times|language=en|access-date=2019-04-05}}</ref>\n*30 December 2018: A 34-year-old Indonesian female work permit holder was found dead at the Golden Dragon Hotel in Geylang. A 29-year-old Bangladeshi work permit holder was subsequently arrested and would be charged with murder.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/indonesian-woman-found-dead-at-geylang-hotel-suspect-arrested|title=Indonesian woman found dead at Geylang hotel, suspect arrested|last=hermesauto|date=2018-12-31|website=The Straits Times|language=en|access-date=2019-04-04|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190216123101/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/indonesian-woman-found-dead-at-geylang-hotel-suspect-arrested|archive-date=16 February 2019|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The now 30-year-old Bangladeshi, Ahmed Salim, was charged with murder on 2 January 2019.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Alkhatib |first1=Shaffiq |title=Man charged with murder after body found in Geylang hotel |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/man-charged-with-murder-after-body-found-in-geylang-hotel |accessdate=14 July 2019 |publisher=The Straits Times |date=2 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n===2019===\n* 17 January 2019: 34-year-old M. Krishan allegedly murdered 40-year-old Mallika Begum Rahamansa Abdul Rahman at a flat at Block 693D Woodlands Avenue 6, with the former arrested on the same day.<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Ang |first1=Jolene |last2=Goh |first2=Timothy |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/man-arrested-for-alleged-murder-after-woman-found-dead-in-woodlands |title=Man arrested for alleged murder after woman found dead in Woodlands |website=The Straits Times |access-date=4 January 2020 |date=17 January 2019}}</ref> Krishan was subsequently charged on 18 January.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/man-34-charged-over-woodlands-murder|title=Man, 34, charged with murder of woman in Woodlands flat|last=Alkhatib|first=Shaffiq|date=2019-01-18|website=The Straits Times|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190206162117/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/man-34-charged-over-woodlands-murder|archive-date=6 February 2019|access-date=2019-04-04|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n*11 March 2019: A 23-year-old Malaysian work permit holder Yee Jing Man was arrested for allegedly murdering 30-year-old director Lin Xinjie, who was found dead at the International Furniture Centre at 62 [[Sungei Kadut]] Loop, together with 29-year-old director Li Mingqiao who was another injured victim.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/man-allegedly-murdered-at-sungei-kadut-loop-one-other-injured-suspect-to-be-charged|title=Man allegedly murdered in Sungei Kadut Loop, one other injured; suspect to be charged|last=Alkhatib|first=Shaffiq|date=2019-03-11|website=The Straits Times|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190313020023/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/man-allegedly-murdered-at-sungei-kadut-loop-one-other-injured-suspect-to-be-charged|archive-date=13 March 2019|access-date=2019-04-04|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Yee was fired for the second time earlier that day for poor work attitude, which led him to attack Lin and Li.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/suspect-allegedly-attacked-boss-after-being-fired-again|title=Suspect allegedly attacked boss after being fired again|last=Ng|first=Charmaine|date=2019-03-13|website=The Straits Times|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190406233551/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/suspect-allegedly-attacked-boss-after-being-fired-again|archive-date=2019-04-06|access-date=2019-04-06}}</ref> Yee was charged with murder two days later.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/man-charged-over-sungei-kadut-murder|title=Man charged over Sungei Kadut murder|last=Alkhatib|first=Shaffiq|date=2019-03-14|website=The Straits Times|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190406233245/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/man-charged-over-sungei-kadut-murder|archive-date=2019-04-06|access-date=2019-04-06}}</ref>\n*May 2019: Lawyer Jeffrey Ong Su Aun was the managing partner of law firm JLC Advisors. Ong could not be contacted after S$33.4 million from the escrow account of engineering firm Allied Technologies, which was parked in his law firm, may have been paid out by Ong without the prior knowledge of the engineering firm. He fled Singapore for Malaysia on 13 May before he went uncontactable on 16 May. He was arrested in Kuala Lumpur by the [[Royal Malaysian Police]] on 29 May before he was extradited back to Singapore the next day. Ong has been charged with cheating offences involving tricking CCJ Investments to disburse S$6 million, and forgery offences where he forged bank statements in order to conceal discrepancies.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/law-firm-partner-jeffrey-ong-believed-to-have-ordered-pay-out-of-33-million-belonging-to|title=Lawyer goes missing after ordering payout of $33 million held in escrow account|last=K.C.|first=Vijayan|date=2019-05-23|website=The Straits Times|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191016174015/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/law-firm-partner-jeffrey-ong-believed-to-have-ordered-pay-out-of-33-million-belonging-to|archive-date=2019-10-16|access-date=2019-11-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/missing-lawyer-jeffrey-ong-arrested-and-charged-with-cheating|title=Missing lawyer Jeffrey Ong arrested and charged with cheating|last=Alkhatib|first=Shaffiq|date=2019-06-07|website=The Straits Times|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190608181226/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/missing-lawyer-jeffrey-ong-arrested-and-charged-with-cheating|archive-date=2019-06-08|access-date=2019-10-16}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/lawyer-jeffrey-ong-faces-eight-new-cheating-charges|title=Lawyer Jeffrey Ong, linked to missing $33m, faces 8 new forgery charges|last=Ng|first=Charmaine|date=2019-06-13|website=The Straits Times|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190615044718/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/lawyer-jeffrey-ong-faces-eight-new-cheating-charges|archive-date=2019-06-15|access-date=2019-10-16}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/lawyer-allegedly-linked-to-missing-33-million-faces-4-new-charges|title=Lawyer Jeffrey Ong, allegedly linked to missing $33 million, faces 4 new charges|last=Alkhatib|first=Shaffiq|date=2019-10-14|website=The Straits Times|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191016174049/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/lawyer-allegedly-linked-to-missing-33-million-faces-4-new-charges|archive-date=2019-10-16|access-date=2019-10-16}}</ref>\n*2 July 2019: Known as the Orchard Towers murder, a 31-year-old man, Satheesh Noel Gobidass, was assaulted and murdered at [[Orchard Towers]] by a large group. Eight suspects were arrested, with seven initially charged for murder on 4 July 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/seven-charged-for-murder-of-man-at-orchard-towers|title=Orchard Towers fight: Six men, one woman charged with murder|last=Wong|first=Cara|date=2019-07-04|website=The Straits Times|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190714132352/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/seven-charged-for-murder-of-man-at-orchard-towers|archive-date=2019-07-14|access-date=2019-11-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.todayonline.com/singapore/8-murder-suspects-arrested-after-man-at-orchard-towers-dies-from-injuries|title=8 murder suspects arrested after man at Orchard Towers dies from injuries|last=ELANGOVAN|first=NAVENE|date=2019-07-02|website=TODAYonline|access-date=2019-11-01}}</ref> On 11 July 2019, three suspects were acquitted of murder, and charged with consorting with a person carrying an offensive weapon in a public place.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/murder-charges-against-3-dropped-in-orchard-towers-case|title=Murder charges against 3 dropped in Orchard Towers case|last=Alkhatib|first=Shaffiq|date=2019-07-12|website=The Straits Times|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190712162755/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/murder-charges-against-3-dropped-in-orchard-towers-case|archive-date=2019-07-12|access-date=2019-11-01}}</ref>\n*8 October 2019: Muhammad Ikram Abdul Aziz, 24 was arrested in a joint operation by the [[Central Narcotics Bureau]] and the [[Singapore Police Force|police]] at the void deck below his housing unit at Block 731 Jurong West Street 72 before being escorted to his home, where a loaded pistol was discovered.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/two-men-arrested-for-possession-of-loaded-pistol|title=Two men arrested for possession of loaded pistol|last1=Wong|first1=Cara|date=9 October 2019|website=The Straits Times|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191011100918/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/two-men-arrested-for-possession-of-loaded-pistol|archive-date=2019-10-11|access-date=9 October 2019}}</ref> The following day, a second man, Amirul Asyraff Muhammad Junus, 25 was arrested for consorting with Ikram who was in possession of firearm. No drugs were found on the two of them. Both of them were charged for their respective offences.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/two-men-charged-over-offences-involving-pistol|title=Two charged over pistol found in Jurong West flat; first such case in a decade|last1=Alkhatib|first1=Shaffiq|date=10 October 2019|website=The Straits Times|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191012100736/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/two-men-charged-over-offences-involving-pistol|archive-date=2019-10-12|access-date=10 October 2019}}</ref>\n*27 October 2019: Two murder cases happened on the same day.\n**54-year-old Chinese national Wang Shuzhen allegedly murdered her husband, 63-year-old former policeman Teh Hock Pine at their flat at Block 633 [[Ang Mo Kio]] Avenue 6 in the early hours.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/woman-charged-with-murder-of-man-in-ang-mo-kio-flat|title=Woman accused of killing ex-policeman said to be her husband in Ang Mo Kio flat|last1=Tan|first1=Tam Mei|date=28 October 2019|website=The Straits Times|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191030235739/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/woman-charged-with-murder-of-man-in-ang-mo-kio-flat|archive-date=30 October 2019|access-date=31 October 2019}}</ref> Wang was arrested and charged the next day for murder.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/63-year-old-man-found-dead-in-ang-mo-kio-flat-53-year-old-woman-arrested-for|title=22-year-old man arrested over double murder of relatives in Commonwealth Avenue block|last1=Yong|first1=Clement|date=27 October 2019|website=The Straits Times|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191029214039/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/63-year-old-man-found-dead-in-ang-mo-kio-flat-53-year-old-woman-arrested-for|archive-date=29 October 2019|access-date=31 October 2019}}</ref>\n**22-year-old Gabriel Lien Goh allegedly murdered both his mother, 56-year-old former teacher Lee Soh Mui and his 90-year-old grandmother See Keng Keng. Goh was arguing with his mother in a housing unit at Block 7A [[Commonwealth, Singapore|Commonwealth]] Avenue when he stabbed her to death. Goh's grandmother ran out to their neighbour's unit for help, before Goh punched the neighbour's relatives who let his grandmother in. Goh proceeded to assault his grandmother to death and went down to the first floor, where he acted aggressively towards members of the public before he was subdued and arrested.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/double-murders-at-commonwealth-avenue-22-year-old-arrested|title=22-year-old man arrested over double murder of relatives in Commonwealth Avenue block|last1=Wong|first1=Cara|last2=Chong|first2=Clara|date=27 October 2019|website=The Straits Times|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191101162149/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/double-murders-at-commonwealth-avenue-22-year-old-arrested|archive-date=1 November 2019|access-date=31 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mothership.sg/2019/10/commonwealth-avenue-murder-son/|title=Man allegedly murders mom & grandma in Commonwealth, details as provided by S\u2019pore Chinese newspapers|last=Zheng|first=Zhangxin|date=2019-10-28|website=Mothership.sg|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191030193944/https://mothership.sg/2019/10/commonwealth-avenue-murder-son/|archive-date=2019-10-30|access-date=2019-10-30}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mothership.sg/2019/10/gabriel-lien-goh-beat-grandmother-neighbour/|title=Commonwealth double deaths: Man allegedly beat grandma to death in neighbour\u2019s house|last=Lee|first=Joshua|date=2019-10-30|website=Mothership.sg|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191030194255/https://mothership.sg/2019/10/gabriel-lien-goh-beat-grandmother-neighbour/|archive-date=2019-10-30|access-date=2019-10-30}}</ref> Goh was charged for the alleged murder of both his mother and grandmother on 28 October and 18 November respectively.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/commonwealth-double-deaths-man-charged-with-murder-of-woman-believed-to-be|title=Commonwealth double deaths: Man charged with murder of woman believed to be his mother|last=Tan|first=Tam Mei|date=2019-10-28|website=The Straits Times|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191030194539/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/commonwealth-double-deaths-man-charged-with-murder-of-woman-believed-to-be|archive-date=2019-10-30|access-date=2019-10-30}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/commonwealth-double-deaths-man-faces-second-murder-charge-over-grandmothers|title=Commonwealth double deaths: Man accused of killing his mother charged with murdering grandmother|last=Ng|first=Charmaine|date=18 November 2019|website=The Straits Times|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191118130910/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/commonwealth-double-deaths-man-faces-second-murder-charge-over-grandmothers|archive-date=18 November 2019|access-date=18 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==2020s==\n=== 2020 ===\n*3 January 2020: A former podiatrist from Melbourne, Paul Leslie Quirk, 48, murdered his wife, Christina Khoo Gek Hwa, 43, in their home at 125 Compassvale Bow.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/murder-esparina-residences-condominium-buangkok-paul-quirk-12232894|title=Man charged with murdering his wife at Buangkok condominium|website=CNA|language=en|access-date=2020-02-25}}</ref> Screams were heard by neighbours and Quirk was seen  armed with a big stick, hurling his dog off the balcony of his third-floor apartment. Khoo was found unresponsive, and was pronounced dead on the spot. The dog was found bloodied on the ground floor. Quirk was charged with murder, and was being remanded at Changi Prison for psychiatric observation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theaustralian.com.au/world/australian-paul-quirk-facing-death-penalty-over-wifes-murder-in-singapore/news-story/93c6e015d879da0cca63a1b8a2a14486|title=Australian Paul Quirk facing death penalty over wife\u2019s murder in Singapore|last=|first=|date=25 January 2020|website=www.theaustralian.com.au|url-access=subscription|access-date=2020-02-25}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n[[Category:Crime in Singapore| ]]\n[[Category:Singapore crime-related lists|Major crimes]]\n[[Category:Lists of events in Singapore|Major crimes]]\n", "text_old": "{{Inc-up|date=April 2019}}\n{{use Singapore English|date=August 2019}}\n{{short description|wikimedia list article}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2019}}\n\nThe following is a list of '''major [[Crime in Singapore|crimes in Singapore]]'''. They are arranged in chronological order.\n\nMajor crimes such as homicide, kidnapping, firearm-related, aggravated sexual crime like rape and sexual assault by penetration, bomb and explosive-related and other major sensitive crimes are investigated by Major Crime Division of [[Criminal Investigation Department (Singapore)|Criminal Investigation Department (CID)]] in the [[Singapore Police Force]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.police.gov.sg/about-us/organisational-structure/specialist-staff-departments/criminal-investigation-department|title=Specialist Staff Departments|website=Singapore Police Force|language=en|access-date=2019-04-06|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190120143100/https://www.police.gov.sg/about-us/organisational-structure/specialist-staff-departments/criminal-investigation-department|archive-date=20 January 2019|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Drug-related crimes like drug trafficking are handled by the [[Central Narcotics Bureau]]. White-collar crimes like fraud and misappropriation of finances are handled by the [[Commercial Affairs Department]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.police.gov.sg/about-us/organisational-structure/specialist-staff-departments/commercial-affairs-department|title=Specialist Staff Departments|website=Singapore Police Force|language=en|access-date=2019-10-16}}</ref> while corruption offences are under the purview of the [[Corrupt Practices Investigation Bureau]]. Criminals which are of concern to the national security of Singapore are firmly dealt with by the [[Internal Security Department (Singapore)|Internal Security Department]] via the [[Internal Security Act (Singapore)|Internal Security Act]] and other laws.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mha.gov.sg/isd/about-isd|title=About ISD|website=Ministry of Home Affairs|language=en|access-date=2019-10-17}}</ref>\n\n==1960s==\n\n===1963===\n* 12 July 1963: detainees at the prison on [[Pulau Senang]] started a riot and killed prison officer Daniel Stanley Dutton and three of his assistants. 64 were accused of murder and rioiting. After a five-month-long trial, 18 men were convicted of murder and hanged in Changi Prison on 29 October 1965. Another 29 men were also found guilty of rioting.<ref>{{cite web|last=Cornelius-Takahama|first=Vernon|url=http://infopedia.nl.sg/articles/SIP_728_2005-01-19.html|title=Pulau Senang|publisher=National Library Board, Singapore|date=2001|accessdate=20 November 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130313050528/http://infopedia.nl.sg/articles/SIP_728_2005-01-19.html|archivedate=13 March 2013}}</ref>\n* 27 August 1963: Sunny Ang Soo Kuan allegedly murdered his girlfriend, Jenny Cheok Cheng Kid, during a scuba-diving trip in the straits between [[Sisters' Islands]]. He was found guilty in a jury trial, sentenced to death, and hanged on 6 February 1967.<ref name=\"straitstimes.com\">{{cite news|title=Guilty As Charged: Sunny Ang found guilty of girlfriend's murder though body was never found|url=http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/guilty-as-charged-sunny-ang-found-guilty-of-girlfriends-murder-though-body|newspaper=The Straits Times|location=Singapore|date=16 May 2016|accessdate=16 May 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160516050602/http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/guilty-as-charged-sunny-ang-found-guilty-of-girlfriends-murder-though-body|archive-date=2016-05-16|url-status=live}}</ref> Cheok's body was never found.<ref>{{cite web|author1=Jasli, Tettyana|author2=Chew, Valerie|url=http://infopedia.nl.sg/articles/SIP_1789_2011-09-26.html|title=The Sunny Ang murder case|publisher=National Library Board, Singapore|accessdate=20 November 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130102145524/http://infopedia.nl.sg/articles/SIP_1789_2011-09-26.html|archivedate=2 January 2013}}</ref>\n\n'''1968'''\n\n*24 May 1968: 19-year-old Ong Beang Leck was last seen alive by his father as he left his father's shop. Later on, Ong's father received two separate phone calls on 26 May and 5 June in which the caller claimed he had kidnapped Ong and demanded a ransom from the elder Ong to free his son. A ransom of $20000 was eventually negotiated and paid, but still, there was no sign of Ong. A week after the ransom was paid, a rental car owner found one of the cars he rented out three weeks before had a foul-smelling odour. Tests revealed that the smell was that of blood. The person who last rented the car was found to be 24-year-old Richard Lai Chun Seng. Lai confessed that he, along with four others, was part of a kidnapping, in which the victim was none other than the missing youth Ong Beang Leck. Lai also stated that he took part in the plan as he needed money to save his failing business, and that he thought the plan was to lure Ong into the rental car, render the youth unconscious and held him hostage until the ransom was paid; however, on the night of 25 June 1968, as soon as Ong entered the car, Lai was shocked to see the three of his four other accomplices taking out weapons he was unaware of and attacked Ong, which led to the boy's death. This relevation led to the arrest of the other four accomplices; one of them was Ong's 24-year-old close friend Lee Chor Pet, the others were 29-year-old Chow Sien Cheong, 32-year-old Lim Kim Kwee, and 23-year-old Ho Kee Fatt (the latter two had ran off to Malaysia before their arrest by the Royal Malaysian Police). Lee led the police to a manhole in Jurong, where Ong's highly decomposed body was found. Lee, Lim and Ho, who were the three people assaulting Ong right from the back of the car, were charged with the murder of the youth. The three were found guilty of murder and sentenced to death on 11 June 1970, and all the three men were hanged on 27 January 1973. Lai, who became the prosecution's main witness, was subsequently jailed for 4 years for his involvement in both the ransom negotiation and the abduction of Ong. For possessing the ransom money, Chow was also given a 4-year jail sentence as well.\n\n==1970s==\n\n===1970===\n* 6 January 1970: 31-year-old dance hostess Mimi Wong Weng Siu (\u9ec4\u5a49\u79c0) and 37-year-old sweeper Sim Woh Kum (\u51bc\u677e\u9526) in late 1969 were convicted of murder of a Mrs Watanabe and sentenced to death on 7 December 1970. Wong became the first woman to receive the capital punishment from a Singapore court.<ref>{{cite news|title=Guilty As Charged: Dance hostess Mimi Wong murdered her Japanese lover\u2019s wife|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/guilty-as-charged-dance-hostess-mimi-wong-murdered-her-japanese-lovers-wife|newspaper=The Straits Times|location=Singapore|date=14 May 2016|accessdate=14 May 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160517103525/http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/guilty-as-charged-dance-hostess-mimi-wong-murdered-her-japanese-lovers-wife|archive-date=2016-05-17|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===1971===\n* 29 December 1971: Businessman Ngo Cheng Poh and two of his employees were killed by a group of 10 men, who also robbed them of 120 gold bars. All were charged with murder.<ref>{{cite news|title=Guilty As Charged: Seven who killed for 120 gold bars hanged|url=http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/guilty-as-charged-seven-who-killed-for-120-gold-bars-hanged|newspaper=The Straits Times|location=Singapore|date=16 May 2016|accessdate=16 May 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160516054911/http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/guilty-as-charged-seven-who-killed-for-120-gold-bars-hanged|archive-date=2016-05-16|url-status=live}}</ref> Seven of the ten men were convicted of murder and hanged on 28 February 1975 while the remaining three were put under indefinite detention.<ref>{{cite web|last=Tok|first=Cherylyn|url=http://infopedia.nl.sg/articles/SIP_1753_2011-02-14.html|title=Gold Bar Murders|publisher=National Library Board, Singapore|accessdate=20 November 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130313045835/http://infopedia.nl.sg/articles/SIP_1753_2011-02-14.html|archivedate=13 March 2013}}</ref>\n\n===1972===\n* 18 September 1972: A 22-year-old seamstress Cheng Li Zhen was walking along [[Queenstown, Singapore|Queenstown]] with her sister when she suddenly screamed and collapsed to the ground with blood oozing out from her chest. It was only after she was in the hospital that they found that it was a gunshot wound. She never regained consciousness and died in the hospital soon after. The case remains unsolved.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Mystery of Queenstown 1972{{!}}My Queenstown|url = http://goodmorningyesterday.blogspot.sg/2009/04/mysterious-shooting-incident-in.html|website = myqueenstown.blogspot.sg|accessdate = 2015-10-18|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150924012522/http://goodmorningyesterday.blogspot.sg/2009/04/mysterious-shooting-incident-in.html|archive-date = 2015-09-24|url-status = live}}</ref>\n* 24 November 1972: Gunman Lim Ban Lim, who killed 27-year-old Corporal Koh Chong Thye on 23 June 1968, was ambushed by police officers in the vicinity of Block 6 near Golden City Theatre. Officers shot Lim three times in his body in a fire fight, killing Lim. His aide Chua Ah Kow shot himself dead during a gunfight three weeks later at Tank Road.<ref>{{cite news|title=Guilty As Charged: Lim Ban Lim was most wanted gunman in Singapore and Malaysia in 1960s|url=http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/guilty-as-charged-lim-ban-lim-was-most-wanted-gunman-in-singapore-and|newspaper=The Straits Times|location=Singapore|date=16 May 2016|accessdate=16 May 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160515114826/http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/guilty-as-charged-lim-ban-lim-was-most-wanted-gunman-in-singapore-and|archive-date=2016-05-15|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===1974===\n* 9 May 1974: 44-year-old Sim Joo Keow strangled her 53-year-old sister-in-law Quek Lee Eng over $2,000, before dismembering her body and keeping her torso in two earthen jars in her home. Quek's head and arms were found in a parcel near the Kallang River bank. Sim was sentenced to 10 years in jail in January 1975, after being convicted of manslaughter and hiding evidence.<ref>{{cite news|title=Guilty As Charged: Sim Joo Keow strangled sister-in-law, chopped up her body|url=http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/guilty-as-charged-sim-joo-keow-strangled-sister-in-law-chopped-up-her-body|newspaper=The Straits Times|location=Singapore|date=16 May 2016|accessdate=16 May 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160515105714/http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/guilty-as-charged-sim-joo-keow-strangled-sister-in-law-chopped-up-her-body|archive-date=2016-05-15|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===1975===\n* July 1975: District Judge E.C. Foenander sentenced Suhaymi Harith, 40, Khalil Mohammed Dol, 39, Wassan Sakeebun, 45, and Wagiman Abdullah, 47 a total of 64 years in jail plus 144 strokes of the cane. All four pleaded guilty to 228 charges of housebreaking, robbery and theft committed between 5 January 1973 and 13 June 1975.<ref>{{cite news|title=Guilty As Charged: Serial robbers, dressed in only their swimming trunks, terrorised residents|url=http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/guilty-as-charged-serial-robbers-dressed-in-only-their-swimming-trunks|newspaper=The Straits Times|location=Singapore|date=16 May 2016|accessdate=16 May 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160517111748/http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/guilty-as-charged-serial-robbers-dressed-in-only-their-swimming-trunks|archive-date=2016-05-17|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===1978===\n* 25 April 1978: 18-year-old police national serviceman [[Lee Kim Lai]]<ref>{{cite news|title=Guilty As Charged: Three friends who wanted to become robbers killed 2 men to get a gun|url=http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/guilty-as-charged-three-friends-who-wanted-to-become-robbers-killed-2-men-to|newspaper=The Straits Times|location=Singapore|date=16 May 2016|accessdate=16 May 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160515103958/http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/guilty-as-charged-three-friends-who-wanted-to-become-robbers-killed-2-men-to|archive-date=2016-05-15|url-status=live}}</ref> was abducted by three men from his sentry post at [[Mount Vernon, Singapore|Mount Vernon]] and forced into a taxi. They killed him for his service revolver and also killed the taxi driver. The three men were convicted of murder and hanged on 24 February 1984.<ref>{{cite news|title=Murderer's last gift \u2014 his eyes|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article/straitstimes19840226-1.2.28.aspx|newspaper=The Straits Times|location=Singapore|date=26 February 1984|accessdate=16 March 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160318222353/http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article/straitstimes19840226-1.2.28.aspx|archive-date=2016-03-18|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*August 1978: Siti Aminah binte Jaffar, 24, a former barmaid and Anwar Ali Khan was caught for trafficking 43.5g of diamorphine (pure heroin), which exceeds the mandatory death penalty of 15g. Both were eventually sentenced to death. Anwar was hanged in 1983 after President Devan rejected his plea of clemency. Siti was spared with the death penalty and placed her under life imprisonment after President Devan accepted her plea of clemency. Siti became the first woman about to be sentenced to death for drug trafficking, but spared due to an accepted plea of clemency.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article/straitstimes19830219.2.33.1.aspx|title=Drugs woman told she will not hang|access-date=2016-10-28|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161029115820/http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article/straitstimes19830219.2.33.1.aspx|archive-date=2016-10-29|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===1979===\n* 6 January 1979: Four children between the ages of five and ten were [[Geylang Bahru family murders|found brutally slashed to death]] in their [[Housing and Development Board|HDB]] flat in [[Geylang|Geylang Bahru]]. The case remains unsolved.<ref>{{cite web|last=Kutty|first=N. G.|url=http://newspapers.nl.sg/Digitised/Article/straitstimes19790107.2.3.aspx|title=Four kids slashed to death...|newspaper=The Straits Times|location=Singapore|date=7 January 1979|accessdate=20 November 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121107051236/http://newspapers.nl.sg/Digitised/Article/straitstimes19790107.2.3.aspx|archive-date=2012-11-07|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Jasli|first=Tettyana|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/infopedia/articles/SIP_1872_2012-02-28.html|title=Geylang Bahru family murders|publisher=National Library Board, Singapore|accessdate=25 January 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141228000842/http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/infopedia/articles/SIP_1872_2012-02-28.html|archive-date=2014-12-28|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==1980s==\n\n===1980===\n*3 October 1980: PC Nawi bin Saini and another policeman spotted 25-year-old Malaysian Seow Lam Seng and his accomplice 30-year-old Lee Ah Fatt loitering suspiciously just meters from a bank along [[Katong|Tanjong Katong]] Road.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tnp.sg/news/singapore/msian-man-charged-firearm-possession-after-38-years-run|title=M'sian man charged with firearm possession after 38 years on the run|last=ALKHATIB|first=SHAFFIQ|date=2018-03-27|website=The New Paper|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180327002520/https://www.tnp.sg/news/singapore/msian-man-charged-firearm-possession-after-38-years-run|archive-date=27 March 2018|access-date=2019-11-11}}</ref> When the duo were searched and screened, Lee allegedly drew his pistol and pointed at the officers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thesundaily.my/archive/how-law-caught-fugitive-38-years-later-NUARCH537784|title=How the law caught up with fugitive 38 years later|last=|first=|date=5 April 2018|website=www.thesundaily.my|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191111212405/https://www.thesundaily.my/archive/how-law-caught-fugitive-38-years-later-NUARCH537784|archive-date=11 November 2019|access-date=2019-11-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/fugitive-returns-to-crime-scene-after-38-years|title=Fugitive returns to crime scene after 38 years|last=Chua|first=Ilyda|date=2018-03-29|website=The Straits Times|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180406122235/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/fugitive-returns-to-crime-scene-after-38-years|archive-date=6 April 2018|access-date=2019-11-11}}</ref> PC Nawi then drew his revolver and fired three shots at Lee. Lee continued to struggle with the officers despite being shot while Seow took advantage of the officers' distraction and fled. Seow also discarded his gun as he fled.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article/straitstimes19801004-1.2.4|title=Gunman shot dead near Katong bank|last=Lai|first=Yew Kong|date=4 October 1980|website=|publisher=The Straits Times|via=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/|access-date=11 November 2019}}</ref> Lee succumbed to his injuries in hospital while Seow fled to Malaysia and was on the run for 38 years. On 22 March 2018, 63-year-old Seow was nabbed in [[Penang]] by the Royal Malaysian Police and extradited to Singapore two days later.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/after-38-years-on-the-run-man-wanted-for-firearms-offence-nabbed-in-penang|title=After 38 years on the run, man wanted for firearms offence nabbed in Penang|last=Boh|first=Samantha|date=2018-03-25|website=The Straits Times|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180330224646/http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/after-38-years-on-the-run-man-wanted-for-firearms-offence-nabbed-in-penang|archive-date=30 March 2018|access-date=2019-11-11}}</ref> On 26 March 2018, Seow was charged for unlawful possession of firearms.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.todayonline.com/singapore/63-year-old-run-illegal-possession-pistol-caught-after-38-years|title=63-year-old on the run for illegal possession of pistol caught after 38 years|last=LOW|first=YOUJIN|date=25 March 2018|website=TODAYonline|access-date=2019-11-11}}</ref>\n\n===1981===\n* 25 January and 7 February 1981: Notoriously dubbed as the [[Toa Payoh ritual murders|Adrian Lim ritual murders]] and widely remembered by Singaporeans up till today,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mustsharenews.com/unbelievable-crimes-singapore/|title=10 Most Unbelievable Crimes That Happened In Singapore / Toa Payoh ritual murders|last=Kash|first=Saba|date=2018-05-05|website=Must Share News|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://goodyfeed.com/5-murder-cases-in-spore-that-will-shock-you/|title=5 Murder Cases in S\u2019pore that will Shock you / Toa Payoh ritual murders (1981)|last=|first=|date=2015-09-28|website=Goody Feed|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://remembersingapore.org/2011/01/24/headlines-that-shook-singapore/|title=Headlines that shook Singapore (since 1955) / Adrian Lim Murders|last=|first=|date=2011-01-24|website=Remember Singapore|language=en|access-date=2019-10-22}}</ref> Lim, a self-professed [[Mediumship|medium]], together with his two accomplices, Catherine Tan Mui Choo and Hoe Kah Hong murdered two children, purportedly as blood sacrifices in some ritual. All three of them were found guilty of murder and sentenced to death. They were hanged on 25 November 1988.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Munoo|first1=Rajendra|title=Adrian Lim Murders|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/infopedia/articles/SIP_71_2005-02-02.html?s=adrian%20lim|publisher=National Library Board, Singapore|accessdate=25 January 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160202103907/http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/infopedia/articles/SIP_71_2005-02-02.html?s=adrian%20lim|archive-date=2016-02-02|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/guilty-as-charged-adrian-lim-and-his-2-holy-wives-kidnapped-tortured-and|title=Guilty As Charged: Adrian Lim and his 2 'holy' wives kidnapped, tortured and killed 2 children|last=|first=|date=2016-05-15|website=The Straits Times|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190216003913/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/guilty-as-charged-adrian-lim-and-his-2-holy-wives-kidnapped-tortured-and|archive-date=2019-02-16|access-date=2019-10-22}}</ref>\n*20 September 1981: 22-year-old Ramu Annadavascan and his 16-year-old accomplice Rathakrishnan Ramasamy assaulted 45-year-old boilerman Kalingam Mariappan with a rake. The assault ensued from an argument between both Ramu and Kalingam. Afterwards, the two then proceeded to pour petrol onto the unconscious Kalingam, and set fire on him, causing Kalingam to be burned to death. Both were later found guilty of murder; Ramu was condemned to death and he headed to the gallows on 19 September 1986, while Rathakrishnan, who was under the age of 18 when he committed the murder, was spared the gallows and detained indefinitely at the President's pleasure. After serving nearly 20 years, Rathakrishnan was released from prison in September 2001.\n\n===1983===\n* 30 June and 23 July 1983: Known as the Andrew Road triple murders, Sek Kim Wah, a 19-year-old [[National service in Singapore|conscript]], broke into the home of businessman Robert Tay Bak Hong at Andrew Road on 23 July with the aid of his accomplice, 19-year-old Malaysian Nyu Kok Meng. They were armed with a rifle Sek had stolen from Nee Soon camp. All five victims: Tay, his wife, their Filipino maid, Tay's daughter and her tutor were confined to a bedroom. They proceeded to rob Tay's family of their jewellery and cash out money from their bank accounts. While Nyu was guarding the victims, Sek decided to murder all five victims by escorting them one-by-one out of the bedroom in a bid to erase witnesses. Sek proceeded to struck Tay and his wife with a chair and strangled them. Sek also strangled their maid. In all, Sek murdered 3 people. Nyu discovered Sek's murder intentions only when he caught him in the act in another room. Fearing that Tay's daughter and her tutor would be next, Nyu carried the rifle with him and locked the bedroom door upon dashing in. When Sek's repeated requests to open the door was denied by Nyu, Sek immediately fled. Nyu then released Tay's daughter and her tutor. Nyu fled to Malaysia before he surrendered and was extradited to Singapore. Sek was arrested at his sister's home on 29 July, where he attempted suicide when police were closing in on him. During the trial, when asked how he felt when strangling Tay's wife, Sek brought up an incident when he was nearly strangled by someone at the Singapore Boys\u2019 Home until he blacked out. Sek said: \u201cAt first I felt discomfort. Then it was very thrilling... as if the lights were being switched on and off.\u201d (Adapted from a 2016 Straits Times recollection article<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/guilty-as-charged-serial-murderer-sek-kim-wah-found-it-thrilling-to-strangle|title=Guilty As Charged: Serial murderer Sek Kim Wah found it 'thrilling' to strangle victims|last=Jalelah|first=Abu Baker|date=2016-05-15|website=The Straits Times|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190216151418/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/guilty-as-charged-serial-murderer-sek-kim-wah-found-it-thrilling-to-strangle|archive-date=2019-02-16|access-date=2019-10-23}}</ref>) However, his encounter at the Boys' Home was found to be made up.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://video.toggle.sg/en/video/series/true-files-s2/ep2/367407|title=True Files S2|website=Toggle|access-date=2019-10-23}}</ref> Nyu was acquitted of murder, but charged with armed robbery and sentenced to life imprisonment and six strokes of cane. Prior to the Andrew Rd triple murders, Sek had also murdered two other people in [[Marine Parade]] by strangling them before disposing their bodies near [[Seletar Reservoir]] on 30 June. Sek was found guilty of murder and according to the Straits Times article: Sek thanked the court for the sentence, saying that he had always wanted to die on the gallows. Eventually, he was hanged on 9 December 1988 for the murder of all five victims.<ref>{{cite news|title=Andrew Road murders: 19-year-old is charged|url=http://newspapers.nl.sg/Digitised/Article/straitstimes19830731-1.2.2.aspx|newspaper=The Straits Times|location=Singapore|date=31 July 1983|accessdate=25 January 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131112213359/http://newspapers.nl.sg/Digitised/Article/straitstimes19830731-1.2.2.aspx|archive-date=2013-11-12|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Andrew Road murders: Two for trial|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article/straitstimes19840322.2.102.aspx|newspaper=The Straits Times|location=Singapore|date=22 March 1984|accessdate=25 January 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160202124533/http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article/straitstimes19840322.2.102.aspx|archive-date=2016-02-02|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Execution By Hanging: 9/12/1988 Sek Kim Wah \u2013 Singapore|url=http://www.truecrimelibrary.com/crime_series_show.php?id=1041&series_number=13|website=True Crime Library|accessdate=25 January 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121213165536/http://www.truecrimelibrary.com/crime_series_show.php?id=1041&series_number=13|archivedate=13 December 2012}}</ref>\n\n===1984===\n* 12 December 1984: Ayakanno Marithamuthu disappearance remained a mystery and his 'murder' was famously dubbed the [[Death of Ayakannu Marithamuthu|curry murder]]. Marithamuthu, a caretaker at the [[Public Utilities Board]] holiday chalets in [[Changi]], was allegedly bludgeoned to death in the [[Orchard Road]] Presbyterian Church. His body was suspected to be dismembered, cooked in curry, packed in plastic bags and disposed in rubbish bins along the roads. However, his remains and evidence of the murder were never found. His wife and her three brothers were charged in court in 1987 but released in the same year due to lack of evidence. The brothers were arrested again and released in June 1991 after spending four years in prison.<ref name=\"Other gruesome murders that took place in Singapore\" /> The case remains unsolved till today.\n\n===1985===\n*22 May 1985: Winnifred Teo Suan Lie, an 18-year-old [[Catholic Junior College]] student, was the victim of a rape and murder case. On 22 May, she left her house for a jog, but never returned home. Her mother made a police report. Teo's naked body was later found lying in undergrowth off Old Holland Road. She suffered multiple stab wounds on her neck. Her body showed signs of a fierce but futile protest, probably made when she was trying to fight off her killer(s). An autopsy showed that she had been sexually assaulted, and died of massive bleeding from the stab wounds. The murderer(s) were never discovered. The case remains unsolved.{{citation needed|date=January 2016}}\n*18 December 1985: Known as Ah Huat, Lim Keng Peng had committed theft and fled from the scene of crime. When he was spotted by detective Goh Ah Khia who had earlier attended to the crime, Lim fired a shot at detective Goh's chest and fled. Detective Goh died afterwards. The murder sparked a manhunt for Lim and he was also responsible for the shooting of a restaurant owner in a robbery attempt in April that year.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://scontent-lht6-1.cdninstagram.com/v/t51.2885-15/e35/51762376_144486183227255_8482172687112765112_n.jpg?_nc_ht=scontent-lht6-1.cdninstagram.com&_nc_cat=111&oh=76ab619d5d51dd99ed0000563f97a109&oe=5E8292A8&ig_cache_key=MTk3NDAxNTU4MzQyNDgyNDgxOQ==.2|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191120032433/https://scontent-lht6-1.cdninstagram.com/v/t51.2885-15/e35/51762376_144486183227255_8482172687112765112_n.jpg?_nc_ht=scontent-lht6-1.cdninstagram.com&_nc_cat=111&oh=76ab619d5d51dd99ed0000563f97a109&oe=5E8292A8&ig_cache_key=MTk3NDAxNTU4MzQyNDgyNDgxOQ==.2|url-status=dead|archive-date=2019-11-20|title=Two killings pointed to Ah Huat|last=Chong|first=Elena|date=1980s|work=The Straits Times|access-date=20 November 2019}}</ref> He evaded detection from the police until on 3 May 1988, he was confronted by the police at a coffee shop in Clementi.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.keshvani.com/print/obituary/stephenkoh.html|title=ASP (Retd) Stephen Koh \u2013 Goodbye to an SPF Legend ...: Keshvani Online|last=Keshvani|first=Nisar|date=|website=www.keshvani.com|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191120033728/https://www.keshvani.com/print/obituary/stephenkoh.html|archive-date=20 November 2019|access-date=20 November 2019}}</ref> While they attempted to arrest Lim, Lim managed to pull out his gun. However, the three police officers who confronted him each fired a shot at Lim. Lim did not survive the ordeal.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://video.toggle.sg/en/video/series/crimewatch-2003/ep1/410732|title=Crimewatch 2003, Episode 1|last=|first=|date=|website=Toggle|access-date=20 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n'''1988'''\n\n*16 February 1988: Upon hearing that his elderly foster father Tan Ai Soon was severely assaulted, the angered 22-year-old Koh Swee Beng gathered Tan's 3 sons Tan Eng Chye, Tan Eng Poh and Tan Eng Geok, the Tan brothers' brother-in-law Ng Eng Guan and their friend Ong Hong Thor to confront 31-year-old Tay Kim Teck, the man who assaulted the elder Tan. They then chased the man and beat him up. During the beating, Koh fatally stabbed Tay twice, leading to Tay's death within minutes. All were later arrested and charged with murder; however, only Koh was found guilty of murder and sentenced to death while the other five had their charges reduced to rioting and they each received a jail term of 2 years and 4 strokes of the cane. Koh was eventually granted clemency by the President of Singapore and had his death sentence commuted to life imprisonment.\n\n\n===1989===\n\n* 15 February 1989: In one of the rare cases involving the [[List of Singapore police officers killed in the line of duty|death of a policeman on duty]], two men were attempting to break into a shop unit at Block 107, Tampines St 11 in the wee hours when they were spotted by two policemen following a tip-off by a member of the public. When confronted, 29-year-old Ong Yeow Tian ran off while one of the policeman, Police Constable (PC) Chua Yeu Hua arrested his accomplice. The other policeman, 22-year-old PC Mirza Abdul Halim chased after Ong. Ong managed to hide in the bushes before launching an assault at PC Mizra. Ong used his weapon to stab PC Mizra before PC Mizra took out his revolver in an attempt to defend himself. Ong overpowered PC Mizra and shot him in the head before fleeing the scene together with the revolver. Ong fled in a taxi before it was sighted by another two policemen, Sergeant Omar Amin and PC Benny Goh. The taxi was pulled over and out of a sudden, Ong use the stolen revolver to fire at them. In return, PC Goh successfully shot Ong in the abdomen before he managed to flee. The [[Police Tactical Unit (Singapore)|Police Task Force]] was activated to hunt for Ong. When one of the groups of the Police Task Force was patrolling, Ong who was hiding managed to shoot one of the man on patrol who was saved by a bulletproof vest. He was eventually subdued and arrested. PC Mizra went into a coma. He was given the rare field promotion to the rank of Corporal before Corporal Mizra passed away a day after the shooting. Ong's accomplice received jail and caning while Ong was found guilty for unlawful discharge of firearms and sentenced to death. Ong's appeal was dismissed and he was hanged on 25 November 1994.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article/newpaper19890215-1.2.3.3|title=Gunfight in Tampines: Cop, suspect shot|last=Ng|first=Wan Ching|date=1989-02-15|work=The New Paper (Singapore)|access-date=2019-10-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://video.toggle.sg/en/video/series/crimewatch-1995/ep7/432007|title=Crimewatch 1995|website=Toggle|access-date=2019-10-14}}</ref> Such incident has resulted in the introduction of snatch-resistant holster in later years.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tnp.sg/news/singapore/man-grabs-gun-shoots-police-officer-khoo-teck-puat-hospital|title=Man grabs gun, shoots police officer at Khoo Teck Puat Hospital / Past cases of gun-snatching|last=Tan|first=Judith|last2=Sen|first2=Ng Jun|date=2015-06-21|website=The New Paper|language=en|access-date=2019-10-14}}</ref>\n*11 April 1989: 50 year old Ibrahim Masod abetted Liow Han Heng, 44 to kidnap Liow\u2019s ex-boss 56 year old Phang Tee Wah, they lured Phang to come to Thompson Plaza and discuss, he was eventually lured to Liow\u2019s house in Yishun, Liow and Ibrahim found him dead on the next day, Phang\u2019s body was found decomposed on 15 April 1989, they were arrested and sentenced to death. Liow died of heart failure before hanged, Ibrahim\u2019s appeal of clemency was rejected and hanged on 1994.\n*2 October 1989: A 17-year-old student from Mayflower Secondary School, Liang Shan Shan, was reported missing by her parents. She was last seen at her school, boarding her school bus at 1 pm. 12 days later, her highly decomposed body was discovered by NS servicemen undergoing their training exercises at Yishun Industrial Park. Forensic pathologist Chao Tzee Cheng could not ascertain the cause of death: he could not tell whether it was a suicide, murder or accident due to the corpse's state of severe decomposition. Nevertheless, the police investigations narrowed down to one suspect: Liang's school bus driver Oh Laye Koh. Oh was then charged with her murder, purely based on circumstantial evidence. He was initially acquitted of her murder at the end of his trial in 1992; however, the prosecution appealed against his acquittal, pointing out how Oh, despite his insistence that he did not kill Liang or know her whereabouts, was able to lead police to the place where Liang's bag and books were, which was some distance away from where her body was found; Oh claimed he went to fix his brakes at 1 pm when the girl was last seen alive, but it was found that he went there at 9 am; and lastly, he even contacted and tried to convince the witnesses to testify on his behalf that they did not see his bus that day. The appeal was accepted, and the re-trial started on 27 April 1994. Oh chose to remain silent when he was told to make his defence. Judicial Commissioner Amarjeet Singh concluded from Oh's decision to remain silent and also his failure to provide evidence \"arose from a consciousness of guilt in the face of the circumstantial evidence\". In JC Singh's words towards Oh, \"I am constrained to draw an irresistible inference that you were the last person with the deceased and you had intentionally caused her death and that the deceased's death was not suicidal or accidental. Although the prosecution was unable to identify the unlawful act, it is not necessary, in my opinion, always to do so.\" As such, on 3 May 1994, Oh was found guilty and convicted of Liang's murder and he was subsequently sentenced to death. Oh's appeal was dismissed on 29 June 1994, and he was executed by hanging on 19 May 1995.\n\n==1990s==\n\n===1990===\n* 15 May 1990: Tan Ah Hong and James Soh Fook Leong were stabbed by two men after chatting on the spiral steps of the Amber Beacon Tower at [[East Coast Park]]. They managed to make their way to a nearby restaurant for help. Soh, who was stabbed in the back, survived the ordeal. Tan died before the police arrived. She was stabbed in the neck, just below the ear. The murderers were never found and the case remains unsolved.{{citation needed|date=January 2015}}\n\n===1991===\n* 4 May 1991: Filipino domestic worker [[Flor Contemplacion]] murdered another Filipino domestic worker, Della Maga, and Nicholas Huang, the four-year-old son of Maga's employer. She was sentenced to death in January 1993 and hanged on 17 March 1995. The incident caused diplomatic relations between Singapore and the Philippines to be strained for some years.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Chew|first1=Valerie|title=Flor Contemplacion|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/infopedia/articles/SIP_1551_2009-07-31.html|publisher=National Library Board, Singapore|accessdate=25 January 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150107061231/http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/infopedia/articles/SIP_1551_2009-07-31.html|archive-date=2015-01-07|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* September 1991: Dutchman [[Johannes van Damme]] was arrested at [[Changi Airport]] after the police found 9.5 pounds of heroin in his suitcase. He was found guilty of drug trafficking, sentenced to death, and hanged on 23 September 1994.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Shenon|first1=Philip|title=Singapore Executes a Dutch Engineer Arrested on Drug Charges|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1994/09/24/world/singapore-executes-a-dutch-engineer-arrested-on-drug-charges.html|newspaper=The New York Times|accessdate=25 January 2015|date=24 September 1994|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150209204916/http://www.nytimes.com/1994/09/24/world/singapore-executes-a-dutch-engineer-arrested-on-drug-charges.html|archive-date=2015-02-09|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===1993===\n* September 1993: Chong Poh Choon, a [[Republic of Singapore Navy|Navy]] regular, murdered his three children at their [[Housing Development Board|HDB]] flat in [[Bukit Batok]]. Chong was eventually sentenced to life imprisonment.<ref>{{cite news|title=Dad who killed children jailed for life|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article/straitstimes19940910-1.2.39.12.aspx|newspaper=The Straits Times|accessdate=25 January 2015|date=10 September 1994|location=Singapore|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160202114445/http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article/straitstimes19940910-1.2.39.12.aspx|archive-date=2016-02-02|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n*4 December 1993 - 26-year-old Maniam S/O Rathinswamy and his accomplice S.S. Asokan, were both sentenced to death for the murder of illegal moneylender Tan Heng Hong. Earlier on in 1993, both Maniam and Asokan murdered Tan and drove Tan's car to Mandai, burning it together with Tan's corpse. Despite the charred remains, Tan's identity was ascertained, as well as the cause of death: the late forensic pathologist Professor Chao Tzee Cheng identified that the cause of Tan's death was a cut artery on his neck. Maniam, who was eventually arrested and tried, claimed that on the night of Tan's murder, while the three of them were arguing violently over letting Tan to pay back Asokan's commission over a pen he sold to Tan, Asokan became so agitated that he picked up the axe Maniam bought the day before to kill Tan, and it was Asokan's idea to burn the corpse, proclaiming his innocence. However, Asokan, who fled to Malaysia and got extradited back to Singapore to face trial, stated that Maniam told him to grab the axe and kill Tan when he refused to pay the commission, saying that he did not mean to hit or kill him, and that he was only following Maniam's orders. Justice Sinnathuray rejected their defences and stating that if they had no intention to kill, the weapons would not have been brought in the first place, and satisfied that they both shared a common intention to murder Tan, therefore he convicted both of them as charged. The two men were eventually hanged on 9 December 1995.\n\n===1994===\n* 6 June 1994 : Known as the Oriental Hotel Murder, two Japanese tourists Fujii Isae, 49 and Miyoko Takishita, 56, were robbed by two Malay men, 25-year-old Abdul Nasir bin Amer Hamsah and 32-year-old Abdul Rahman bin Arshad. The two acquaintances, who came to the Oriental Hotel for a job interview, saw the Japanse tour group which Fujii and Takashita were with, and deciding to rob them. Takashita was assaulted by Abdul Rahman and she pretended to faint from the assault. Fujii, however, was severely assaulted by Abdul Nasir. As he was trying to escape, he lost his balance and accidentally stepped onto Fujii's face. This led to a facial fracture and caused Fujii to suffocate to death. Both men were not arrested until when two years later, Abdul Nasir was arrested for attempting to rob and suffocate a taxi driver. His fingerprints were then tested and found to match those found at the crime scene, and thus he was charged with the murder of Fujii. Abdul Rahman, who was later found to be in prison serving a 20-month jail sentence for theft, was also charged with murder, though he later pleaded guilty to robbery with hurt, and sentenced to 10 years' jail with 16 strokes of the cane. Abdul Nasir was eventually found guilty of robbery with hurt and sentenced to 18 years' jail and 18 strokes of the cane. However, it was not the end of Abdul Nasir's ordeal, as he had to go back to court to face a kidnapping charge, which he committed together with drug trafficker Low Theng Gee during the period of his remand before the trial, where they briefly kidnapped two officers before being abducted. Abdul Nasir was later convicted of kidnapping and sentenced to life imprisonment with 12 strokes of the cane in January 1997. Justice T. S. Sinnathuray ordered Abdul Nasir's life sentence to run consecutively with the jail term he received for robbing Fujii, meaning Abdul Nasir had to serve a total of 38 years in prison (At that time, life imprisonment in Singapore was defined as a 20-year jail sentence). Abdul Nasir filed an appeal for his two jail terms to run concurrently, but it was dismissed on 20 August 1997. However, Chief Justice Yong Pung How decided that the definition of life imprisonment should be considered as a term of imprisonment for a convict's remaining natural life instead of 20 years' imprisonment, and this amendment will apply to future cases. Abdul Nasir was not affected by this and hence his life term remained as a jail term of 20 years, and he would still be spending 38 years in prison.\n\n===1995===\n* 26 February 1995: Britain's oldest merchant bank [[Barings Bank]] collapsed due to Briton [[Nick Leeson]]'s trading activities, who lost $1.4 billion by speculating on the [[Singapore International Monetary Exchange]], primarily using [[futures contracts]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Barings Bank collapses from Nick Leeson's losses |url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/history/events/e7cb71fe-b7b9-445e-b5d1-655bf301d6a8|website=NLB|accessdate=20 July 2019|date=26 February 1995}}</ref> He was arrested on 23 November 1995 after fleeing Singapore for 272 days. Subsequently, Nick Leeson pleaded guilty to two charges out of three charges of forgery and eight charges of cheating and was sentenced to 6\u00bd years in prison.<ref>{{cite news|title=Guilty As Charged: Rogue trader Nick Leeson brought down Britain's oldest merchant bank Barings|url=http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/guilty-as-charged-rogue-trader-nick-leeson-brought-down-britains-oldest|newspaper=The Straits Times|location=Singapore|accessdate=16 May 2016|date=16 May 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160516050310/http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/guilty-as-charged-rogue-trader-nick-leeson-brought-down-britains-oldest|archive-date=2016-05-16|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* 8 March 1995: Briton [[John Martin Scripps|John Martin]] murdered South African Gerard George Lowe in River View Hotel, dismembered his body, and disposed the body parts in the [[Singapore River]]. He was found guilty of murder and hanged on 19 April 1996.<ref name=\"Other gruesome murders that took place in Singapore\">{{cite news|title=Other gruesome murders that took place in Singapore|url=http://news.asiaone.com/News/AsiaOne+News/Crime/Story/A1Story20120403-337375.html|newspaper=The New Paper|location=Singapore|accessdate=25 January 2015|date=4 April 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150104164706/http://news.asiaone.com/News/AsiaOne+News/Crime/Story/A1Story20120403-337375.html|archivedate=4 January 2015}}</ref>\n\n===1996===\n\n* 4 October 1996: 29-year-old Zulkarnain Bin Kemat murdered his drinking and smoking partner, 51-year-old Madam Jetkor Miang Singh at her flat in Ang Mo Kio. Zulkarnain and Madam Jetkor were arguing before Zulkarnain stabbed her neck with a pocket nail knife and kicked her repeatedly. To conceal his crime, Zulkarnain wiped the table containing his fingerprints. He also discarded the ashtray, but failed to discard the cigarette butts which contain his saliva. The case was initially unsolved as police could not establish concrete evidence that Zulkarnian murdered Madam Jetkor and [[DNA profiling]] was not fully reliable. Over the years as DNA profiling becomes more accurate and faster, collection of DNA samples from all convicts was made mandatory in 2002.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sso.agc.gov.sg/Acts-Supp/45-2002/Published/20021226?DocDate=20021226|title=Registration of Criminals (Amendment) Act 2002 - Singapore Statutes Online|last=|first=|date=26 December 2002|website=sso.agc.gov.sg|language=en|access-date=10 November 2019}}</ref> The case reopened in November 2003, which matched the DNA sample found on the cigarette to Zulkarnian. In 2005, 37-year-old Zulkarnian was charged with culpable homicide and sentenced to 8 years imprisonment and 6 strokes of the cane. His sentence ran concurrently with his sentence of 6.5 years and 3 strokes of the cane for consuming drugs, which was imposed in September 2000.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.corpun.com/sgj00502.htm|title=Done in by DNA|last=Fong|first=Tanya|last2=Chong|first2=Elena|date=1 February 2005|publisher=The Straits Times|via=www.corpun.com|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191110145404/https://www.corpun.com/sgj00502.htm|archive-date=10 November 2019|access-date=10 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://video.toggle.sg/en/video/series/crimewatch-2005/ep2/411119|title=Crimewatch 2005, Episode 2|last=|first=|date=|website=Toggle|access-date=10 November 2019}}</ref> After his release, he was arrested again and currently serving a life sentence for drug trafficking in 2013.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.supremecourt.gov.sg/docs/default-source/module-document/judgement/pp-v-zulkarnain-and-others-16-july-2018-final-for-release-pdf.pdf|title=[2018] SGHC 161, Criminal Case No. 43 of 2016|last=|first=|date=16 July 2018|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191110150424/https://www.supremecourt.gov.sg/docs/default-source/module-document/judgement/pp-v-zulkarnain-and-others-16-july-2018-final-for-release-pdf.pdf|archive-date=10 November 2019|access-date=10 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n===1997===\n* 18 June 1997: A woman, Komala Karuppiah was murdered at Block 505 Serangoon North Avenue 4. Her husband, Kannan s/o Marie, who had came back from a trip to Tapah, Perak for a wedding with his son, Sashi, had called the police to report the murder. At first, the police had suspected it was a robbery gone wrong, but after asking Kannan's son, Sashi, Kannan confessed that he had killed Komala after a dispute over a gold ring he had bought for the bride in the marriage. \n\n*20 June 1997: Known as the \"Duck Den Murder\", 19-year-old Malaysian youth and male prostitute Lim Chin Chong murdered his 65-year-old employer and duck den operator Low Cheng Quee (a duck den is known as a brothel for male prostitutes). Lim fled to Malaysia and was on the run for nearly 20 days, seeking refuge in the homes of his acquaintances and relatives before his arrest by the Royal Malaysian Police on 9 July 1997. He was later extradited to Singapore and charged with the murder of Low. On 1 December 1997, after the end of a 6-day-long trial from 24 November 1997, Justice Kan Ting Chiu found Lim guilty of murder and sentenced him to death. Lim was hanged on 23 October 1998, after the rejection of his appeal against the sentence.\n\n===1998===\n* 11 January 1998: A Bulgarian student, 26-year-old Iordanka Apostolova, was involved in an argument with 22-year-old Shaiful Edham Adam at a housing unit in Depot Road. Adam chopped Ms Apostolova's throat together with the help of his friend, 26-year-old Norishyam Mohamed Ali. Shaiful's wife, Hezlinda A Rahman together with the two of them help to dispose her body at a canal near Tenah Merah Ferry Road. Her body was discovered on 13 January, which led to the arrest of Shaiful and Hezlinda. Norishyam surrendered to the police shortly after. Both Shaiful and Norishyam were found guilty of murder and sentenced to death. They were hanged on 2 July 1999 while Hezlinda was sentenced to 6 years imprisonment for helping to dispose Ms Apostolova's body.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/former-detective-richard-lim-beng-gee-65-dies-5-high-profile-cases-he-helped|title=Former detective Richard Lim Beng Gee, 65, dies: 5 high-profile cases he helped crack / BULGARIAN WOMAN'S BODY FOUND IN CANAL, CASE SOLVED IN 36 HOURS|last=Lee|first=Min Kok|date=2016-01-19|website=The Straits Times|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191012154003/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/former-detective-richard-lim-beng-gee-65-dies-5-high-profile-cases-he-helped|archive-date=2019-10-12|access-date=2019-10-12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://video.toggle.sg/en/video/series/true-files-s1/ep13/366934|title=True Files S1|website=Toggle|access-date=2019-10-12}}</ref>\n*7 May 1998: Two men were consuming [[heroin]] at a rubbish centre under a flat in [[Woodlands, Singapore|Woodlands]] when they were spotted by two policemen. In the midst of scuffle, one of the suspects was arrested while the other, 40-year-old Tan Cheng Lock, Anthony snatched a revolver from one of the officer and shot him in the thigh before breaking free. He seek refuge at his mother's flat in Chai Chee before the police located him. The [[Special Tactics and Rescue (Singapore)|Special Tactics and Rescue (STAR)]] unit raided the flat the following night. During the raid, Tan use the stolen revolver to shoot himself to death before police could arrest him.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tnp.sg/news/singapore/man-grabs-gun-shoots-police-officer-khoo-teck-puat-hospital|title=Man grabs gun, shoots police officer at Khoo Teck Puat Hospital / Past cases of gun snatching|last=Tan|first=Judith|last2=Ng|first2=Jun Sen|date=2015-06-21|website=The New Paper|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170507033844/http://www.tnp.sg/news/singapore/man-grabs-gun-shoots-police-officer-khoo-teck-puat-hospital|archive-date=2017-05-07|access-date=2019-10-12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://video.toggle.sg/en/video/series/crimewatch-1999/ep1/433256|title=Crimewatch 1999|last=|first=|date=31 March 1999|website=Toggle|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191012061122/https://video.toggle.sg/en/series/crimewatch-1999/ep1/433256|archive-date=2019-10-12|access-date=2019-10-12}}</ref>\n*20 April 1998: 23-year-old Malaysian freelance assistant cameraman and prop assistant Jonaris Badlishah killed 42-year-old make-up artist Sally Poh Bee Eng over a Rolex wrist watch. He was hanged on 8 Dec 1998 after a 19-day trial.<ref>{{cite news|title=Guilty As Charged: Jonaris Badlishah killed to get a Rolex for girlfriend|url=http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/guilty-as-charged-jonaris-badlishah-killed-to-get-a-rolex-for-girlfriend|newspaper=The Straits Times|location=Singapore|accessdate=16 May 2016|date=16 May 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160515220659/http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/guilty-as-charged-jonaris-badlishah-killed-to-get-a-rolex-for-girlfriend|archive-date=2016-05-15|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===1999===\n*21 April 1999: At Phoenix Garden, retired Inspector T Maniam was found dead after being beaten to death. The witnesses, a maid and his youngest step-daughter, Fairos Banu provided with evidence. Although the maid's evidence proved inconclusive, it helped them to find the vehicle the murderers used and his step-daughter's evidence proved that one of the murderers was her mother's boyfriend that was beaten by Maniam after he saw them walking hand in hand near his home in 1996. The mastermind of the murder, his wife had thought of murdering him as the home he lived with her and his stepdaughters as it had a value of $1.5 million. She had thought that once he died, the house would be hers, since she was a joint owner. She and two others involved were arrested and sentenced to hang.\n* 9 September 1999: At Sian Tuan Ave, a 14-year-old daughter of a wealthy car dealer was kidnapped by 3 kidnappers: Chinese nationals Zhou Jian Guang and Shi Song Jing, aged 26 and 29 respectively together with their mastermind, 33 year-old Singaporean Vincent Lee Chuan Leong. She was kept in a rented house while they demanded S$500,000 for her release. The sum was re-negotiated to S$330,000 and paid to them before she was released on the morning of 12 September. Just 20 minutes after her release, Lee was arrested at his flat. Separately, the two Chinese nationals were arrested on 14 September. They were all found guilty of kidnapping and sentenced to life imprisonment.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/former-detective-richard-lim-beng-gee-65-dies-5-high-profile-cases-he-helped|title=Former detective Richard Lim Beng Gee, 65, dies: 5 high-profile cases he helped crack / TEENAGE GIRL KIDNAPPED WHILE WALKING HOME|last=Lee|first=Min Kok|date=2016-01-19|website=The Straits Times|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191012154609/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/former-detective-richard-lim-beng-gee-65-dies-5-high-profile-cases-he-helped|archive-date=2019-10-12|access-date=2019-10-14}}</ref>\n\n==2000s==\n===2000===\n\n* 8/26 August 2000: Three men: 34-year-old Wan Kamil Mohamed Shafian, 35-year-old Ibrahim Mohamed and 30-year-old Rosli Ahmat decided to commit robberies using weapons and firearms they had bought. They intended to use a taxi as a getaway vehicle and so on the morning of 8 August, they targeted a taxi driven by 42-year-old Koh Ngiap Yong(\u8bb8\u4e1a\u8363). They told Koh to drive the taxi to Chestnut Drive before handcuffing him. Wan Kamil ordered Rosli Ahmat to stab Koh with a bayonet before they unlocked the handcuff. In the process, they dropped a handcuff key. They drove to Woodlands and intended to commit robberies, before backing out due to the presence of [[Closed-circuit television|CCTV]]<nowiki/>s.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/former-detective-richard-lim-beng-gee-65-dies-5-high-profile-cases-he-helped|title=Former detective Richard Lim Beng Gee, 65, dies: 5 high-profile cases he helped crack / TAXI DRIVER KILLED BY THREE MEN|last=Lee|first=Min Kok|date=2016-01-19|website=The Straits Times|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191012154609/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/former-detective-richard-lim-beng-gee-65-dies-5-high-profile-cases-he-helped|archive-date=2019-10-12|access-date=2019-10-22}}</ref> Koh's<nowiki/> body was discovered the <nowiki/>following morning, but the murder became unsolved due to limited leads until another murder occurred on the evening of 26 August. At an overhead bridge at Jalan Kukoh, a money changer was robbed and shot twice by Wan Kamil, together with the help of his accomplice Ibrahim Mohamed. The stolen phone (From the deceased money changer) they used after the murder was traced by police. All three of them were arrested on 15 October 2000 by STAR officers. The taxi driver's murder was traced to them when the handcuffs and keys recovered at Wan Kamil's flat did not tally with each other. On 5 September 2001, all three of them were found guilty of murder and sentenced to death. They were hanged on 25 October 2002.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://video.toggle.sg/en/video/series/crimewatch-2002/ep10/411133|title=Crimewatch 2002|website=Toggle|access-date=2019-10-22}}</ref>\n\n===2001===\n*6 January 2001: 45-year-old Zaiton binte Abu Bakar, a divorcee, was murdered at her home, was found by her daughter Norjanna after she came back from clearing her work at her uncle's accountancy firm and visiting her father. The suspect, 29-year-old Othman Hassan, was found to have murdered her after police inspected his home and found belongings owned by Zaiton. He had murdered her when he went to her home to fix faulty taps and return a debt he owed, but when an argument about the debt escalated, he stabbed her six times in the abdomen and then ransacked her belongings. He was sentenced to nine years of jail and 12 strokes of the cane.\n* 14 May 2001: 34-year-old Anthony Ler Wee Teang made headlines for hiring a youth to assassinate his wife, 30-year-old Annie Leong Wai Mun. Ler approached four youths and offered them a reward of S$100,000 to kill Leong, who was in the midst of divorcing him. A 15-year-old whom Ler had known for five years accepted the offer. Ler manipulated the youth to carry out the deed and after several failed attempts, the youth fatally stabbed Leong with a knife given to him by Ler. Ler was found guilty of conspiring and abetting the murder of Leong and was hanged on 13 December 2002. The youth was spared the death sentence because he was under 18 years old when he killed Leong and placed under indefinite detention under the President's pleasure.<ref>{{cite news|title=Devil with a smile|url=http://news.asiaone.com/news/crime/devil-smile?page=0%2C0|newspaper=The Straits Times|location=Singapore|accessdate=25 January 2015|date=5 October 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170407030133/http://news.asiaone.com/news/crime/devil-smile?page=0%2C0|archive-date=2017-04-07|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Teen who killed Anthony Ler's wife in 2001 appeals for clemency after 16 years behind bars |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/teen-who-killed-anthony-lers-wife-in-2001-appeals-for-clemency-after-16-years |accessdate=20 July 2019 |publisher=The Straits Times |date=25 November 2017}}</ref> On 2 November 2018, the youth, at 32 years of age, was released after his petition for clemency was granted by [[President of Singapore|President]] [[Halimah Yacob]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/annie-leongs-teen-killer-gets-clemency-after-17-years-in-jail|title=Teen who killed Anthony Ler's wife gets clemency after 17 years in jail|last=hermes|date=2018-12-13|website=The Straits Times|language=en|access-date=2019-04-04|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181214235554/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/annie-leongs-teen-killer-gets-clemency-after-17-years-in-jail|archive-date=14 December 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n*10 August 2001: A day before the wedding of 33-year-old businessman Tay Teng Joo, he was kidnapped by 45-year-old Chng Teo Heng together with the assistance of his accomplices, 52-year-old businesswoman Agnes Ng Lei Eng and 42-year-old freelance painter Ng Soon Teck. Tay was blindfolded and driven around in a car while they demanded a ransom of S$4 million. The sum was eventually reduced to S$1.22 million and Tay was released. It wasn't long before police nabbed all three suspects after a police report was made in 24 hours. Despite spending only S$903, the police managed to recover the money. They were all sentenced to life imprisonment, with Chng given an additional six strokes of cane for using a knife when abducting Tay into the car.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/three-previous-cases-of-kidnapping-for-ransom-over-13-years|title=Three previous cases of kidnapping for ransom over 13 years|last=Lim|first=Yan Liang|date=2014-01-10|website=The Straits Times|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191013160407/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/three-previous-cases-of-kidnapping-for-ransom-over-13-years|archive-date=2019-10-13|access-date=2019-10-13}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://video.toggle.sg/en/video/series/crimewatch-2002/ep3/411123|title=Crimewatch 2002|website=Toggle|access-date=2019-10-13}}</ref>\n*2 October 2001: A man robbed and stabbed a 28-year-old woman, Ms Soh San in a lift at Bukit Batok. She died from her injuries while the robber fled with S$30. Despite appeals for eyewitnesses from an episode of [[Crimewatch (Singaporean TV series)|Crimewatch]], the case remains unsolved.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://video.toggle.sg/en/video/series/crimewatch-2001/ep9/411107|title=Crimewatch 2001|last=|first=|date=|website=Toggle|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190921191347/https://video.toggle.sg/en/video/series/crimewatch-2001/ep9/411107|archive-date=2019-09-21|access-date=2019-09-21}}</ref> The man went on to commit other offences in the following years while police have no knowledge of his unconfessed killing. On 17 November 2013, the case reopened when 28-year-old Gunasegaran Ramasamy surrendered himself and confessed to the 2001 killing out of guilt. He was 16 years of age when he killed Ms Soh. Initially charged with murder, his charge was reduced to robbery with hurt. He was sentenced to 10 years imprisonment and 12 strokes of the cane.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/man-gets-10-years-and-12-strokes-of-the-cane-for-stabbing-woman-in-2001-lift|title=Man gets 10 years and 12 strokes of the cane for stabbing woman in 2001 lift robbery|last=Chong|first=Elena|date=2017-03-20|website=The Straits Times|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190921190922/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/man-gets-10-years-and-12-strokes-of-the-cane-for-stabbing-woman-in-2001-lift|archive-date=2019-09-21|access-date=2019-09-21}}</ref>\n*9-24 December 2001: A terrorist group, [[Jemaah Islamiyah]] (JI) plot to [[Singapore embassies attack plot|bomb several targets in Singapore]] such as US-aligned foreign embassies and [[Yishun MRT station]] were uncovered by the Internal Security Department, leading to an arrest of 15 JI Singaporeans that month. In subsequent years, about 40 more Singaporean JIs or JI-linked individuals were arrested.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/opinion/ji-arrests-15-years-later|title=JI arrests: 15 years later|last=Jayakumar|first=Shashi|date=2016-12-09|website=The Straits Times|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191004175741/https://www.straitstimes.com/opinion/ji-arrests-15-years-later|archive-date=2019-10-04|access-date=2019-10-28}}</ref>\n*\n\n===2002===\n* 2 January 2002: British financial adviser Michael McCrea murdered his friend Kho Nai Guan and Kho's girlfriend, Lan Ya Ming, in Kho's apartment in Pinewood Garden. With the help of his girlfriend, Audrey Ong, and two others, McCrea disposed Kho and Lan's bodies in a car and abandoned it at the car park in [[Orchard Towers]]. McCrea and Ong fled from Singapore on 5 January and were arrested in Melbourne in June after being on the run for about six months. Ong was deported to Singapore and sentenced in February 2003 to 12 years imprisonment, while McCrea was extradited to Singapore in 2005 and sentenced to 24 years imprisonment in June 2006.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Tan|first1=Yee Lin|title=Orchard Towers double murder|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/infopedia/articles/SIP_1603_2009-10-31.html|publisher=National Library Board, Singapore|accessdate=25 January 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150210053321/http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/infopedia/articles/SIP_1603_2009-10-31.html|archive-date=2015-02-10|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* December 2002: Australian [[Van Tuong Nguyen]] was convicted of carrying about 400 grams of heroin at [[Changi Airport]] while travelling from Cambodia to Australia and sentenced to death on 20 March 2004 by the [[High Court of Singapore|High Court]]. After a failed appeal to the [[Court of Appeal of Singapore|Court of Appeal]] and despite pleas for clemency from the Australian government, Nguyen was hanged on 2 December 2005.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/asia-pacific/4487366.stm|title=Australian executed in Singapore|date=2 December 2005|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=26 January 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141129075117/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/asia-pacific/4487366.stm|archive-date=2014-11-29|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===2003===\n\n* 21 March/8 April 2003: Already wanted for sex-related offences by Malaysian police, 28-year-old Malaysian Suresh Nair Vellayutham raped a clinic assistant in a cubicle of a female toilet on the morning of 21 March 2003. Then on the afternoon of 8 April 2003 at the Grand Hyatt hotel, he rushed into a hotel room where two air stewardess just entered and raped the 31-year-old air stewardess twice while molesting her 30-year-old colleague. Suresh was arrested on 11 April 2003. He was found guilty of rape, molestation and threatening his victims. He was sentenced to 26 years jail and 40 strokes of the cane.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/regional/2004/11/25/tormented-by-a-malaysian-serial-rapist|title=Tormented by a Malaysian serial rapist|last=|first=|date=2004-11-25|website=The Star Online|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191025200009/https://www.thestar.com.my/news/regional/2004/11/25/tormented-by-a-malaysian-serial-rapist|archive-date=2019-10-25|access-date=2019-10-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2003/11/30/malaysian-jailed-for-raping-singapore-stewardess|title=Malaysian jailed for raping Singapore stewardess|last=|first=|date=2003-11-30|website=The Star Online|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191025194147/https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2003/11/30/malaysian-jailed-for-raping-singapore-stewardess|archive-date=2019-10-25|access-date=2019-10-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://video.toggle.sg/en/video/series/true-files-s4/ep1/367500|title=True Files S4|website=Toggle|access-date=2019-10-25}}</ref>\n*25 December 2003: A 7-year-old girl was briefly kidnapped by two kidnappers: 35-year-old Tan Ping Koon and 42-year-old Chua Ser Lian. She was in the landed house at Yio Chu Kang when Chua sneaked in and took the girl into a car driven by Tan. A catering assistance caught them in the act and took down the license plate number. The info was relayed to the catering assistance's husband and when he spotted the getaway car, he decided to trail after them in his own vehicle. The two kidnappers realised they were followed and released the girl at Tampines. However, the two kidnappers called the girl's father the following day and demanded S$1 million from him or they would hurt her family. The sum of S$70,000 was eventually agreed and paid to them before Tan and Chua were subsequently arrested. They were both found guilty of kidnapping and sentenced to life imprisonment with three strokes of cane.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mothership.sg/2018/01/kidnap-cases-singapore/|title=Last 2 times children were kidnapped off the streets in S\u2019pore: 1999 & 2003|last=Lay|first=Belmont|date=2019-10-14|website=Mothership.sg|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191014114330/https://mothership.sg/2018/01/kidnap-cases-singapore/|archive-date=2019-10-14|access-date=2019-10-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://video.toggle.sg/en/video/series/crimewatch-2004/ep9/411072|title=Crimewatch 2004|website=Toggle|access-date=2019-10-14}}</ref>\n\n===2004===\n* 2 April 2004: 44-year-old Chia Teck Leng was sentenced to 42 years in jail by High Court Judge Tay Yong Kwang after swindling four foreign banks out of $117 million from 1999 to 2003 using his position as the financial manager of [[Asia Pacific Breweries]] (APB).<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/guilty-as-charged-chia-teck-leng-led-a-double-life-and-cheated-banks-of | title=Guilty As Charged: Chia Teck Leng led a double life and cheated banks of millions | publisher=Straits Times | date=16 May 2016 | accessdate=16 May 2016 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160517061212/http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/guilty-as-charged-chia-teck-leng-led-a-double-life-and-cheated-banks-of | archive-date=2016-05-17 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Longest jail term for the worst case of commercial fraud |url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/infopedia/articles/SIP_422_2005-01-25.html |publisher=NLB |accessdate=20 July 2019}}</ref>\n* 10 October 2004: Eight-year-old Huang Na was [[Murder of Huang Na|found dead and stuffed inside a box]] at [[Telok Blangah Hill Park]]. Malaysian Took Leng How, an acquaintance of Huang's mother, was found guilty of murder and sentenced to death on 27 August 2005. Took was hanged on 3 November 2006 after failing to overturn his conviction at the [[Court of Appeal of Singapore|Court of Appeal]] and after [[President of Singapore|President]] [[S. R. Nathan]] rejected his plea for clemency.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Tan|first1=Yee Lin|title=Huang Na murder|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/infopedia/articles/SIP_1604_2009-10-31.html|publisher=National Library Board, Singapore|accessdate=25 January 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150110042757/http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/infopedia/articles/SIP_1604_2009-10-31.html|archive-date=2015-01-10|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* November 2004: Nigerian [[Iwuchukwu Amara Tochi]] was arrested at Changi Airport for carrying 100 capsules containing heroin. He was hanged on 26 January 2007 after failing to overturn his conviction at the Court of Appeal and after President S. R. Nathan rejected his plea for clemency.<ref>{{cite news|title=Young Tochi hanged for heroin smuggling|url=http://www.smh.com.au/news/world/young-tochi-hanged-for-heroin-smuggling/2007/01/26/1169594481223.html|publisher=The Sydney Morning Herald|date=26 January 2007|accessdate=26 January 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160209074955/http://www.smh.com.au/news/world/young-tochi-hanged-for-heroin-smuggling/2007/01/26/1169594481223.html|archive-date=2016-02-09|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===2005===\n* 15\u201316 June 2005: Known as the [[Kallang]] body parts murder, factory supervisor Leong Siew Chor (\u6881\u5c11\u521d) murdered his lover, Chinese national Liu Hong Mei who was an ethnic Manchu woman from [[Northeastern China]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://news.sohu.com/20050620/n226015193.shtml|title=22\u5c81\u957f\u6625\u59d1\u5a18\u65b0\u52a0\u5761\u906d\u788e\u5c38 \u5acc\u72af\u5468\u4e94\u5c06\"\u8fc7\u5802\"-\u641c\u72d0\u65b0\u95fb\u4e2d\u5fc3|website=news.sohu.com}}</ref> and dismembered her body into seven parts. He dumped her body parts at multiple places across the island, such as [[Kallang River]]. He also stole her credit card and withdrew $2,000 from her bank account after having sex with her. He was arrested on 17 June 2005 and sentenced to death on 19 May 2006. Leong was hanged on 30 November 2007 after President S. R. Nathan rejected his plea for clemency.<ref name=\"Other gruesome murders that took place in Singapore\" /><ref>{{cite web|last1=Tok|first1=Cherylyn|title=Kallang body parts murder|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/infopedia/articles/SIP_1793_2011-03-17.html|publisher=National Library Board, Singapore|accessdate=25 January 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141227143223/http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/infopedia/articles/SIP_1793_2011-03-17.html|archive-date=2014-12-27|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* 7 September 2005: Filipino domestic worker Guen Garlejo Aguilar killed another Filipino domestic worker, Jane Parangan La Puebla, over a sum of S$2,000 that La Puebla owed her. She hid La Puebla's body in her room for two days before dismembering it and dumping the body parts near [[Orchard MRT station]] and [[MacRitchie Reservoir]]. The court found her guilty of manslaughter and sentenced her to 10 years imprisonment in May 2006.<ref name=\"Other gruesome murders that took place in Singapore\" />\n\n===2006===\n* 15 February 2006: In the first crime involving firearms since 2000, Tan Chor Jin, nicknamed the \"One-eyed Dragon\" forcefully entered the flat of Lim Hock Soon, a nightclub owner. He seized Lim's family valuables before tying up Lim, his wife, his daughter and Lim's maid. He then proceeded to shoot and kill Lim, where five of the six bullets hit Lim. He managed to flee the country with the help of his accomplice, Ho Yueh Keong. He was nabbed by the [[Royal Malaysian Police]] 10 days later at a hotel in Kuala Lumpur before being extradited back to Singapore on 1 March 2006. Initially charged with murder, his charge was amended to discharging of firearm. During the trial, Tan choose to be unrepresented. In one of his defence, he claimed that Lim was about to hit him with a chair and thus shot Lim in self-defence. But his defence fell flat when the prosecution noted that Lim was tied up and could not have lifted the chair. On 22 May 2007, he was found guilty and sentenced to hang. (Under Singapore law, offenders charged with unlawful discharge of firearms will be sentenced to death, even with no intention to kill.)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sso.agc.gov.sg/Act/AOA1973|title=Arms Offences Act - Singapore Statutes Online|last=|first=|date=|website=sso.agc.gov.sg|language=en|access-date=2019-10-13}}</ref> The Court of Appeal also dismissed Tan's appeal against his death sentence on 30 January 2008.<ref>{{cite web|title=Tan Chor Jin v Public Prosecutor [2008] 4 SLR 306; [2008] SGCA 32|url=http://www.singaporelaw.sg/sglaw/laws-of-singapore/case-law/free-law/court-of-appeal-judgments/13530-tan-chor-jin-v-public-prosecutor-2008-4-slr-306-2008-sgca-32|website=SingaporeLaw.sg|accessdate=25 January 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160130170543/http://www.singaporelaw.sg/sglaw/laws-of-singapore/case-law/free-law/court-of-appeal-judgments/13530-tan-chor-jin-v-public-prosecutor-2008-4-slr-306-2008-sgca-32|archive-date=30 January 2016|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> He was subsequently executed on 9 January 2009.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Teo|first1=Wan Gek|title=Donor 'designated kidney expressly' for Tang|newspaper=The Straits Times|location=Singapore|url=http://news.asiaone.com/News/the+Straits+Times/Story/A1Story20090111-113780.html|accessdate=25 January 2015|date=11 January 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160131175029/http://news.asiaone.com/News/the+Straits+Times/Story/A1Story20090111-113780.html|archive-date=31 January 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=The suspected murderer who shocked Singapore|url=http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/world/archives/2007/01/22/2003345842|accessdate=25 January 2015|agency=Taipei Times|date=22 January 2007|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140607153720/http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/world/archives/2007/01/22/2003345842|archive-date=2014-06-07|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/guilty-as-charged-one-eyed-dragon-tan-chor-jin-shot-nightclub-owner|title=Guilty As Charged: 'One-eyed Dragon' Tan Chor Jin shot nightclub owner|last=Hoe|first=Pei Shan|date=2016-05-17|website=The Straits Times|language=en|access-date=2019-10-13}}</ref> His accomplice, Ho, was charged on 15 July 2015 for harbouring Tan out of Singapore.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Alkhatib |first1=Shaffiq |url=https://www.tnp.sg/news/singapore-news/man-charged-harbouring-one-eyed-dragon |title=Man charged with harbouring 'One-Eyed Dragon' |website=The New Paper |access-date=13 October 2019 |date=15 July 2015}}</ref> Ho pleaded guilty on 8 August 2016.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Hussain |first1=Amir |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/one-eyed-dragon-tan-chor-jins-accomplice-found-guilty-after-9-years-on-the |title='One-eyed Dragon' Tan Chor Jin's accomplice found guilty after 9 years on the run |website=The Straits Times |access-date=13 October 2019 |date=8 August 2016}}</ref> Two days later, he was sentenced to a 20-month jail term.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Hussain |first1=Amir |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/one-eyed-dragon-tan-chor-jins-accomplice-jailed-20-months-after-9-years-on |title='One-eyed Dragon' Tan Chor Jin's accomplice jailed 20 months after 9 years on the run |website=The Straits Times |access-date=13 October 2019 |date=10 August 2016}}</ref>\n*June 2006: Lawyer David Rasif fled with S$11.3 million of his clients' money, one of the largest amount misappropriated by a rogue Singaporean lawyer. He was last seen by his wife in [[Bangkok]], [[Thailand]] on 5 June 2006. About S$7.4 million in cash and gold have been recovered and as of today, he is still at large.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.asiaone.com/singapore/fugitive-david-rasifs-daughter-new-face-first-runner|title=Fugitive David Rasif's daughter is New Face first runner-up / Who is David Rasif?|last=Yeoh|first=Wee Teck|date=2013-10-25|website=AsiaOne|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191016120749/https://www.asiaone.com/singapore/fugitive-david-rasifs-daughter-new-face-first-runner?nopaging=1|archive-date=2019-10-16|access-date=2019-10-16}}</ref>\n\n===2007===\n* 1 July 2007: 16-year-old teenager Muhammad Nasir Abdul Aziz was ordered by his lover, 24-year-old Aniza Binte Essa to murder her husband, 29-year-old Manap Sarlip. That early morning, Manap was stabbed nine times by Nasir at the lift landing area and just outside the husband and wife housing unit in Whampoa. Both Nasir and Aniza were arrested shortly after. Aniza initially faced the death penalty for abetting murder, which was later reduced to abetting manslaughter. A psychiatrist discovered she had a mental disorder that diminished her responsibility for the murder. She was sentenced to 9 years jail while Nasir pleaded guilty to murder. As he was under 18 years old when he killed Manap, he was spared the gallows and hence indefinitely detained under the President's pleasure.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.asiaone.com/News/AsiaOne+News/Crime/Story/A1Story20080415-59971.html|title=Teen detained under the President's pleasure for murder of lover's husband|last=|first=|date=|website=www.asiaone.com|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080523192115/https://www.asiaone.com/News/AsiaOne%2BNews/Crime/Story/A1Story20080415-59971.html|archive-date=2008-05-23|access-date=2019-10-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.asiaone.com/print/News/The+Straits+Times/Story/A1Story20080415-59845.html|title=Teen, 17, pleads guilty but won't be hanged|last=Lum|first=Selina|date=2008-04-15|website=www.asiaone.com|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080610120146/http://www.asiaone.com/print/News/The%2BStraits%2BTimes/Story/A1Story20080415-59845.html|archive-date=2008-06-10|access-date=2019-10-29}}</ref>\n\n===2008===\n* 27 February 2008: In a rare case of a criminal escaping from prison, [[Jemaah Islamiyah]] terrorist [[Mas Selamat Kastari]] discreetly escaped from the now defunct Whitley Road Detention Centre, sparking a nation-wide manhunt. He managed to flee Singapore across to Johor via a handmade floating device on 3 March 2008 and eventually hid himself in Skudai, Johor for about a year before he was arrested by Malaysia's Counter Terrorism Division on 1 April 2009.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/asia/se-asia/mas-selamat-hid-butter-used-mineral-water-bottles-in-escape-malaysia-police|title=Mas Selamat hid butter, used mineral water bottles in escape: Malaysia police|last=|first=|date=2017-03-26|website=The Straits Times|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180713051346/https://www.straitstimes.com/asia/se-asia/mas-selamat-hid-butter-used-mineral-water-bottles-in-escape-malaysia-police|archive-date=2018-07-13|access-date=2019-10-28}}</ref> He was repatriated back to Singapore on 24 September 2010 and detained indefinitely under the Internal Security Act.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.channelnewsasia.com/stories/afp_singapore/view/1083131/1/.html|title=Mas Selamat repatriated, detained under Singapore's ISA - Channel NewsAsia|last=|first=|date=2010-09-24|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111207031310/http://www.channelnewsasia.com/stories/afp_singapore/view/1083131/1/.html|archive-date=2011-12-07|access-date=2019-10-28}}</ref>\n*6 March 2008: 43-year-old Lim Bock Song had stabbed his drinking partner to death before fleeing to [[Outram Park MRT station]]. Following information by eyewitnesses, two policemen sighted Lim at the station's [[North East MRT line|North East Line]] platform. When confronted, Lim brandished his knife and advanced towards Staff Sergeant (SSG) Azli Othman. Despite SSG Azli drawing his revolver and warning Lim not to advance further, Lim charged towards SSG Azli before firing a shot at his chest. He was pronounced dead at the scene and a coroner's inquiry in 2010 concluded that SSG Azli's action was justified.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/shangri-la-shooting-police-shootings-very-rare-in-singapore|title=Shangri-La shooting: Police shootings very rare in Singapore / March 6, 2008|last=Goy|first=Priscilla|date=2015-06-01|website=The Straits Times|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191022154127/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/shangri-la-shooting-police-shootings-very-rare-in-singapore|archive-date=2019-10-22|access-date=2019-10-22}}</ref>\n*27 July - 23 August 2008: 18-year-old Fabian Adiu Edwin and 25-year-old Ellarry Puling, both Malaysian nationals, committed a series of robberies by targeting six victims between 27 July and 23 August that year. Their vicious robberies led to the death of one of their victims, 35-year-old security guard Loh Ee Hui. On 23 August, Fabian used a wooden stick to smack at Loh's head three times and stomped on his chest, while Ellarry acted as a lookout. Loh died in hospital from skull fractures. On 7 September that year, Fabian was arrested, followed by Ellarry the next day. In September 2011, Fabian was found guilty of murder and given the mandatory death sentence. However, in 2012, the mandatory death penalty law was revised. It reduces the sentence of death, for those convicted of drug trafficking or murder, to life imprisonment if conditions were met.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/murderer-fails-to-escape-the-gallows-6-other-cases-involving-the-revised|title=Murderer fails to escape the gallows: 6 other cases involving the revised death penalty laws|last=Abu Baker|first=Jalelah|date=16 January 2015|website=The Straits Times|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180321155910/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/murderer-fails-to-escape-the-gallows-6-other-cases-involving-the-revised|archive-date=21 March 2018|access-date=24 November 2019}}</ref> This enabled Fabian to undergo a retrial and on 17 July 2013, he became the first person to have his death sentence commuted to life imprisonment under the revised death penalty. His young age and low IQ were factors which spared him from the gallows, although Fabian will also receive 24 strokes of the cane.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://sg.news.yahoo.com/malaysian-escapes-gallows-singapore-law-reform-065353712.html|title=Malaysian escapes gallows after Singapore law reform|last=|first=|date=17 July 2013|website=sg.news.yahoo.com|publisher=AFP News|language=en-SG|via=Yahoo Singapore|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191125145940/https://sg.news.yahoo.com/malaysian-escapes-gallows-singapore-law-reform-065353712.html|archive-date=25 November 2019|access-date=2019-11-24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.asiaone.com/node/28592|title=Murderer escapes death sentence|last=Lum|first=Selina|date=19 July 2013|website=asiaone.com|publisher=The Straits Times|language=en|via=AsiaOne|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191125150111/https://www.asiaone.com/node/28592|archive-date=25 November 2019|access-date=24 November 2019}}</ref> In March 2012, Ellarry was found guilty of robbery with hurt and sentenced to 19 years imprisonment and 24 strokes of the cane.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://i88.photobucket.com/albums/k173/corpuncom/archive3/23949bxm.jpg|title=Man gets 19 years for part in violent robberies|last=Lum|first=Selina|date=25 November 2019|work=The Straits Times|access-date=24 November 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191125145804/https://i88.photobucket.com/albums/k173/corpuncom/archive3/23949bxm.jpg|archive-date=25 November 2019}}</ref>\n*19 September 2008: Famously known as the Yishun triple murder, Chinese national Wang Zhijian murdered his lover Zhang Meng, 41, Zhang's daughter Feng Jianyu, 17, and Zhang's flatmate Yang Jie, 36, in Zhang's house. He also attempted to murder Yang's daughter, Li Meilin, 15.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.asiaone.com/News/AsiaOne%2BNews/Crime/Story/A1Story20080919-88727.html |title=Three dead in Yishun killing frenzy |website=Asiaone |access-date=14 October 2019 |date=19 September 2008}}</ref> At the end of the trial on 30 November 2012, he was sentenced to death for only Yang's murder while successfully raising the defence of diminished responsibility for the murder of the other two.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Phua |first1=Amanda |url=https://www.asiaone.com/News/Latest%2BNews/Singapore/Story/A1Story20121201-387103.html |title=Yishun triple murderer 'tried to silence the witnesses': Judge |website=Asiaone |access-date=14 October 2019 |date=1 December 2012}}</ref> On 30 November 2014, during the cross-appeal between Wang and the prosecution, Wang's appeal against the death sentence was rejected while the prosecution's appeal was allowed, which made Wang guilty of all three murders.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Lum |first1=Selina |url=https://www.asiaone.com/singapore/yishun-murders-death-penalty-stands |title=Yishun murders: Death penalty stands |website=Asiaone |access-date=14 October 2019 |date=1 December 2014}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title = Yishun triple murders: A look back at the case|url = http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/yishun-triple-murders-a-look-back-at-the-case|website = The Straits Times|accessdate = 2015-10-18|last = migration|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20151107054145/http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/yishun-triple-murders-a-look-back-at-the-case|archive-date = 2015-11-07|url-status = live}}</ref>\n\n===2009===\n* April 2009: Chinese national Wang Wenfeng was sentenced to death for murdering taxi driver Yuen Swee Hong. Although he failed in his appeal against his sentence in the Court of Appeal in July 2012, he was re-sentenced to life imprisonment and caning in 2013 after changes to the law took effect that year.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lee|first1=Amanda|title=Man spared the gallows despite killing cabbie|newspaper=Today|location=Singapore|url=http://www.todayonline.com/singapore/man-spared-gallows-despite-killing-cabbie|accessdate=25 January 2015|date=14 November 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160129231901/http://www.todayonline.com/singapore/man-spared-gallows-despite-killing-cabbie|archive-date=2016-01-29|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==2010s==\n\n===2010===\n*29 May 2010: Four East Malaysians from Sarawak: 21-year-old Micheal Garing, 31-year-old Tony Anak Imba, 20-year-old Hairee Landak and 19-year-old Donny Meluda decided to commit a vicious robbery spree.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.asiaone.com/singapore/i-asked-why-he-had-parang|title='I asked why he had parang'|last=ALKHATIB|first=SHAFFIQ|date=19 October 2013|website=AsiaOne|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190407084855/https://www.asiaone.com/singapore/i-asked-why-he-had-parang|archive-date=7 April 2019|access-date=2019-04-07}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/kallang-slashings-jail-for-man-who-fled-singapore-killing-10946450|title=Kallang slashings: Jail for man who fled Singapore after construction worker killing|last=Lam|first=Lydia|date=19 November 2018|website=CNA|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181120125710/https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/kallang-slashings-jail-for-man-who-fled-singapore-killing-10946450|archive-date=20 November 2018|access-date=2019-04-07|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Armed with assorted weapons, ranging from [[Parang (knife)|parang]] to tap handle, they prowled Sims Ave and Kallang area at night. They brutally assaulted three separate male victims without warning and robbed them, with each of them sustaining serious injuries. Then their fourth target, 41-year-old construction worker Shanmuganathan Dillidurai, was kicked off from his bicycle and repeatedly slashed. Dillidurai died at the scene. All, but Meluda were soon arrested as Meluda fled to Malaysia hours after the crimes were committed. On 18 January 2013, Landak was sentenced to 33-year jail and 24 strokes of cane for armed robbery with hurt.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/sarawak-cleaner-jailed-33-years-for-role-in-2010-kallang-slashings|title=Sarawak cleaner jailed 33 years for role in 2010 'Kallang slashings'|last1=Lum|first1=Selina|date=18 January 2013|website=The Straits Times|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191013164100/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/sarawak-cleaner-jailed-33-years-for-role-in-2010-kallang-slashings|archive-date=13 October 2019|access-date=31 October 2019}}</ref> On 20 April 2015, Garing, who was armed with a 58&nbsp;cm parang when he viciously attacked the fourth victim, was found guilty of murder and sentenced to death. Tony was also convicted of murder, however he was spared the gallows and was sentenced to life imprisonment and 24 strokes of cane.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/death-and-life-in-prison-for-two-men-from-sarawak-convicted-of-2010-kallang|title=Death and life in prison for two men from Sarawak convicted of 2010 Kallang slashings|last1=Hoe|first1=Pei Shan|date=20 April 2015|website=The Straits Times|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180207072532/http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/death-and-life-in-prison-for-two-men-from-sarawak-convicted-of-2010-kallang|archive-date=7 February 2018|access-date=31 October 2019}}</ref> The prosecution's appeal to impose the stiffer death sentence on Tony and Garing's appeal to lower his sentence to life imprisonment were both turned down by the Court of Appeal on 27 February 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/kallang-slashings-duos-sentences-upheld-by-appeal-court|title=Kallang slashings: Duo's sentences upheld by appeal court|last=Lum|first=Selina|date=2017-02-27|website=The Straits Times|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190407085105/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/kallang-slashings-duos-sentences-upheld-by-appeal-court|archive-date=7 April 2019|access-date=2019-11-12}}</ref> Meluda was caught on 14 January 2017 when he attempted to enter Sarawak from Kuala Lumpur after being on the run for more than six years,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/final-suspect-in-deadly-2010-kallang-slashings-arrested-in-msia-handed-over|title=Final suspect in deadly 2010 Kallang slashings arrested in Malaysia; handed over to Singapore police|last=|first=|date=18 January 2017|website=The Straits Times|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191013154608/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/final-suspect-in-deadly-2010-kallang-slashings-arrested-in-msia-handed-over|archive-date=13 October 2019|access-date=13 October 2019}}</ref> and was extradited to Singapore on 18 January 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.asiaone.com/singapore/kallang-slashings-appeal-court-defers-judgment-pair-convicted-murder|title=Kallang slashings: Appeal court defers judgment for pair convicted of murder|last=Lum|first=Selina|date=2017-01-26|website=AsiaOne|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191112173023/https://www.asiaone.com/singapore/kallang-slashings-appeal-court-defers-judgment-pair-convicted-murder|archive-date=12 November 2019|access-date=2019-11-12}}</ref> He was initially charged for murder on 20 January 2017,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/fourth-man-charged-with-2010-kallang-murder|title=Fourth man charged with 2010 Kallang murder after 6 years on the run|last1=Alkhatib|first1=Shaffiq Idris|date=20 January 2017|website=The Straits Times|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190407085052/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/fourth-man-charged-with-2010-kallang-murder|archive-date=7 April 2019|access-date=13 October 2019}}</ref> which was eventually reduced to armed robbery with hurt. On 19 November 2018, Meluda was sentenced to 33-year jail and 24 strokes of cane.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/last-member-of-gang-in-kallang-slashings-gets-33-years-jail-caning|title=Last member of gang in Kallang slashings gets 33 years' jail, caning|last=Lum|first=Selina|date=2018-11-20|website=The Straits Times|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181120034818/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/last-member-of-gang-in-kallang-slashings-gets-33-years-jail-caning|archive-date=20 November 2018|access-date=2019-04-07|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Garing was executed on the morning of 22 March 2019 after his appeal for clemency failed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/asia/se-asia/malaysian-convicted-of-murder-executed-in-singapore|title=Malaysian convicted of murder is executed in Singapore|last=|first=|date=2019-03-22|website=The Straits Times|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190327145003/https://www.straitstimes.com/asia/se-asia/malaysian-convicted-of-murder-executed-in-singapore|archive-date=27 March 2019|access-date=2019-04-07|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/kallang-slashings-malaysian-micheal-garing-2010-murder-executed-11370142|title=Kallang slashings: Malaysian convicted of 'savage, merciless' 2010 murder is executed|last=|first=|date=22 March 2019|website=CNA|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191113062246/https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/kallang-slashings-malaysian-micheal-garing-2010-murder-executed-11370142?cid=FBcna|archive-date=13 November 2019|access-date=13 November 2019}}</ref>\n*3 July 2010: Calvin Tan Jian Wei, Edwin Tan Jian An and Ho Boon Sheng intoxicated an 18-year-old pub waitress and raped her in a hotel in Jiak Chuan Road on the night of 3\u20134 July 2010. They were arrested in the morning of 4 July and sentenced in 2015 to imprisonment and caning.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lim|first1=Yvonne|title=Brothers jailed for assisting in rape of pub waitress|url=http://www.todayonline.com/singapore/brothers-jailed-assisting-rape-pub-waitress|accessdate=13 January 2015|publisher=MediaCorp Press Ltd|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150111215845/http://www.todayonline.com/singapore/brothers-jailed-assisting-rape-pub-waitress|archive-date=2015-01-11|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*30 October 2010: [[Republic Polytechnic]] student, Darren Ng, was involved in a 'staring' incident with a group of teenage gang members. He was then brutally attacked by them at [[NTUC Downtown East|Downtown East]] mall in [[Pasir Ris]] and later died in hospital. A total of 12 youths were charged for rioting and culpable homicide. They were sentenced to between 3 and 12 years jail, with all receiving caning of between 3 and 12 strokes.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://i88.photobucket.com/albums/k173/corpuncom/archive3/23914bxm.jpg|title=Jailed for Downtown east fight (First person convicted)|last=Chong|first=Elena|date=2012-03-07|work=The Straits Times|access-date=2019-10-13|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191013114220/https://i88.photobucket.com/albums/k173/corpuncom/archive3/23914bxm.jpg|archive-date=13 October 2019|via=https://www.corpun.com/}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://i88.photobucket.com/albums/k173/corpuncom/archive3/23970bxm.jpg|title=Downtown East case: 2nd youth jailed, ordered to be caned|last=Huang|first=Claire|date=2012-05-05|work=TODAY (Singapore)|access-date=2019-10-13|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191013114222/https://i88.photobucket.com/albums/k173/corpuncom/archive3/23970bxm.jpg|archive-date=13 October 2019|via=https://www.corpun.com/}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://i88.photobucket.com/albums/k173/corpuncom/archive3/24068axm.jpg|title=Four more youths charged for Downtown East riot|last=|first=|date=2012-07-19|work=TODAY (Singapore)|access-date=2019-10-13|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191013114214/https://i88.photobucket.com/albums/k173/corpuncom/archive3/24068axm.jpg|archive-date=13 October 2019|via=https://www.corpun.com/}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://i88.photobucket.com/albums/k173/corpuncom/archive3/24106bxm.jpg|title=Five youths jailed, caned over Downtown East murder|last=Lum|first=Selina|date=2012-09-08|work=The Straits Times|access-date=2019-10-13|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191013114219/https://i88.photobucket.com/albums/k173/corpuncom/archive3/24106bxm.jpg|archive-date=13 October 2019|via=https://www.corpun.com/}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://i88.photobucket.com/albums/k173/corpuncom/archive3/24125bxm.jpg|title=Youth involved in gang clash gets jail, caning (Last person convicted)|last=Singh|first=Khushwant|date=2012-09-25|work=The Straits Times|access-date=2019-10-13|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191013114221/https://i88.photobucket.com/albums/k173/corpuncom/archive3/24125bxm.jpg|archive-date=13 October 2019|via=https://www.corpun.com/}}</ref>\n\n===2011===\n*16 May 2011: The dead body of Ruliyawati, an Indonesian domestic worker, was discovered in the rooftop water tank of a flat in [[Woodlands, Singapore|Woodlands]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Indonesian maid's body found in Woodlands rooftop water tank|url=http://news.asiaone.com/News/AsiaOne+News/Singapore/Story/A1Story20110516-279169.html|accessdate=27 December 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150104173405/http://news.asiaone.com/News/AsiaOne+News/Singapore/Story/A1Story20110516-279169.html|archive-date=2015-01-04|url-status=live}}</ref> A coroner's inquest found that she had drowned herself but the two wounds on her back were caused by her boyfriend, Bangladeshi national Mohammed Repon Mostafa. Repon, who was initially accused of her death, was granted a discharge not amounting to an acquittal in 2013.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Jalelah Abu Baker|title=Water tank death: Maid drowned but two wounds were caused by boyfriend|newspaper=The Straits Times|url=http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/water-tank-death-maid-drowned-but-two-wounds-were-caused-by-boyfriend|accessdate=23 January 2016|date=May 2, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160208003110/http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/water-tank-death-maid-drowned-but-two-wounds-were-caused-by-boyfriend|archive-date=2016-02-08|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===2012===\n*28 May 2012: The police found the body of Mallika Jesudasan, 56, with neck injuries in a flat in [[Bukit Batok]]. Jesudasan was said to have been killed in a bedroom by her 31-year-old son, Sujay Solomon Sutherson, believed to be mentally ill.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Suspect in Bukit Batok murder charged|url = http://news.asiaone.com/News/Latest+News/Singapore/Story/A1Story20120529-349002.html|website = news.asiaone.com|accessdate = 2015-10-27|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160217054550/http://news.asiaone.com/News/Latest+News/Singapore/Story/A1Story20120529-349002.html|archive-date = 2016-02-17|url-status = live}}</ref> Sujay was convicted of culpable homicide not amounting to murder on 15 September 2015 and sentenced to life imprisonment.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Siau|first1=Ming En|title=Man who slit his mum's throat sentenced to life imprisonment|url=http://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/cy-man-who-slit-mum-s/2129376.html|accessdate=23 January 2016|agency=Channel News Asia|date=16 September 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160131104058/http://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/cy-man-who-slit-mum-s/2129376.html|archive-date=2016-01-31|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===2013===\n*10 July 2013: Staff Sergeant Iskandar bin Rahmat murdered 67-year-old Tan Boon Sin and his 42-year-old son Tan Chee Heong. The body of the elder Tan was found in his home at Hillside Drive in Kovan while the body of his son was dragged under a car for 1&nbsp;km from the home before being dislodged outside [[Kovan MRT station]].<ref>{{Cite web|title = 'I was fearing for my life': Kovan double murders accused claims self-defence|url = http://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/i-was-fearing-for-my-life/2228116.html|accessdate = 2015-12-02|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20151205162528/http://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/i-was-fearing-for-my-life/2228116.html|archive-date = 2015-12-05|url-status = live}}</ref> Justice [[Tay Yong Kwang]] of the [[High Court of Singapore|High Court]] found Iskandar guilty of murder on 4 December 2015 and sentenced him to death.<ref>{{cite web|title=Public Prosecutor v Iskandar bin Rahmat [2015] SGHC 310|url=http://www.singaporelawwatch.sg/slw/attachments/74322/%5B2015%5D%20SGHC%20310.pdf|website=Singapore Law Watch|accessdate=23 January 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160129084708/http://www.singaporelawwatch.sg/slw/attachments/74322/%5B2015%5D%20SGHC%20310.pdf|archive-date=2016-01-29|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*16 November 2013: Tuti Aeliyah, a 28-year-old Indonesian domestic helper, stabbed and strangled her employer's daughter, 16-year-old Shameera Basha Noor Basha, to death.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Domestic helper charged with murder for allegedly stabbing employer's daughter to death|url = http://www.todayonline.com/singapore/domestic-helper-charged-murder-allegedly-stabbing-employers-daughter-death|website = TODAYonline|accessdate = 2015-10-27|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160129231911/http://www.todayonline.com/singapore/domestic-helper-charged-murder-allegedly-stabbing-employers-daughter-death|archive-date = 2016-01-29|url-status = live}}</ref> She was initially charged with murder, but the charge was reduced to culpable homicide after she was diagnosed to be suffering from severe depression with psychotic symptoms. The High Court found her guilty and sentenced her to 12 years imprisonment in May 2015.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lum|first1=Selina|title=Maid jailed 12 years for strangling 16-year-old girl with pinafore|newspaper=The Straits Times|url=http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/maid-jailed-12-years-for-strangling-16-year-old-girl-with-pinafore|accessdate=23 January 2016|date=25 May 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160208003023/http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/maid-jailed-12-years-for-strangling-16-year-old-girl-with-pinafore|archive-date=2016-02-08|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*25 November 2013: 44-year-old Lim Ann Nee allegedly drowned her 17-month-old son, Emilien Lacroix, in the sea off [[East Coast Park]] and was charged with murder. She was found to be suffering from acute transient psychotic disorder and had her charge reduced to culpable homicide in 2014. On 24 March 2015, she was given a discharge not amounting to an acquittal.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Chong|first1=Elena|title=Woman given a discharge over son's death as she was of unsound mind then|newspaper=The Straits Times|url=http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/woman-given-a-discharge-over-sons-death-as-she-was-of-unsound-mind-then|accessdate=23 January 2016|date=24 March 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160208002959/http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/woman-given-a-discharge-over-sons-death-as-she-was-of-unsound-mind-then|archive-date=2016-02-08|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*8 December 2013: Known as the [[2013 Little India riot|Little India riot]], it was Singapore's first riot since [[1969 race riots of Singapore|1969]]. About 400 men rioted in [[Little India, Singapore|Little India]] after an earlier fatal bus accident resulted in a fatality. 28 men were arrested at the scene, of whom four were released. 52 Indian nationals and one Bangladeshi national were repatriated.\n*12 December 2013: 33-year-old Jasvinder Kaur's decapitated body was found in Whampoa River. The body was topless and missing two arms, only dressed in a pair of black pants. 25-year-old forklift driver Gursharan Singh, was charged with murder, while the other suspect, 33-year-old Harvinder Singh, Kaur's husband, is on the run and on [[Interpol]]'s wanted list.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Headless body murder an organised crime of passion: Coroner's report|url = http://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/headless-body-murder-an/2013196.html|website = Channel NewsAsia|accessdate = 2015-10-27|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20151102061417/http://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/headless-body-murder-an/2013196.html|archive-date = 2015-11-02|url-status = live}}</ref> In July 2015, a coroner's court found that Kaur had been murdered by Harvinder Singh. In April 2015, Gursharan Singh was sentenced to 30 months imprisonment for assisting Harvinder Singh in disposing Kaur's body and for failing to make a police report.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Ho|first1=Olivia|title=Headless woman killed by hubby: Court|newspaper=The Straits Times|url=http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/headless-woman-killed-by-hubby-court|accessdate=23 January 2016|date=29 July 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160208001225/http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/headless-woman-killed-by-hubby-court|archive-date=2016-02-08|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*28-29 December: 37-year-old Dexmon Chua Yizhi was murdered in a van, with his body found in Lim Chu Kang on 1 January 2014. 2 suspects, 53-year-old Chia Kee Chen and 64-year-old Chua Leong Aik were charged with murder, with the third suspect, Djatmiko Febri Irwansyah (late 20s), having fled Singapore.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Chong |first1=Elena |title=Man charged with murder at Choa Chu Kang multi-storey carpark |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/man-charged-with-murder-at-choa-chu-kang-multi-storey-carpark |accessdate=15 December 2019 |publisher=The Straits Times |date=2 January 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Lim |first1=Yan Liang |title=Choa Chu Kang Murder: Second man charged and remanded for further investigations |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/choa-chu-kang-murder-second-man-charged-and-remanded-for-further-investigations |accessdate=14 July 2019 |publisher=The Straits Times |date=10 January 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Lim Chu Kang murder: Police seek Indonesian man |url=https://www.todayonline.com/singapore/lim-chu-kang-murder-police-seek-indonesian-man |accessdate=14 July 2019 |agency=Todayonline |date=3 January 2014}}</ref> In January 2016, Chua was jailed for five years for his role in the murder.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Law |first1=Elizabeth |title=Revenge attack so savage it left bloodstains on van's ceiling |url=https://www.tnp.sg/news/singapore/revenge-attack-so-savage-it-left-bloodstains-vans-ceiling |accessdate=14 July 2019 |publisher=The New Paper |date=9 January 2016}}</ref> In August 2017, Chia was sentenced to life in jail.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Chelvan |first1=Vanessa Paige |title=Man convicted of murder for beating wife\u2019s former lover to death |url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/man-convicted-of-murder-for-beating-wife-s-former-lover-to-death-7574916 |accessdate=14 July 2019 |publisher=The Straits Times |date=17 January 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Ng |first1=Kelly |title=Businessman who killed wife's ex-lover spared the gallows, jailed for life |url=https://www.todayonline.com/singapore/businessman-who-killed-wifes-ex-lover-jailed-life |accessdate=14 July 2019 |publisher=Todayonline |date=4 August 2017}}</ref> However, the prosecution appealed, which was allowed by the apex court. It overturned the life sentence, sentencing Chia to death.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Lum |first1=Selina |title=Businessman who murdered wife's ex-lover sentenced to death upon prosecution's appeal |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/apex-court-hands-down-death-penalty-to-businessman-for-murdering-wifes-ex |accessdate=14 July 2019 |publisher=The Straits Times |date=27 June 2018}}</ref> Djatmiko Febri Irwansyah is still on the run.\n\n===2014===\n*8 January 2014: In the first such case of kidnapping after a decade of hiatus, 41-year-old Lee Sze Yong and 50-year-old Heng Chen Boon kidnapped 79-year-old Ng Lye Poh along Hougang Ave 8. One of Mdm Ng's son is Mr Lim Hock Chee, who is the chief executive officer of [[Sheng Siong]], a well-known supermarket chain in Singapore. That morning, Lee tricked Mdm Ng to get into a car before blindfolding her. He then demanded from Mr Lim a ransom of S$20 million. The sum was eventually reduced to S$2 million and Mdm Ng was released at Seletar West Camp area at around midnight. Both Lee and Heng were arrested shortly after Mdm Ng's release. The S$2 million ransom was fully recovered at Sembawang park, the place where the kidnappers ordered Lim to drop the ransom.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.asiaone.com/singapore/sheng-siong-kidnap-elderly-victim-was-led-car-and-later-blindfolded|title=Sheng Siong kidnap: Elderly victim was led to car and later blindfolded|last=Lum|first=Selina|date=2016-09-02|website=AsiaOne|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191013152420/https://www.asiaone.com/singapore/sheng-siong-kidnap-elderly-victim-was-led-car-and-later-blindfolded|archive-date=2019-10-13|access-date=2019-10-13}}</ref> Heng, who was originally charged with kidnapping, had his charge reduced. In May 2015, he pleaded guilty to abetting Lee to abduct Ng, and was sentenced to three years imprisonment. In November 2016, Lee was charged with kidnapping and sentenced to life imprisonment and 3 strokes of cane.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Alkatib|first1=Shaffiq|title=Lawyers of Sheng Siong kidnapping accomplice say he was too trusting of friend he helped|url=http://news.asiaone.com/news/singapore/lawyers-sheng-siong-kidnapping-accomplice-say-he-was-too-trusting-friend-he-helped|website=Asia One|accessdate=23 January 2016|date=14 May 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160217054513/http://news.asiaone.com/news/singapore/lawyers-sheng-siong-kidnapping-accomplice-say-he-was-too-trusting-friend-he-helped|archive-date=2016-02-17|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/sheng-siong-kidnapping-life-imprisonment-caning-for-kidnapper-7652602|title=Sheng Siong kidnapping: Life imprisonment, caning for kidnapper|last=Paige Chelvan|first=Vanessa|date=2019-10-13|website=CNA|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191013152749/https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/sheng-siong-kidnapping-life-imprisonment-caning-for-kidnapper-7652602|archive-date=2019-10-13|access-date=2019-10-13}}</ref>\n*4 June 2014: 51-year-old Andrea Tay Su Lin killed her 75-year-old mother, Rosaline Lim, at their flat in [[Ang Mo Kio]]. She then committed suicide by throwing herself out from the window. Tay had a poor relationship with her mother, whom she blamed for her grandmother's death.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Chong|first1=Elena|title=Ang Mo Kio double death: Woman killed mum and took her own life, says coroner|newspaper=The Straits Times|url=http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/ang-mo-kio-double-death-woman-killed-mum-and-took-her-own-life-says-coroner|accessdate=23 January 2016|date=3 December 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160208003048/http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/ang-mo-kio-double-death-woman-killed-mum-and-took-her-own-life-says-coroner|archive-date=2016-02-08|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*11 June 2014: A body without legs was found in a luggage at Syed Alwi Road, [[Little India, Singapore|Little India]]. Two Pakistani men were arrested as suspects in the case.<ref>{{cite news|title=Grisly legless body find: Two Pakistanis held for murder|url=http://www.todayonline.com/singapore/grisly-legless-body-find-two-pakistanis-held-murder|accessdate=27 December 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140617093704/http://www.todayonline.com/singapore/grisly-legless-body-find-two-pakistanis-held-murder|archive-date=2014-06-17|url-status=live}}</ref> On 17 February 2016, they were found guilty of murder and sentenced to death.<ref>{{cite news|title=Legless body in suitcase: Duo found guilty, to hang for murder|newspaper=The Straits Times|url=http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/legless-body-in-suitcase-duo-found-guilty-to-hang-for-murder?xtor=CS1-10#link_time=1487299045|accessdate=18 February 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181002051947/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/legless-body-in-suitcase-duo-found-guilty-to-hang-for-murder?xtor=CS1-10#link_time=1487299045|archive-date=2 October 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n*21 August 2014: 80-year-old Char Chin Fah was accused of murdering his daughter-in-law, 54-year-old Ong Guat Leng, in their home in [[Tampines]]. Chin was remanded at Complex Medical Centre in [[Changi]] for psychiatric assessment in August 2014. He was sentenced to 8 years in jail in 2016.<ref>{{cite news|last=Poh|first=Ian|title=Tampines murder case: 80-year-old accused remanded for psychiatric evaluation|newspaper=The Straits Times|url=http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/tampines-murder-case-80-year-old-accused-remanded-for-psychiatric-evaluation|accessdate=23 January 2016|date=27 August 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160208003011/http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/tampines-murder-case-80-year-old-accused-remanded-for-psychiatric-evaluation|archive-date=2016-02-08|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*20 November 2014: 40-year-old Jackson Lim Hou Peng was accused of murdering a Vietnamese woman, 32-year-old Tran Cam Ny, in a flat in [[Ang Mo Kio]]. On 19 December 2014, Lim was found to be \"not of unsound mind\" after an extended period of psychiatric evaluation and was due to be tried in court.<ref>{{cite news|last=Lim|first=Yvonne|title=Man accused of murdering Vietnamese woman fit to plead in court|newspaper=Today|url=http://www.todayonline.com/singapore/man-accused-murdering-vietnamese-woman-fit-plead-court|accessdate=23 January 2016|date=19 December 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160130060213/http://www.todayonline.com/singapore/man-accused-murdering-vietnamese-woman-fit-plead-court|archive-date=2016-01-30|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*29 November 2014 - 9 January 2015: A 31-year-old man raped his 14-year-old daughter multiple times over a period of 3 months in their family flat at Punggol. The case came to light after a police report was filed when her boyfriend at that time arranged her to see their school counsellor. On 14 November 2018, the man was sentenced to 26-year jail and 24 strokes of cane.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/technician-found-guilty-of-raping-teenage-daughter|title=Technician found guilty of raping teenage daughter|last=hermesauto|date=2018-10-15|website=The Straits Times|language=en|access-date=2019-04-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181103102518/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/technician-found-guilty-of-raping-teenage-daughter|archive-date=3 November 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/man-who-raped-teenage-daughter-gets-26-years-jail-24-strokes|title=Man who raped teenage daughter gets 26 years' jail, 24 strokes|last=hermesauto|date=2018-11-14|website=The Straits Times|language=en|access-date=2019-04-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190218225314/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/man-who-raped-teenage-daughter-gets-26-years-jail-24-strokes|archive-date=18 February 2019|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n*17 December 2014: Zheng Xianghua, a Chinese national, stabbed himself after allegedly killing Wang Xueyan, also a Chinese national, in a flat in [[Tampines]]. He was charged with murder on 20 December 2014,<ref>{{Cite web|title=Man charged in Tampines murder case|url=http://news.asiaone.com/news/crime/man-charged-tampines-murder-case|website=Asia One|accessdate=23 January 2016|date=21 December 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160217063137/http://news.asiaone.com/news/crime/man-charged-tampines-murder-case|archive-date=2016-02-17|url-status=live}}</ref> but the charge was subsequently reduced to culpable homicide not amounting to murder, and Zheng was sentenced to 9 years' imprisonment on 11 April 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Truck driver jailed 9 years for killing wife he suspected of having affair|url=http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/truck-driver-jailed-9-years-for-killing-wife-he-suspected-of-having-affair|website=The Straits Times|accessdate=26 May 2016|date=11 April 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160416225430/http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/truck-driver-jailed-9-years-for-killing-wife-he-suspected-of-having-affair|archive-date=2016-04-16|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===2015===\n* 13 April 2015: Annie Ee Yu Lian, a 26-year-old waitress, died from acute fat [[embolism]] as a result of systematic abuse from her flatmates in a flat at Woodlands for 8 months. The couple, Tan Hui Zhen and her husband Pua Hak Chuan, were charged with voluntarily causing grievous hurt with a dangerous weapon resulting in Ee's death and were sentence to 16.5 years and 14 years jail respectively on 1 December 2017. In addition, Pua was given 14 strokes of the cane.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sg.news.yahoo.com/couple-admits-causing-flatmates-death-systematic-abuse-145204129.html|title=Couple admit to causing flatmate\u2019s death through \u2018systematic\u2019 abuse|access-date=2018-01-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180112101217/https://sg.news.yahoo.com/couple-admits-causing-flatmates-death-systematic-abuse-145204129.html|archive-date=2018-01-12|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*1 June 2015: Known as the [[Shooting of Taufik Zahar|Shangri-La shooting]], a car driven by 34-year-old Mohamad Taufik Zahar took an incorrect turn and ended up at a high security checkpoint. Fearing arrest and drugs being uncovered, he was told to speed off by one of his passengers. [[Gurkha Contingent|Gurkha officers]] neutralised the threat by firing five shots. One of the bullets shot Taufik to death before the car came to a halt.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/shangri-la-shooting-car-took-wrong-turn-into-security-zone|title=Shangri-La shooting: Car took wrong turn into security zone|last=Hussain|first=Amir|date=2016-01-27|website=The Straits Times|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190210221156/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/shangri-la-shooting-car-took-wrong-turn-into-security-zone|archive-date=2019-02-10|access-date=2019-10-22}}</ref> In 2016, a coroner's inquiry ruled Taufik's death as 'a lawful killing'.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/drivers-death-in-shangrila-la-shooting-case-ruled-a-lawful-killing|title=Driver's death in Shangri-La shooting case ruled 'a lawful killing'|last=Pang|first=Xue Qiang|date=2016-04-22|website=The Straits Times|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190704133939/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/drivers-death-in-shangrila-la-shooting-case-ruled-a-lawful-killing|archive-date=2019-07-04|access-date=2019-10-22}}</ref>\n*20 June 2015: Known as the [[Khoo Teck Puat Hospital]] (KTPH) shooting, it is another rare case involving a policeman's revolver being snatched. 24-year-old Muhammad Iskandar Sa\u2019at was arrested on 19 June 2015 for theft of motor vehicle and was escorted to KTPH by two policemen when he claimed to have chest pain. His grip restraints were loosened on his left arm and right wrist for blood drawing and minimising discomfort respectively. While one of the policeman left the examination room to break fast, 31-year-old Staff Sergeant (SSG) Muhammad Sadli Razali was on his mobile phone. Iskandar out of a sudden assaulted SSG Sadli and attempted to escape. As SSG Sadli held on to his legs, Iskandar snatched SSG Sadli's revolver. Even when Iskandar was pinned to the ground, he fired three shots at SSG Sadli. Iskandar was eventually subdued. SSG Sadli suffered gunshot wounds on his left thumb and right root. Iskandar was charged on 22 June 2015 for unlawful discharge of firearms<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/man-charged-over-unlawful-discharge-of-a-firearm-in-khoo-teck-puat-hospital|title=Man charged over unlawful discharge of a firearm in Khoo Teck Puat hospital shooting|last=Rei|first=Kurohi|date=2015-06-22|website=The Straits Times|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190703025426/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/man-charged-over-unlawful-discharge-of-a-firearm-in-khoo-teck-puat-hospital|archive-date=3 July 2019|access-date=2019-11-12}}</ref> and on 19 March 2018, Iskandar was sentenced to life imprisonment and 18 strokes of the cane.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/man-who-shot-police-officer-gets-life-term-in-jail-caning|title=Man who snatched police officer's revolver and fired three shots gets life term in jail, caning|last=K.C.|first=Vijayan|date=2018-03-20|website=The Straits Times|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190703025407/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/man-who-shot-police-officer-gets-life-term-in-jail-caning|archive-date=3 July 2019|access-date=2019-11-12}}</ref>\n*5 October 2015: Belgian national Philippe Graffart allegedly murdered his five-year-old son, Keryan Graffart, at their D'Leedon condominium along Farrer Road.<ref>{{cite news|title=Singapore police extend investigation of Belgian charged with son's murder|url=http://www.bangkokpost.com/news/asean/782849/singapore-police-extend-investigation-of-belgian-charged-with-son-murder|accessdate=2 December 2015|agency=AFP}}</ref> The murder charge was later reduced to culpable homicide, and found that he suffered from major depressive disorder during a custody battle. On 1 August, Philippe pleaded guilty and was sentenced to five years jail on 22 August 2016.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Chelvan |first1=Vanessa Paige |title=D'Leedon murder: Belgian expat admits to killing 5-year-old son |url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/d-leedon-murder-belgian-expat-admits-to-killing-5-year-old-son-7881934 |accessdate=14 July 2019 |publisher=CNA |date=1 August 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Belgian expat jailed for 5 years for killing son |url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/belgian-expat-jailed-for-5-years-for-killing-son-7863634 |accessdate=14 July 2019 |publisher=CNA |date=22 August 2016}}</ref>\n*22 November 2015: 26-year-old Neo Chun Zheng murdered former [[Scoot]] air stewardess, 23-year-old Soh Yuan Lin, by stabbing her in the neck with a knife outside his HDB flat in [[Boon Lay]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lee|first1=Pearl|title=Man charged with murder of former air stewardess|url=http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/man-charged-with-murder-of-former-air-stewardess|accessdate=3 December 2015|publisher=Straits Times|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151202050005/http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/man-charged-with-murder-of-former-air-stewardess|archive-date=2015-12-02|url-status=live}}</ref> Neo pleaded guilty to culpable homicide and was sentenced to 13 years jail on 12 November 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/boon-lay-killing-possessive-man-gets-13-years-jail-for-stabbing-former-air|title=Boon Lay killing: Possessive man gets 13 years' jail for stabbing former air stewardess|last=hermesauto|date=2018-11-12|website=The Straits Times|language=en|access-date=2019-04-05|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190211132000/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/boon-lay-killing-possessive-man-gets-13-years-jail-for-stabbing-former-air|archive-date=11 February 2019|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n*30 December 2015: 64-year-old general practitioner Wee Teong Boo sexually assaulted a 23-year-old student in his clinic when she went for a consultation. Initially charged with rape, the courts found him guilty of sexual assault by penetration, based on his admission that he inserted his ungloved finger, lubricated with his saliva into her vagina and that he had erectile dysfunction. As the victim was molested by Wee a month prior to the incident as well, Wee was also convicted of molestation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tnp.sg/news/singapore/doctor-cleared-rape-guilty-sexual-assault|title=Doctor cleared of rape but guilty of sexual assault|last=Lum|first=Selina|last2=|first2=|date=2019-02-26|website=The New Paper|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190226060408/https://www.tnp.sg/news/singapore/doctor-cleared-rape-guilty-sexual-assault|archive-date=2019-02-26|access-date=2019-10-22}}</ref> On 27 February 2019, Wee was sentenced to 10-year jail.<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/doctor-gets-10-years-jail-for-sexually-assaulting-and-molesting-patient-in|title=Doctor gets 10 years' jail for sexually assaulting and molesting patient in his clinic|last=Lum|first=Selina|date=2019-02-27|website=The Straits Times|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190309071048/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/doctor-gets-10-years-jail-for-sexually-assaulting-and-molesting-patient-in|archive-date=9 March 2019|access-date=2019-04-07|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===2016===\n*14 February 2016: 47-year-old Singaporean Loh Suan Lit murdered 57-year old Teck Whye Chin Long Kong Temple helper Tan Poh Huat.<ref>{{cite news|title=47-year-old Singaporean charged with Teck Whye temple murder|url=http://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/video/47-year-old-singaporean/2552822.html|accessdate=7 March 2016|publisher=CNA|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160307221409/http://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/video/47-year-old-singaporean/2552822.html|archive-date=2016-03-07|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Man charged with Teck Whye temple murder brought to various crime scenes|url=http://razor.tv/section/77922/vertical.html?movideo_p=77922&movideo_m=1467786|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160307163421/http://razor.tv/section/77922/vertical.html?movideo_p=77922&movideo_m=1467786|url-status=dead|archive-date=7 March 2016|publisher=The New Paper|accessdate=7 March 2016}}</ref> The charge was later reduced to a count of culpable homicide in addition to an unrelated charge for burgling a food stall. Loh was sentenced to a total of 14 years jail and six strokes of the cane on 15 January 2018.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Lum |first1=Selina |title=Jobless man who killed temple helper in aborted burglary gets 14 years' jail, caning |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/jobless-man-who-killed-temple-helper-in-aborted-burglary-gets-14-years-jail |accessdate=14 July 2019 |publisher=The Straits Times |date=15 January 2018}}</ref>\n*25 February 2016: 50-year-old coffee-shop assistant Khor Tzoong Meng murdered 38-year-old Ang Kim Keat at Blk 23 [[Hougang]] Avenue 3.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Ong|first1=Justin|title=Coffeeshop assistant charged for Hougang murder|url=http://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/coffeeshop-assistant/2550538.html|accessdate=7 March 2016|publisher=CNA|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160307164337/http://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/coffeeshop-assistant/2550538.html|archive-date=2016-03-07|url-status=live}}</ref> The murder charge was later reduced to culpable homicide. Khor pleaded guilty and was sentenced to eight years jail on 31 July 2017.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Lum |first1=Selina |title=Coffeeshop assistant jailed 8 years for fatal slashing of patron over self-service policy |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/coffeeshop-assistant-jailed-8-years-for-fatal-slashing-of-patron-over-self |accessdate=14 July 2019 |publisher=The Straits Times |date=31 July 2017}}</ref> \n*13 March 2016: 68-year-old Kong Peng Yee murdered his wife 63-year-old Wong Chik Yeok at [[Compassvale]] Crescent.<ref>{{cite news|title=Man charged with wife's murder|url=http://news.asiaone.com/news/crime/man-charged-wifes-murder|accessdate=16 March 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160317072512/http://news.asiaone.com/news/crime/man-charged-wifes-murder|archive-date=2016-03-17|url-status=live}}</ref> The murder charge was reduced to culpable homicide as he suffered from a psychotic episode during the time of crime. On 16 October 2017, Kong was sentenced to two years jail.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Chelvan |first1=Vanessa Paige |title=69-year-old retiree pleads guilty to stabbing wife to death |url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/69-year-old-retiree-pleads-guilty-to-stabbing-wife-to-death-9197928 |accessdate=14 July 2019 |publisher=CNA |date=8 September 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Lum |first1=Selina |title=Judge gives man shortest sentence of 2 years\u2019 jail for killing wife |url=https://www.tnp.sg/news/singapore/judge-gives-man-shortest-sentence-2-years-jail-killing-wife |accessdate=14 July 2019 |publisher=The New Paper |date=17 October 2017}}</ref> The case was appealed to the Court of Appeal, which increased the sentence to six years jail on 27 June 2018.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Lum |first1=Selina |title=Court of Appeal decides on more jail time for man who killed wife in psychotic episode |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/court-of-appeal-decides-on-more-jail-time-for-man-who-killed-wife-in |accessdate=14 July 2019 |publisher=The Straits Times |date=27 June 2018}}</ref>\n*21 March 2016: 47-year-old Boh Soon Ho was charged on 7 April 2016<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/man-to-be-charged-with-murder-of-woman-in-circuit-road-flat|title=Man, 47, charged with murder of woman in Circuit Road flat|last=Hussain|first=Amir|date=2016-04-07|website=The Straits Times|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190207060624/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/man-to-be-charged-with-murder-of-woman-in-circuit-road-flat|archive-date=2019-02-07|access-date=2019-10-22}}</ref> for strangling his 28-year-old girlfriend, Chinese national Zhang Huaxiang to death. He fled to Malaysia before he was arrested by the Royal Malaysian Police and brought back to Singapore to face trial, which is ongoing.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/circuit-road-murder-trial-accused-said-he-spent-money-on-nurse-but-got|title=Circuit Road murder trial: Accused said he spent money on nurse but got nothing|last=Lum|first=Selina|date=2019-09-19|website=The Straits Times|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190921163611/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/circuit-road-murder-trial-accused-said-he-spent-money-on-nurse-but-got|archive-date=2019-09-21|access-date=2019-10-22}}</ref>\n*8 May 2016: 30-year-old maid Maryani Usman Utar punched and straggled one-year-old Richelle Teo Yan Jia over what she perceived as poor treatment by her employers. Charged with culpable homicide not amounting to murder, Maryani was sentenced to 7-year jail in 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/indonesian-maid-charged-over-death-of-1-year-old-girl-in-simei-flat|title=Indonesian maid charged over death of 1-year-old girl in Simei flat|last=hermesauto|date=2016-05-10|website=The Straits Times|language=en|access-date=2019-04-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190213105008/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/indonesian-maid-charged-over-death-of-1-year-old-girl-in-simei-flat|archive-date=13 February 2019|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/maid-who-claimed-she-was-stressed-jailed-seven-years-for-causing-toddlers|title=Maid who claimed she was stressed jailed seven years for causing toddler's death|last=hermesauto|date=2018-11-22|website=The Straits Times|language=en|access-date=2019-04-07}}</ref>\n*{{Anchor|David Roach}}7 July 2016: In the rare case of a bank robbery in recent years, 27-year-old Canadian David James Roach robbed a [[Standard Chartered]] bank in Holland Village. He presented a note to the bank teller stating that he had a weapon before he making off with S$30,000. Roach immediately fled to Bangkok after the robbery. The Thai authorities arrested Roach, and subsequently charged him of violating their foreign exchange act and for money laundering. Roach was given a 14-month sentence in jail and the money was seized by the Thai authorities.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.chiangraitimes.com/singapore-bank-robber-david-james-roach-gets-11-months-for-violating-thailands-currency-regulations.html|title=Singapore Bank Robber David James Roach Gets 11 Months for Violating Thailand\u2019s Currency Regulations \u2013 CTN News \u2013 Chiang Rai Times|website=www.chiangraitimes.com|access-date=2019-04-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180219061508/http://www.chiangraitimes.com/singapore-bank-robber-david-james-roach-gets-11-months-for-violating-thailands-currency-regulations.html|archive-date=19 February 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Singapore was unsuccessful at requesting an extradition from the Thai authorities as the two countries have no relevant treaty. Upon his release on 11 January 2018, Roach was deported to Canada via London. Singapore requested Britain the extradition of Roach on the same day, which led to Roach being detained while in transit at London.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.todayonline.com/singapore/stanchart-robbery-suspect-detained-uk-spore-seeking-extradition|title=StanChart bank robbery suspect detained in UK; S\u2019pore seeking extradition|website=TODAYonline|access-date=2019-04-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180321045733/http://www.todayonline.com/singapore/stanchart-robbery-suspect-detained-uk-spore-seeking-extradition|archive-date=21 March 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> To secure the extradition, Singapore authorities assured the British authorities that Roach would not be caned if he is found guilty.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.todayonline.com/singapore/spore-agrees-not-cane-alleged-stanchart-robber-if-uk-extradites-him|title=S'pore agrees not to cane alleged StanChart robber if UK extradites him|website=TODAYonline|access-date=2019-04-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180327101900/http://www.todayonline.com/singapore/spore-agrees-not-cane-alleged-stanchart-robber-if-uk-extradites-him|archive-date=27 March 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> A London court of law found that the extradition request satisfied all requirements on 29 August 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.todayonline.com/singapore/uk-court-approves-singapores-request-extradite-stanchart-robbery-suspect|title=UK court approves Singapore\u2019s request to extradite StanChart robbery suspect|website=TODAYonline|access-date=2019-04-07}}</ref> On 23 October 2018, Britain's Secretary of State ordered the extradition. However, Roach filed an appeal against the extradition order on 31 October 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/stanchart-robbery-suspect-files-appeal-against-extradition-from-uk-to|title=StanChart robbery suspect files appeal against extradition from UK to Singapore|last=Tan|first=Tam Mei|date=2018-11-08|website=The Straits Times|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190208100156/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/stanchart-robbery-suspect-files-appeal-against-extradition-from-uk-to|archive-date=8 February 2019|access-date=2019-04-07|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The appeal was dismissed in February 2020,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thechronicleherald.ca/news/provincial/cape-breton-man-to-be-extradited-to-singapore-to-face-charges-related-to-a-bank-robbery-409880/|title=Cape Breton man to be extradited to Singapore to face charges related to a bank robbery {{!}} The Chronicle Herald|last=Montgomery|first=Sharon|website=www.thechronicleherald.ca|language=en|access-date=2020-03-17}}</ref> and Roach was extradited and was handed over to [[Singapore Police Force]]'s custody on 16 February 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/stanchart-robber-david-roach-extradited-singapore-uk-12545390|title=StanChart robbery: Suspect David Roach extradited to Singapore from UK|website=CNA|language=en|access-date=17 March 2020|date=17 March 2020}}</ref> He was charged the next day with the robbery, as well as unlawfully removing the money out of Singapore.<ref>{{Cite web|last1=Lam|first1=Lydia|url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/stanchart-robbery-david-roach-charged-singapore-offences-12548178|title=StanChart robbery: David Roach charged in Singapore almost 4 years after alleged offences|website=CNA|language=en|access-date=17 March 2020|date=17 March 2020}}</ref>\n*9 July 2016: 64-year-old Toh Sia Guan allegedly caused the death of 52-year-old coffee shop helper Goh Eng Thiam. Goh was found at Geylang Lorong 23 lying motionless on the floor.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/geylang-lor-23-murder-64-year-old-suspect-taken-to-crime-scenes|title=Geylang Lorong 23 murder: 64-year-old suspect taken to crime scenes|last=hermesauto|date=2016-07-27|website=The Straits Times|language=en|access-date=2019-04-05|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161107084706/http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/geylang-lor-23-murder-64-year-old-suspect-taken-to-crime-scenes|archive-date=7 November 2016|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n*11 July 2016: 42-year-old Chua Meng Guan was stabbed repeatedly to death outside a pub at Jalan Besar by 50-year-old Oh Beng Yam. Oh then fled to Johor after the stabbing. As of 2018, Oh remained at large with his last known location being in Thailand.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/2016-stabbing-death-suspect-still-at-large-2-years-after-fleeing-singapore|title=2016 stabbing death suspect still at large 2 years after fleeing Singapore|last=hermesauto|date=2018-03-22|website=The Straits Times|language=en|access-date=2019-04-05}}</ref>\n*12 July 2016: Leslie Khoo Kwee Hock was charged for murdering his 31-year-old girlfriend, Cui Yajie, an engineer from Tianjin. He burnt her body for a few days, and only a few pieces of charred fabric and a brassiere hook remained.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/news/asia/southeast-asia/article/3001553/singaporean-man-leslie-khoo-kwee-hock-denies|title=Strangled, dumped and burned: Chinese woman\u2019s death in Singapore|date=2019-03-13|website=South China Morning Post|language=en|access-date=2019-03-14|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190313112925/https://www.scmp.com/news/asia/southeast-asia/article/3001553/singaporean-man-leslie-khoo-kwee-hock-denies|archive-date=2019-03-13|url-status=live}}</ref> He was found guilty of murder<ref>{{Cite web|last1=Lam|first1=Lydia|url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/gardens-by-the-bay-murder-trial-leslie-khoo-cui-yajie-guilty-11729532|title=Gardens by the Bay murder: Man found guilty of killing China mistress, burning her body|date=18 July 2019|publisher=CNA|access-date=20 August 2019}}</ref> and sentenced to life in jail on 19 August 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|last1=Lam|first1=Lydia|url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/gardens-by-the-bay-murder-leslie-khoo-sentenced-jail-cui-yajie-11819850|title=Gardens by the Bay murder: Man gets life imprisonment for killing mistress, burning her body|date=19 August 2019|publisher=CNA|access-date=20 August 2019}}</ref>\n*13 July 2016: 50-year-old Thennarasu Karupiah assaulted 55-year-old Arokiasamy Paul Rajoo at Taj Mahal Bollywood Music Lounge at Boat Quay. Arokiasamy died 3 days later due to the injuries sustained. In 2018, Thennarasu pleaded guilty to culpable homicide not amounting to murder and was sentenced to 15 years and five months jail.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/ex-gang-member-imprisoned-for-deadly-assault|title=Ex-gang member imprisoned for deadly assault|last=hermes|date=2018-10-02|website=The Straits Times|language=en|access-date=2019-04-05|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181002123740/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/ex-gang-member-imprisoned-for-deadly-assault|archive-date=2 October 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n*25/26 July 2016: 58 year-old Prema S Naraynasamy and her daughter 36-year-old Gaiyathiri Murugaiyan allegedly killed 24-year-old Myanmar domestic worker Piang Ngaih Don at Block 145 Bishan Street 11 sometime between Jul 25 and 26. They were charged with murder.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/two-women-charged-with-murder-at-bishan-7919676|title=Two women charged with murder at Bishan|website=CNA|language=en|access-date=2019-04-05|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170924144651/http://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/two-women-charged-with-murder-at-bishan-7919676|archive-date=24 September 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n*11 October 2016: 41-year-old Lim Ying Siang set fire to two styrofoam boxes at Block 493 market in Jurong West in the wee hours. The fire raged and burned the entire market. It also caused damages to two coffee shops nearby. 56 stall owners at Block 493 market lost their stalls and assets, with the overall loses from all parties amounting to more than S$6 million. Lim was arrested on 13 October 2016<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/police-arrest-suspect-in-jurong-west-market-fire|title=Police arrest suspect in Jurong West market fire|last=Seow|first=Bei Yi|date=15 October 2016|website=The Straits Times|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180622061658/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/police-arrest-suspect-in-jurong-west-market-fire|archive-date=22 June 2018|access-date=19 November 2019}}</ref> and on 20 March 2018, he was sentenced to 11.5 years jail and 3 strokes of cane for  committing mischief by fire and drug consumption.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/man-gets-1112-years-jail-for-jurong-west-market-fire-that-led-to-6-million-in|title=Man gets 11\u00bd years' jail for Jurong West market fire that led to more than $6 million in damage and losses|last=Alkhatib|first=Shaffiq Idris|date=20 March 2018|website=The Straits Times|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180322195016/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/man-gets-1112-years-jail-for-jurong-west-market-fire-that-led-to-6-million-in|archive-date=22 March 2018|access-date=19 November 2019}}</ref> A temporary market was set up for displaced stallholders,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/2-storey-complex-to-replace-fire-ravaged-jurong-west-market-7528352|title=2-storey complex to replace fire-ravaged Jurong West market|last=Chan|first=Luo Er|date=1 January 2017|website=CNA|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191119101848/https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/2-storey-complex-to-replace-fire-ravaged-jurong-west-market-7528352|archive-date=19 November 2019|access-date=19 November 2019}}</ref> with the new market sitting on the affected site which opened in December 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/jurong-central-plaza-opens-replaces-market-destroyed-in-2016-11077938|title=Jurong Central Plaza opens, replaces market destroyed in 2016 fire|last=Goh|first=Nabila|date=1 January 2019|website=CNA|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190102114250/https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/jurong-central-plaza-opens-replaces-market-destroyed-in-2016-11077938|archive-date=2 January 2019|access-date=19 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n===2017===\n* 20 January 2017: 41-year-old Teo Ghim Heng got into an argument with his wife before strangling and burning both his pregnant wife, 39-year-old Choong Pei Shan, and their four-year-old daughter Teo Zi Ning at their flat in Woodlands.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/woodlands-double-deaths-man-charged-with-murder-of-wife-appears-in-court-for|title=Woodlands double deaths: Man charged with murder of wife appears in court for first time|last=Shaffiq Idris Alkhatib|date=2017-02-06|website=The Straits Times|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190403100141/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/woodlands-double-deaths-man-charged-with-murder-of-wife-appears-in-court-for|archive-date=3 April 2019|url-status=live|access-date=2019-04-03|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Their charred bodies were found 8 days later, on the first day of Chinese New Year. Teo was charged with the murder of his wife and daughter. The third charge for the murder of his unborn child is stood down for now.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/woodlands-murder-teo-ghim-heng-strangled-pregnant-wife-daughter-11682212|title=Woodlands double deaths: Man strangled pregnant wife with towel before killing 4-year-old daughter|last=Lam|first=Lydia|date=2019-07-02|website=CNA|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190702070416/https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/woodlands-murder-teo-ghim-heng-strangled-pregnant-wife-daughter-11682212|archive-date=2019-07-02|access-date=2019-10-23}}</ref>\n*26 April 2017: 39-year-old Bangladeshi construction worker, Das Ratan Chandra, was arrested for having sex with a 12-year-old girl in a forested area in Lower Peirce Reservoir Park. On 12 April 2019, Chandra was found guilty of 3 counts of statutory rape and was sentenced to 22-year jail and 18 strokes of cane.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/construction-worker-raped-12-year-old-girl-lower-peirce-11437364|title=Construction worker gets jail, caning for raping 12-year-old girl thrice at reservoir|website=CNA|language=en|access-date=2019-04-12}}</ref>\n*10 May 2017: 48-year-old cleaner Paramjit Singh Minder Singh raped a 61-year-old factory operator at knifepoint in a female toilet at her workplace. He was charged with one count of aggravated rape and two counts of aggravated sexual assault by penetration and sentenced to 18-year jail with 24 strokes of cane.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/cleaner-who-raped-factory-worker-62-gets-18-years-jail-and-24-strokes-of-the|title=Cleaner who raped factory worker, 62, gets 18 years' jail and 24 strokes of the cane|last=hermesauto|date=2018-11-16|website=The Straits Times|language=en|access-date=2019-04-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190216101526/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/cleaner-who-raped-factory-worker-62-gets-18-years-jail-and-24-strokes-of-the|archive-date=16 February 2019|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n*21 June 2017: 41-year-old Indonesian maid Khasanah murdered 79-year-old Chia Ngim Fong and his wife, 78-year-old Madam Chin Sek Fah at their flat in Bedok Reservoir.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.todayonline.com/singapore/double-murder-bedok-reservoir-road|title=Couple in late 70s found murdered in Bedok Reservoir home|website=TODAYonline|access-date=2019-04-03|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190403100132/https://www.todayonline.com/singapore/double-murder-bedok-reservoir-road|archive-date=3 April 2019|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> She fled Singapore for [[Batam]] before she was arrested in Indonesia.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/asia/se-asia/bedok-double-murder-suspect-shares-how-she-fled-singapore|title=Bedok double murder: Indonesian suspect shared how she fled Singapore|last=hermesauto|date=2017-07-01|website=The Straits Times|language=en|access-date=2019-04-03|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190403102244/https://www.straitstimes.com/asia/se-asia/bedok-double-murder-suspect-shares-how-she-fled-singapore|archive-date=3 April 2019|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> She was not extradited on the basis of the principle of personaliteit, which states that any citizen arrested in Indonesia for crimes overseas would be processed with its own legal system. Singapore authorities are working with Indonesia on this case.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/bedok-double-murder-maid-arrested-in-indonesia-will-not-be-sent-8987968|title=Bedok double murder: Maid arrested in Indonesia will not be sent to Singapore|website=CNA|language=en|access-date=2019-04-03|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190403103136/https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/bedok-double-murder-maid-arrested-in-indonesia-will-not-be-sent-8987968|archive-date=3 April 2019|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n* 10 July 2017: 69-year-old Tan Nam Seng stabbed his son-in-law 38-year-old Spencer Tuppani in Telok Ayer St. Tuppani ran and collapsed 70m away, outside an eatery on Boon Tat St. Tan also prevented others from rendering help to Tuppani<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/boon-tat-street-stabbing-69-year-old-man-charged-with-murder-of-9022130|title=Boon Tat Street stabbing: 69-year-old man charged with murder of son-in-law|website=CNA|language=en|access-date=2019-04-03|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190403103134/https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/boon-tat-street-stabbing-69-year-old-man-charged-with-murder-of-9022130|archive-date=3 April 2019|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> which caused Tuppani to die in hospital shortly after. Tan was charged with murder on 12 July and was remanded for three weeks for psychiatric evaluation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/boon-tat-street-murder-accused-remanded-for-three-more-weeks-for-psychiatric|title=Boon Tat Street murder accused remanded for three more weeks for psychiatric assessment|last=hermesauto|date=2017-08-03|website=The Straits Times|language=en|access-date=2019-04-03|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190403100128/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/boon-tat-street-murder-accused-remanded-for-three-more-weeks-for-psychiatric|archive-date=3 April 2019|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n*18 November 2017: A 51-year-old security guard raped his niece's 24-year-old Indonesian maid in his niece's flat. He was sentenced to 10.5 years of jail, with 6 months of it in lieu of caning as he is aged above 50. Names are withheld to protect the identity of the victim.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/man-jailed-1012-years-for-raping-assaulting-maid|title=Man jailed 10\u00bd years for raping, assaulting maid|last=hermes|date=2019-03-19|website=The Straits Times|language=en|access-date=2019-04-06}}</ref>\n*30 December 2017: 29-year-old cleaner Jayselan N Chandrasegar stabbed and slashed his 26-year-old pregnant wife Mayuri Krishnakuma along Lorong 16 Geylang.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/man-29-charged-after-stabbing-wife-in-geylang|title=Man, 29, charged after stabbing wife in Geylang|last=hermesauto|date=2018-01-01|website=The Straits Times|language=en|access-date=2019-04-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180207060215/http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/man-29-charged-after-stabbing-wife-in-geylang|archive-date=7 February 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The unborn baby was not hurt in the attack. On 11 December 2018, Jayselan was convicted of causing grievous hurt to Mayuri with a weapon, and for failing to provide his urine sample after he was caught for suspected drug-related offences. He was sentenced to 7-year jail and 6 strokes of cane.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/cleaner-gets-jail-cane-for-stabbing-wife|title=Cleaner gets jail, cane for stabbing wife|last=hermes|date=2018-12-12|website=The Straits Times|language=en|access-date=2019-04-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181212150827/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/cleaner-gets-jail-cane-for-stabbing-wife|archive-date=12 December 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===2018===\n* 19 July 2018: The ITE examinations director, 56-year-old Low Hwee Geok, was found dead at the [[ITE College Central]] campus carpark after she was allegedly stabbed by her ex-husband.<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Tay |first1=Tiffany Fumiko |last2=Tan |first2=Tam Mei |last3=Ng |first3=Keng Gene |last4=Koh |first4=Fabian |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/woman-found-dead-man-injured-in-ite-college-central-campus-carpark |title=ITE College Central murder: 56-year-old director of exams division allegedly stabbed by ex-husband |website=The Straits Times |access-date=28 November 2019 |date=19 July 2018}}</ref> The ex-husband, 66-year-old Seet Cher Hng, was arrested on 20 July 2018<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Tan |first1=Tam Mei |last2=Low |first2=De Wei |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/ite-college-central-murder-victim-56-was-a-school-director-whom-friends-said-was-well |title=ITE College Central murder: Police arrest 66-year-old man who allegedly stabbed ex-wife |website=The Straits Times |access-date=28 November 2019 |date=20 July 2018}}</ref> and charged with murder the following day.<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Tan |first1=Tam Mei |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/murder-on-ite-campus-suspect-charged-in-hospital |title=Murder on ITE campus: Suspect charged in hospital |website=The Straits Times |access-date=28 November 2019 |date=21 July 2018}}</ref>\n* 29 July 2018: 58-year-old Balachandran Kothandapani, 34-year-old Farizal Rahmat, and 44-year-old Murugan Joseph assaulted 32-year-old cook Revi Jose Vibin at a [[Roti prata|prata]] shop in Clementi. In an argument for not getting free prata, Balachandran slashed Revi. Murugan was sentenced to 13-month jail, in lieu of 6 strokes of cane as he was medically unfit. Farizal was sentenced to 8 months jail and 6 strokes of cane, in addition to a 400-day jail for committing the offence on remission order. Balachandran Kothandapani was sentenced to one-year jail with 3 months in lieu of 6 strokes of cane as he was above 50 and cannot be caned.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/man-admits-to-being-part-of-trio-who-attacked-cook-with-knife-after-not|title=Man admits to being part of trio who attacked cook with knife after not getting free prata|last=hermesauto|date=2019-03-28|website=The Straits Times|language=en|access-date=2019-04-06|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190329124136/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/man-admits-to-being-part-of-trio-who-attacked-cook-with-knife-after-not|archive-date=29 March 2019|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Elangovan |first1=Navene |title=Jail, caning for second man who took part in attack on prata stall\u2019s cook |url=https://www.todayonline.com/singapore/jail-caning-second-man-who-took-part-attack-prata-stalls-cook |accessdate=14 July 2019 |publisher=Todayonline |date=29 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Tang |first1=Louisa |title=No free prata: Jail for third man involved in attack on Indian food stall's cook |url=https://www.todayonline.com/singapore/jail-third-man-involved-attack-prata-stall-cook |accessdate=14 July 2019 |publisher=Todayonline |date=4 April 2019}}</ref>\n*19 November 2018: 64-year-old father Tan Tian Chye allegedly killed his 35-year-old daughter Desiree Tan Jiaping in his flat at Block 171 Bedok South Road. He was charged with murder and was undergoing psychiatric evaluation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/man-charged-with-daughters-murder|title=Man charged with daughter's murder|last=hermes|date=2018-11-21|website=The Straits Times|language=en|access-date=2019-04-05}}</ref>\n*30 December 2018: A 34-year-old Indonesian female work permit holder was found dead at the Golden Dragon Hotel in Geylang. A 29-year-old Bangladeshi work permit holder was subsequently arrested and would be charged with murder.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/indonesian-woman-found-dead-at-geylang-hotel-suspect-arrested|title=Indonesian woman found dead at Geylang hotel, suspect arrested|last=hermesauto|date=2018-12-31|website=The Straits Times|language=en|access-date=2019-04-04|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190216123101/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/indonesian-woman-found-dead-at-geylang-hotel-suspect-arrested|archive-date=16 February 2019|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The now 30-year-old Bangladeshi, Ahmed Salim, was charged with murder on 2 January 2019.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Alkhatib |first1=Shaffiq |title=Man charged with murder after body found in Geylang hotel |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/man-charged-with-murder-after-body-found-in-geylang-hotel |accessdate=14 July 2019 |publisher=The Straits Times |date=2 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n===2019===\n* 17 January 2019: 34-year-old M. Krishan allegedly murdered 40-year-old Mallika Begum Rahamansa Abdul Rahman at a flat at Block 693D Woodlands Avenue 6, with the former arrested on the same day.<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Ang |first1=Jolene |last2=Goh |first2=Timothy |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/man-arrested-for-alleged-murder-after-woman-found-dead-in-woodlands |title=Man arrested for alleged murder after woman found dead in Woodlands |website=The Straits Times |access-date=4 January 2020 |date=17 January 2019}}</ref> Krishan was subsequently charged on 18 January.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/man-34-charged-over-woodlands-murder|title=Man, 34, charged with murder of woman in Woodlands flat|last=Alkhatib|first=Shaffiq|date=2019-01-18|website=The Straits Times|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190206162117/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/man-34-charged-over-woodlands-murder|archive-date=6 February 2019|access-date=2019-04-04|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n*11 March 2019: A 23-year-old Malaysian work permit holder Yee Jing Man was arrested for allegedly murdering 30-year-old director Lin Xinjie, who was found dead at the International Furniture Centre at 62 [[Sungei Kadut]] Loop, together with 29-year-old director Li Mingqiao who was another injured victim.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/man-allegedly-murdered-at-sungei-kadut-loop-one-other-injured-suspect-to-be-charged|title=Man allegedly murdered in Sungei Kadut Loop, one other injured; suspect to be charged|last=Alkhatib|first=Shaffiq|date=2019-03-11|website=The Straits Times|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190313020023/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/man-allegedly-murdered-at-sungei-kadut-loop-one-other-injured-suspect-to-be-charged|archive-date=13 March 2019|access-date=2019-04-04|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Yee was fired for the second time earlier that day for poor work attitude, which led him to attack Lin and Li.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/suspect-allegedly-attacked-boss-after-being-fired-again|title=Suspect allegedly attacked boss after being fired again|last=Ng|first=Charmaine|date=2019-03-13|website=The Straits Times|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190406233551/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/suspect-allegedly-attacked-boss-after-being-fired-again|archive-date=2019-04-06|access-date=2019-04-06}}</ref> Yee was charged with murder two days later.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/man-charged-over-sungei-kadut-murder|title=Man charged over Sungei Kadut murder|last=Alkhatib|first=Shaffiq|date=2019-03-14|website=The Straits Times|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190406233245/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/man-charged-over-sungei-kadut-murder|archive-date=2019-04-06|access-date=2019-04-06}}</ref>\n*May 2019: Lawyer Jeffrey Ong Su Aun was the managing partner of law firm JLC Advisors. Ong could not be contacted after S$33.4 million from the escrow account of engineering firm Allied Technologies, which was parked in his law firm, may have been paid out by Ong without the prior knowledge of the engineering firm. He fled Singapore for Malaysia on 13 May before he went uncontactable on 16 May. He was arrested in Kuala Lumpur by the [[Royal Malaysian Police]] on 29 May before he was extradited back to Singapore the next day. Ong has been charged with cheating offences involving tricking CCJ Investments to disburse S$6 million, and forgery offences where he forged bank statements in order to conceal discrepancies.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/law-firm-partner-jeffrey-ong-believed-to-have-ordered-pay-out-of-33-million-belonging-to|title=Lawyer goes missing after ordering payout of $33 million held in escrow account|last=K.C.|first=Vijayan|date=2019-05-23|website=The Straits Times|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191016174015/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/law-firm-partner-jeffrey-ong-believed-to-have-ordered-pay-out-of-33-million-belonging-to|archive-date=2019-10-16|access-date=2019-11-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/missing-lawyer-jeffrey-ong-arrested-and-charged-with-cheating|title=Missing lawyer Jeffrey Ong arrested and charged with cheating|last=Alkhatib|first=Shaffiq|date=2019-06-07|website=The Straits Times|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190608181226/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/missing-lawyer-jeffrey-ong-arrested-and-charged-with-cheating|archive-date=2019-06-08|access-date=2019-10-16}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/lawyer-jeffrey-ong-faces-eight-new-cheating-charges|title=Lawyer Jeffrey Ong, linked to missing $33m, faces 8 new forgery charges|last=Ng|first=Charmaine|date=2019-06-13|website=The Straits Times|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190615044718/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/lawyer-jeffrey-ong-faces-eight-new-cheating-charges|archive-date=2019-06-15|access-date=2019-10-16}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/lawyer-allegedly-linked-to-missing-33-million-faces-4-new-charges|title=Lawyer Jeffrey Ong, allegedly linked to missing $33 million, faces 4 new charges|last=Alkhatib|first=Shaffiq|date=2019-10-14|website=The Straits Times|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191016174049/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/lawyer-allegedly-linked-to-missing-33-million-faces-4-new-charges|archive-date=2019-10-16|access-date=2019-10-16}}</ref>\n*2 July 2019: Known as the Orchard Towers murder, a 31-year-old man, Satheesh Noel Gobidass, was assaulted and murdered at [[Orchard Towers]] by a large group. Eight suspects were arrested, with seven initially charged for murder on 4 July 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/seven-charged-for-murder-of-man-at-orchard-towers|title=Orchard Towers fight: Six men, one woman charged with murder|last=Wong|first=Cara|date=2019-07-04|website=The Straits Times|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190714132352/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/seven-charged-for-murder-of-man-at-orchard-towers|archive-date=2019-07-14|access-date=2019-11-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.todayonline.com/singapore/8-murder-suspects-arrested-after-man-at-orchard-towers-dies-from-injuries|title=8 murder suspects arrested after man at Orchard Towers dies from injuries|last=ELANGOVAN|first=NAVENE|date=2019-07-02|website=TODAYonline|access-date=2019-11-01}}</ref> On 11 July 2019, three suspects were acquitted of murder, and charged with consorting with a person carrying an offensive weapon in a public place.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/murder-charges-against-3-dropped-in-orchard-towers-case|title=Murder charges against 3 dropped in Orchard Towers case|last=Alkhatib|first=Shaffiq|date=2019-07-12|website=The Straits Times|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190712162755/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/murder-charges-against-3-dropped-in-orchard-towers-case|archive-date=2019-07-12|access-date=2019-11-01}}</ref>\n*8 October 2019: Muhammad Ikram Abdul Aziz, 24 was arrested in a joint operation by the [[Central Narcotics Bureau]] and the [[Singapore Police Force|police]] at the void deck below his housing unit at Block 731 Jurong West Street 72 before being escorted to his home, where a loaded pistol was discovered.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/two-men-arrested-for-possession-of-loaded-pistol|title=Two men arrested for possession of loaded pistol|last1=Wong|first1=Cara|date=9 October 2019|website=The Straits Times|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191011100918/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/two-men-arrested-for-possession-of-loaded-pistol|archive-date=2019-10-11|access-date=9 October 2019}}</ref> The following day, a second man, Amirul Asyraff Muhammad Junus, 25 was arrested for consorting with Ikram who was in possession of firearm. No drugs were found on the two of them. Both of them were charged for their respective offences.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/two-men-charged-over-offences-involving-pistol|title=Two charged over pistol found in Jurong West flat; first such case in a decade|last1=Alkhatib|first1=Shaffiq|date=10 October 2019|website=The Straits Times|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191012100736/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/two-men-charged-over-offences-involving-pistol|archive-date=2019-10-12|access-date=10 October 2019}}</ref>\n*27 October 2019: Two murder cases happened on the same day.\n**54-year-old Chinese national Wang Shuzhen allegedly murdered her husband, 63-year-old former policeman Teh Hock Pine at their flat at Block 633 [[Ang Mo Kio]] Avenue 6 in the early hours.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/woman-charged-with-murder-of-man-in-ang-mo-kio-flat|title=Woman accused of killing ex-policeman said to be her husband in Ang Mo Kio flat|last1=Tan|first1=Tam Mei|date=28 October 2019|website=The Straits Times|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191030235739/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/woman-charged-with-murder-of-man-in-ang-mo-kio-flat|archive-date=30 October 2019|access-date=31 October 2019}}</ref> Wang was arrested and charged the next day for murder.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/63-year-old-man-found-dead-in-ang-mo-kio-flat-53-year-old-woman-arrested-for|title=22-year-old man arrested over double murder of relatives in Commonwealth Avenue block|last1=Yong|first1=Clement|date=27 October 2019|website=The Straits Times|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191029214039/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/63-year-old-man-found-dead-in-ang-mo-kio-flat-53-year-old-woman-arrested-for|archive-date=29 October 2019|access-date=31 October 2019}}</ref>\n**22-year-old Gabriel Lien Goh allegedly murdered both his mother, 56-year-old former teacher Lee Soh Mui and his 90-year-old grandmother See Keng Keng. Goh was arguing with his mother in a housing unit at Block 7A [[Commonwealth, Singapore|Commonwealth]] Avenue when he stabbed her to death. Goh's grandmother ran out to their neighbour's unit for help, before Goh punched the neighbour's relatives who let his grandmother in. Goh proceeded to assault his grandmother to death and went down to the first floor, where he acted aggressively towards members of the public before he was subdued and arrested.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/double-murders-at-commonwealth-avenue-22-year-old-arrested|title=22-year-old man arrested over double murder of relatives in Commonwealth Avenue block|last1=Wong|first1=Cara|last2=Chong|first2=Clara|date=27 October 2019|website=The Straits Times|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191101162149/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/double-murders-at-commonwealth-avenue-22-year-old-arrested|archive-date=1 November 2019|access-date=31 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mothership.sg/2019/10/commonwealth-avenue-murder-son/|title=Man allegedly murders mom & grandma in Commonwealth, details as provided by S\u2019pore Chinese newspapers|last=Zheng|first=Zhangxin|date=2019-10-28|website=Mothership.sg|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191030193944/https://mothership.sg/2019/10/commonwealth-avenue-murder-son/|archive-date=2019-10-30|access-date=2019-10-30}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mothership.sg/2019/10/gabriel-lien-goh-beat-grandmother-neighbour/|title=Commonwealth double deaths: Man allegedly beat grandma to death in neighbour\u2019s house|last=Lee|first=Joshua|date=2019-10-30|website=Mothership.sg|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191030194255/https://mothership.sg/2019/10/gabriel-lien-goh-beat-grandmother-neighbour/|archive-date=2019-10-30|access-date=2019-10-30}}</ref> Goh was charged for the alleged murder of both his mother and grandmother on 28 October and 18 November respectively.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/commonwealth-double-deaths-man-charged-with-murder-of-woman-believed-to-be|title=Commonwealth double deaths: Man charged with murder of woman believed to be his mother|last=Tan|first=Tam Mei|date=2019-10-28|website=The Straits Times|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191030194539/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/commonwealth-double-deaths-man-charged-with-murder-of-woman-believed-to-be|archive-date=2019-10-30|access-date=2019-10-30}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/commonwealth-double-deaths-man-faces-second-murder-charge-over-grandmothers|title=Commonwealth double deaths: Man accused of killing his mother charged with murdering grandmother|last=Ng|first=Charmaine|date=18 November 2019|website=The Straits Times|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191118130910/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/commonwealth-double-deaths-man-faces-second-murder-charge-over-grandmothers|archive-date=18 November 2019|access-date=18 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==2020s==\n=== 2020 ===\n*3 January 2020: A former podiatrist from Melbourne, Paul Leslie Quirk, 48, murdered his wife, Christina Khoo Gek Hwa, 43, in their home at 125 Compassvale Bow.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/murder-esparina-residences-condominium-buangkok-paul-quirk-12232894|title=Man charged with murdering his wife at Buangkok condominium|website=CNA|language=en|access-date=2020-02-25}}</ref> Screams were heard by neighbours and Quirk was seen  armed with a big stick, hurling his dog off the balcony of his third-floor apartment. Khoo was found unresponsive, and was pronounced dead on the spot. The dog was found bloodied on the ground floor. Quirk was charged with murder, and was being remanded at Changi Prison for psychiatric observation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theaustralian.com.au/world/australian-paul-quirk-facing-death-penalty-over-wifes-murder-in-singapore/news-story/93c6e015d879da0cca63a1b8a2a14486|title=Australian Paul Quirk facing death penalty over wife\u2019s murder in Singapore|last=|first=|date=25 January 2020|website=www.theaustralian.com.au|url-access=subscription|access-date=2020-02-25}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n[[Category:Crime in Singapore| ]]\n[[Category:Singapore crime-related lists|Major crimes]]\n[[Category:Lists of events in Singapore|Major crimes]]\n", "name_user": "NelsonLee20042020", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200e1993", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_major_crimes_in_Singapore"}
{"title_page": "Alaska Public Media", "text_new": "[[File:Alaska Public Media station.jpg|thumb|Alaska Public Media's station in Anchorage, Alaska at 3877 University Drive.]]\n'''Alaska Public Media''' is a [[non-profit organization]] with member [[television station|television]] and [[radio station]]s that are part of [[PBS]], [[NPR]] and other [[public broadcasting]] networks.  Formerly known as '''Alaska Public Telecommunications, Inc.,''' Alaska Public Media relies upon several funding sources, including member donations, state and federal dollars, and grants from private foundations, the [[Corporation for Public Broadcasting]] (CPB), and elsewhere.<ref>https://www.alaskapublic.org/about/\n</ref>\n\nAlaska Public Media operates [[KAKM]], a [[television]] station affiliated with the PBS, along with [[public radio]] station [[KSKA]] (FM 91.1).  Alaska Public Media also operates the '''Alaska Public Radio Network''' ('''APRN'''), a network of more than 20 radio stations in Alaska that share news and other audio content statewide; as well as Alaska's omnibus television network, the '''[[Alaska Rural Communications Service]]''', which is a joint venture of Alaska Public Media and Alaska's public broadcasters.\n\nThe stations claim 54,000 TV viewers nightly and 37,000 radio listeners weekly in the Southcentral [[Alaska]] region. Alaska Public Television is viewed statewide except Fairbanks, which is viewed on [[KUAC-TV]] as a locally focused PBS Station.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://www.alaskapublic.org}}\n\n\n[[Category:Alaska media]]\n[[Category:Alaska Public Radio Network| ]]\n[[Category:American radio networks]]\n[[Category:Non-profit organizations based in Alaska]]\n\n{{American broadcast radio}}\n{{Public_broadcasting_in_the_United_States}}\n\n\n{{Alaska-radio-station-stub}}\n{{Alaska-tv-station-stub}}\n{{AnchorageAK-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Unreferenced|date=August 2019}}\n[[File:Alaska Public Media station.jpg|thumb|Alaska Public Media's station in Anchorage, Alaska at 3877 University Drive.]]\n'''Alaska Public Media''' is a [[non-profit organization]] with member [[television station|television]] and [[radio station]]s that are part of [[PBS]], [[NPR]] and other [[public broadcasting]] networks.  Formerly known as '''Alaska Public Telecommunications, Inc.,''' Alaska Public Media relies upon several funding sources, including member donations, state and federal dollars, and grants from private foundations, the [[Corporation for Public Broadcasting]] (CPB), and elsewhere.\n\nAlaska Public Media operates [[KAKM]], a [[television]] station affiliated with the PBS, along with [[public radio]] station [[KSKA]] (FM 91.1).  Alaska Public Media also operates the '''Alaska Public Radio Network''' ('''APRN'''), a network of more than 20 radio stations in Alaska that share news and other audio content statewide; as well as Alaska's omnibus television network, the '''[[Alaska Rural Communications Service]]''', which is a joint venture of Alaska Public Media and Alaska's public broadcasters.\n\nThe stations claim 54,000 TV viewers nightly and 37,000 radio listeners weekly in the Southcentral [[Alaska]] region. Alaska Public Television is viewed statewide except Fairbanks, which is viewed on [[KUAC-TV]] as a locally focused PBS Station.\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://www.alaskapublic.org}}\n\n\n[[Category:Alaska media]]\n[[Category:Alaska Public Radio Network| ]]\n[[Category:American radio networks]]\n[[Category:Non-profit organizations based in Alaska]]\n\n{{American broadcast radio}}\n{{Public_broadcasting_in_the_United_States}}\n\n\n{{Alaska-radio-station-stub}}\n{{Alaska-tv-station-stub}}\n{{AnchorageAK-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ben76266", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alaska_Public_Media"}
